<FIRST>r a AM-People-Fodor 1stLd-Writethru a0759 07-31 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Fodor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0759,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acclaimed Violinist Released After Motel Break-In</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, ` Fodor, 39, ..., and 7th graf, `Fodor, a ..
., to CLARIFY that Fodor shared silver medal with Soviet violinists.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Famed violinist Eugene Fodor Jr., arrested last
week on drug possession and breaking and entering charges, was
released on his own recognizance Monday.
   Fodor, 39, is an internationally acclaimed musician who has won
top honors in both the Tchaikovsky and Paganini violin
competitions. He also has performed at the White House.
   Maids at the Vineyard Harbor Hotel on Martha's Vineyard
discovered Fodor in an unoccupied motel room Thursday. He was later
arraigned on charges of breaking and entering with intent to commit
a felony; trafficking in cocaine and possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute; possession of a hypodermic needle; possession
of heroin; and possession of a dangerous weapon _ a dagger.
   Fodor was held on $50,000 cash bail at the Dukes County Jail
over the weekend after a judge refused to accept his 300-year-old
violin as bail, officials said.
   On Monday, Edgartown Superior Judge Joseph S. Mitchell released
Fodor on his own recognizance. A pre-trial conference was scheduled
for Sept. 7.
   Some family members blamed the incident on Fodor's recent drug
problems. Colleagues said Fodor had not performed as frequently in
recent years and never reached the top ranks of virtuosos.
   Fodor, a Denver native, made his debut with the Denver Symphony.
In 1974, he shared a silver medal with two Soviet violinists in the
Tchaikovsky violin competition in Moscow. He later won the Paganini
International Violin Competition in Genoa, Italy, and most recently
completed a concert tour in South America.
   Relatives said Fodor was on vacation when he was arrested.
</TEXT>
