<FIRST>u w AM-Higgins-Reaction 2ndLd-Writethru a0728 07-31 0899</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Higgins-Reaction, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0728,910</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Higgins</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 9-12 bgng: ``Outside the,'' with noncongressional
reaction from Arab-Americans, B'Nai B'rith and Journalists Committee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted unanimously on Monday to
condemn the apparent execution of kidnapped Marine Lt. Col. William
Higgins as an ``outrageous act of terrorism'' and urged President
Bush to consider retaliation if possible.
   The vote on the amendment, sponsored by Senate Majority leader
George Mitchell of Maine and Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of
Kansas was 99-0. Sen. Spark Matsunaga, D-Hawaii, is ill and did not
vote.
   ``The United States must take the lead in bringing to an end
what has become an international scourge,'' Mitchell said
immediately before the Senate voted.
   ``All nations must act,'' he said. ``If an end is to be put to
terrorism those nations must consult, coordinate and act.''
   ``Faint-hearted efforts and half steps only embolden
terrorists,'' Mitchell said. ``The United States must not shrink
from pursuing every effort to ensure the American people are free
from what is now the possible danger of attack when overseas.''
   Dole, who earlier had crticized Israel for not informing the
United States before seizing suspected terrorists, a step that
allegedly led to Higgins' reported killing, made clear his mind had
not been changed.
   He said that beyond sending a message to terrorist groups and to
nations like Iran _ suspected of being a driving force behind them
_ ``we also want to send a message to our friends.''
   The message: ``This is a very serious matter and we believe that
in any future efforts there should be some notification, some
coordination, and maybe more responsibility assumed by our
friends.''
   Outside the Capitol, the Anti-Defamation League of B'Nai B'rith
said it was shocked by Dole's remarks because they ``failed to
place the blame for Col. Higgins' murder where it truly belongs,
with Iran and the Hezbollah terrorists.''
   ``We must support each other, directing our efforts against
those responsible for the evil of terrorism,'' said a statement
from Burron S. Levinon, chairman, and Abraham H. Foxman, national
director.
   The National Association of Arab-Americans said it condemned
those responsble for Col. Higgins' execution, which it called
``reprehensible,'' but said it supported Dole's remarks and
believed Israeli leaders knew their kidnapping of a Hezbollah
leader would ``set off a cuycle of violence and retribution.''
   The Journalists' Committee to Free Terry Anderson, The
Associated Press correspondent who is the longest-held hostage,
said in a message to Bush and members of Congress it was ``gravely
concerned about U.S. reaction. As Terry's sister, Peggy Say, said
today, this is no time for revenge. Violence only begets violence.
We urge you to use restraint and explore all avenues of peaceful
discussions with Iran.''
   The Senate resolution condemned Higgins' reported death as
``barbaric, cowardly, and utterly imcompatible with the standards
of conduct upheld by civilized people.''
   ``The president should utilize all available resources of the
United States government ... to determine the responsibility of
those responsible ...,'' it said.
   ``The president should determine whether it would be possible to
isolate and bring to justice or retaliate against those responsible
in a manner that would reduce the risk to Americans from
terrorism,'' the non-binding resolution said.
   And it said the president should urgently consult Israel and
other governments ``concerning their policies and actions which
might have relevance to the interests of the United States or
increase the vulnerability of U.S. citizens to attacks by
terrorists''
   Other congressional reaction to the reported execution of an
American hostage ranged from calls for revenge to warnings that
such moves would only worsen conditions in the volatile Middle East.
   ``We can't blow Lebanon up simply to avenge the life of one
American,'' said Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla., chairman of the House
Foreign Affairs Committee.
   House Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., said: ``No cause or
political goal can be used to justify such a despicable, cowardly
act.''
   ``As for options, we're back to square one,'' said Sen. Richard
Lugar, R-Ind., a senior member of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee. ``It's a horrible mess.''
   Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Claiborne Pell, D-R.I.,
called the reported execution ``a dreadful, horrible, devastating
action. I know the president is as horrified as we are. This will
be discussed at the highest levels. And I am sure we will be
cooperating with the executive branch.''
   Rep. William Broomfield of Michigan, the senior Republican on
the House Foreign Affairs Committee, lamented that ``with every
passing year it seems that some areas of the Islamic world are
moving farther and farther away from the orbit of civilized
nations.''
   Others were more blunt. Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., said ``We need
revenge and we need justice, and I will support the president in
whatever means he might employ to bring them about.''
   Rep. Robert Lagomarsino, R-Calif., added: ``The president should
do everything he thinks is necessary to avenge this killing. And I
mean he should consider every possible retaliatory action.''
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., asked Bush in a letter to award
Higgins the Medal of Honor.
   ``This tribute is customarily issued to soldiers who prove valor
in military actions, or in peacetime, demonstrate unique acts of
bravery,'' McConnell told the Senate.
   ``I think Rich's record is clear,'' he said. ``His selfless
efforts to secure peace in a nation consumed by bloodshed and
battle should be recognized and honored.'' Higgins was born in
Danville, Ky.
</TEXT>
