<FIRST>r w PM-MIAWife     07-31 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MIA Wife,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Families Search for Clues on Soldiers Missing in Asia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sherrie L. Hassenger was working in her yard
in tiny Birkenfeld, Ore., when the telephone call came from
Randolph Air Force Base in Texas last June 8.
   The Air Force told her of a report from Laos that her husband,
Arden K. Hassenger, may have been seen. Hassenger, now 53, was lost
over Laos on Christmas Eve 1965 during an armed reconnaissance
flight.
   ``They just told me there was a possible sighting,'' she said
Friday at the annual convention of the National League of Families
of American Prisoners and Missing in Action in Southeast Asia.
   ``It's telling me that there's a possibility that he is alive,''
she said, fighting back tears. ``And I have a lot more hope. It's
information that I would rather have than some people that are
getting a box of bones, a tooth, or whatever, the remains. I'm
thankful for the information.''
   It was the first clue to her husband's whereabouts since he was
lost along with five other crew members. A follow-up letter June 12
said the report included information taken from dog tags.
   The dog tags carry military personnel's serial numbers,
religious affiliation and residence.
   As a result of the call and letter, Mrs. Hassenger decided to
attend her first convention in 12 years. She went for support in
her quest for information, to make contact with relatives of other
crew members, and to find renewed solidarity after years of
wondering in isolation.
   ``Well, they've always told me that they would take care of it,
the Air Force,'' she said. ``And I live so far away from everyone,
I just didn't have the tactics or the know-how. I didn't know that
I was supposed to keep calling, harassing, what I was supposed to
do to get information ... But now I have friends that are going to
help me.''
   Chief Master Sgt. Hassenger is one of 2,348 Americans still held
prisoner, missing or unaccounted for in Southeast Asia. The number
includes 42 civilians, two of whom are women, according to Pentagon
figures supplied by the league. Of those, 1,714 are believed to be
in Vietnam.
   As of July 3 this year, there have been 1,210 firsthand live
sighting reports in Indochina since 1975, the league says, again
using Pentagon figures. Of those reports, 1,078 have been resolved,
including 805 who have since left Indochina, and 273 were
fabrications.
   There are 70 so-called ``discrepancy cases,'' high-priority
cases in which Americans have been reportedly seen as prisoners.
Hassenger, according to a Defense Intelligence Agency message, was
reportedly ``unable to leave'' Laos.
   Since 1973, 235 sets of remains have returned, the bulk of those
in the last nine years.
   Congressmen and members of the Bush administration who addressed
the convention told the families the missing servicemen are a
front-burner issue, but that much depends on the vagaries of
politics in Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia.
   ``The fullest possible accounting remains a matter of highest
national priority,'' Bush told the group. Bush said he has asked
Secretary of State James A. Baker III to raise the issue this week
during an international conference on the future of Cambodia.
   Over the past year there has been progress in dealing with
Hanoi: a series of technical meetings and investigations, more
remains returned from Vietnam.
   But the frustration is growing among family members.
   ``I think they're dragging their feet and pretty soon they'll be
dead and then we don't have an issue, do we?'' said Lorene Walker,
61, of Rapid City, S.D. Her son, Bruce, has been missing for 17
years.
   Bruce Walker's father, Charles, 63, expressed impatience with
the administration and members of Congress for relying on the
Indochinese governments.
   ``As an alternative to directly confronting the Vietnamese, the
CIA must be good for something,'' he said. ``You go find out for
sure what exactly is happening in a country. We do it every place
else. I don't know why we've pulled everybody out of Vietnam.''
</TEXT>
