<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 0302EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PlaneParts     07-31 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Parts,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Crash Investigators To Examine Parts From Six Jets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators probing the crash of a DC-10
in Iowa have recalled metal disks from the tail engines of six
other DC-10s to check for possible flaws, a government spokesman
said.
   The recall was recommended after National Transportation Safety
Board investigators found the 3-foot-diameter disks, which hold the
fan blades of the General Electric Co. engines, may have been cut
from the same slab of metal used in the jet that crashed, said Ted
Lopatkiewicz, an NTSB spokesman.
   Investigators want to examine the quality of the metal used in
making the disks, he said Sunday.
   The agency's investigators believe the fan section of the engine
on United Airlines Flight 232 disintegrated in flight, possibly
causing the hydraulic-steering system failure that caused the July
19 crash in Sioux City, Iowa. The crash killed 111 people.
   The disk from Flight 232 hasn't been found.
   A spokesman for GE's Aircraft Engines division, Dwight Weber,
said it had not been determined that the parts being removed from
the six jetliners contained flaws.
   The recall ``is part of a data-gathering procedure in order to
see if they can tell anything about the missing disk,'' Weber said
by telephone from his home in Cincinnati. ``We're going to work
with the NTSB to look them over.''
   Neither Weber nor Lopatkiewicz would identify the airliners with
disks being recalled, but Lopatkiewicz said one was operated by a
foreign airline and the others were flown by U.S. carriers.
   The disks are believed to have come from a billet, or slab, of
titanium used in 1970 at GE's jet engine plant in the Cincinnati
suburb of Evendale, Lopatkiewicz said.
   ``We don't have the disk from the actual aircraft,''
Lopatkiewicz said by telephone from his home in Falls Church, Va.
``So by looking at others made from same billet, we might be able
to learn something about the metallurgical quality of the disk
we're looking for.''
   The parts will be sent to GE's Evendale plant, where Flight
232's three CF6-6 engines were built, Lopatkiewicz said. They will
be examined by an NTSB team investigating the crash.
   Originally, eight disks for GE's CF6-6 engine were made from the
titanium slab, Lopatkiewicz said. One of the eight disks failed
quality-control tests and was scrapped, and another was used in the
tail engine of Flight 232, he said. The CF6-6 engine was produced
exclusively for the DC-10.
   The six others are being removed from the commercial jetliners
and most likely will be replaced before the aircraft return to the
skies, he said.
   Last week, Weber denied speculation by Rep. John Dingell,
D-Mich, that scrap parts may have been used in the DC-10 engine
that apparently failed on the Iowa flight.
   Dingell, who chairs a House Energy and Commerce subcommittee
that oversees crash investigations, has asked the Federal Aviation
Administration to investigate whether scrap parts were used.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
