<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0404 07-31 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0404,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Nikkei Up</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: LEADS with xx grafs to UPDATE with closing Nikkei, dolla. Picks
up 4th pvs, `Toru Kanai ...'</UNK>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo Monday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange moved
sharply higher.
   The dollar closed at 138.40 yen, down 1.05 yen from Friday's
139.45-yen finish. After opening at 138.90 yen, it ranged between
138.15 and 139.10 yen.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues added 248.24 points, or 0.72 percent, closing at 34,953.87,
yet another record high.
   Toru Kanai, a foreign exchange analyst with New Japan Securities
Co., said the dollar fell gradually because the U.S. Federal
Reserve Board's move to relax monetary policy has made it less
attractive to Japanese buyers.
   Last week, the Federal Reserve Board was seen taking a relaxed
credit position by allowing the federal fund rate to move to 9
percent from 9.25 percent.
   The federal fund rate, the fee that banks charge one another on
overnight loans, is considered a barometer of the central bank's
credit policy.
   ``There is nothing happening here to turn investors away from
buying the dollar, except for the market sentiment for a weaker
dollar due to expectations that the Fed might further relax the
monetary policy,'' Kanai said.
   On the stock exchange market, ``trading was directionless
although the index rose,'' said Masahiro Umemori, a stock analyst
with Nomura Securities.
   He attributed the Nikkei's rebound to the yen's strength against
the dollar on the foreign exchange market.
</TEXT>
