<NOTE>Judge Penalizes Doctor for Patient Dumping</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal agency judge says a Texas
obstetrician let his fear of a malpractice lawsuit cloud his
judgment when he ordered a poor, sick woman who was about to give
birth transferred to another hospital 160 miles away.
   Dr. Michael L. Burditt is the first physician prosecuted for
violating a 1986 federal law against patient dumping. He is
expected to fight the $20,000 civil penalty imposed upon him by the
Department of Health and Human Services.
   The agency on Sunday released the 44-page ruling by
Administrative Law Judge Charles E. Stratton upholding the HHS
inspector general's sanctions against Burditt but reducing the fine
from $25,000 to $20,000.
   The Texas Medical Association has agreed to pay Burditt's legal
costs and any fine stemming from his handling of the case of Rosa
Rivera.
   Mrs. Rivera showed up at the emergency room of DeTar Hospital in
Victoria on Dec. 5, 1986, to have her sixth child without seeing a
doctor during the pregnancy and with blood pressure of 210 over 160
_ high enough to cause stroke and death.
   Burditt, then chief of the hospital's obstetrical department,
was summoned by phone to treat the indigent woman because he was
next on a list to handle emergency obstetrical calls.
   Burditt examined the woman and ordered her transferred to a
better equipped hospital in Galveston, despite the objections of
nurses worried that it would violate the then-new law against
patient dumping which specifies that hospitals must treat patients
in medical emergencies or in active labor.
   Burditt said he would choose his patients until DeTar, a private
hospital, paid his malpractice premiums.
   Mrs. Rivera bore a healthy 6-pound baby boy in the ambulance
parked on the roadside 40 miles east of Victoria.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>GAO Criticizes Desert Management</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal Bureau of Land Management has let
commercial and recreational interests take priority over the
protection of wildlife in the California Desert, government
auditors say.
   The General Accounting Office said in a report released Sunday
that while there has been a shortage of money to develop wildlife
protection plans, ``even if more funds were available ... BLM has
not demonstrated the willingness to take actions necessary to
protect wildlife interests.''
   For example, the GAO said, the bureau has permitted motorcycle
races and established ``free play'' areas for off-highway vehicles
in areas important to the desert tortoise, has allowed livestock
grazing that is harmful to some species, and has placed
insufficient restrictions on mining operations.
   ``BLM has frequently allowed the needs of competing interests,
such as recreation and commercial use, to take precedence over
wildlife interests when conflicts arise,'' the GAO said.
   It said data on the desert tortoise _ an important gauge for the
health of habitat for other species in the desert_ ``indicate that
the effects are not favorable.''
   ``Desert tortoise numbers have decreased dramatically in recent
years, and according to tortoise experts, the species may now be
sliding irreversibly toward extinction,'' the GAO said.
</TEXT>
