<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-31 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Dives, Stocks Bounce Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index bounced back
from last Friday's losses and closed at a new high today, while the
dollar fell sharply against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 248.24 points, or 0.72
percent, closing at 34,953.87. It had declined by 79.65 points last
Friday.
   Yoshio Shimoyama, a senior dealer at Nikko Securities, said the
index climbed on the yen's sharp rise against the dollar and
expectations for lower interest rates.
   ``Economic factors, such as the exchange rate, are becoming
favorable for stock investment, but trading was directionless and
volume was small, mainly because of political uncertainties,'' he
said.
   First section volume was estimated at 500 million shares. Among
gainers were Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. and electrical
issues.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 138.40 yen, down 1.05
yen from last Friday's close of 139.45 yen. After opening at 138.90
yen, the dollar ranged between 138.15 yen and 139.10 yen.
   Takamasa Yamasaki, a senior trader with Daiwa Bank, said,
``Investors had bought the dollar despite the downtrend in the U.S.
interest rate ... and now they are selling back the excess dollars
they bought.''
   ``Market players are trying to make the dollar go lower than the
138-yen level,'' he added. ``If it breaks that (138-yen) line and
falls further, it would keep falling to as low as 133 yen or so.''
</TEXT>
