<HEAD>Barricaded Gunman Shoots Up Detroit Police Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman was barricaded in his house today after
shooting up a police car and firing on a passing helicopter in
response to an effort by authorities to arrest him on an attempted
murder charge.
   ``He's shooting periodically and randomly,'' said police
spokesman Sgt. George Anthony. ``He's well armed. The situation is
extremely dangerous.''
   The incident began in northeast Detroit about 9:45 p.m. Sunday,
when the gunman opened fire on police from the neighboring city of
Highland Park who had arrived at his house to serve the warrant,
Anthony said.
   The gunman, whose name was not being disclosed, later fired many
rounds into a Detroit police car that responded to the shooting.
There were no injuries, Anthony said.
   Police sealed off the area and evacuated several dozen
neighborhood residents.
   The gunman also took shots at a police helicopter hovering over
his home, officials said.
   Police could not immediately provide details on the warrant that
set off the episode.
