<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 0452EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cuba     07-31 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuba,0794</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits a0437 to fix category code</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Voice from Cuba's Dissident Subculture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some people were not born to live in a socialist
system. Miguel is one of them.
   Miguel, not his real name, is an educated man in his late 50's
who has lived in uneasy intimacy with Fidel Castro's revolution for
three decades. He doesn't seem to belong.
   Known as a dissident, although a harmless one, Miguel works as a
guard, receiving the lowest salary he says the law permits _ 100
pesos a month.
   His diet is mind-numbing in its lack of variety although it is
not clear whether the problem is more the result of apathy or
scarcity. He has one meal a day consisting almost always of two or
more fried eggs and a scoop of rice.
   Asked why he is not slim, Miguel says his normal weight is 250
pounds so that, for him, 215 pounds is ``skinny.''
   He is asked why his diet is so limited. He invites his
questioner to inspect a bakery a block away. The shelves are empty
but there is a promise of bread in two hours. He suggests the
promise may be as empty as the shelves.
   What about fruits or vegetables? With a wave of the hand, he
suggests that these are occasionally available but often arrive at
the market too rotten to eat.
   To fight hunger, Miguel smokes a pack of cigarettes a day. That
means one-third of his income goes up in smoke.
   He is part of a subculture here which looks on the revolution
with disdain. Every country has an unassimilable subculture, and
Cuba is no exception.
   Miguel has been at the bottom of the heap for some time. But
Cuban officials point out that people like Miguel at least have a
job, a place to live, food on the table and access to medical care.
   This, indeed, is what sets Cuba apart. Cuba guarantees a minimal
living standard for its people; most other countries don't come
close to that ideal.
   There are tens of millions elsewhere in Latin America who don't
live nearly as well as Miguel. But the psychic pain he suffers is
great because, before the revolution, he once commanded respect as
an educated professional who used to enjoy the good life _
restaurants, nightclubs, the theater.
   The government has pegged him as ideologically unreliable so he
is condemned to his mundane, unchallenging existence. He can't get
permission to leave the country.
   A walk with Miguel through the streets of Havana elicits from
him unbridled criticism of what Castro's revolution has wrought.
   He whines about street crime, smoke-belching buses, crumbling
buildings, the absence of places to buy even a soft drink, the long
lines for public transportation, the political repression.
   To underscore the country's housing shortage, he points out a
unique Cuban institution called a ``posada.'' That is where lovers,
usually young and with no access to privacy at home, can spend some
quiet time together in a no-frills room.
   Continuing his stroll through the city, Miguel wistfully recalls
when Havana was a lovely, modern capital. It is now terribly
rundown.
   The revolution has indeed shown little concern for maintaining
the splendor, albeit defective, of mid-century Havana. Attention
has been focused instead on the countryside, so woefully neglected
by Castro's rightist predecessors.
   Countless numbers suffered appalling deprivation, with little
hope of a decent job, schooling or medical care. A quarter of the
Cuban population was illiterate.
   Castro visited Camaguey province 300 miles east of here this
past week and ticked off the long list of advances in almost every
economic and social category since the revolution. The list sounds
impressive.
   And, according to some U.S. estimates, over one-third of all
Cubans live better than they did before the revolution.
   Even after 30 years, Castro's appearance generates emotional
responses. Many Cubans still sense that ``Fidel,'' as they call
him, is no ordinary mortal.
   But the day before Castro spoke, there was evidence that
shortages extend well beyond Havana.
   Long lines of shoppers were seen all over Camaguey. At one
store, several hundred people waited for hours to buy tins of a
European import roughly equivalent to Spam. The price was 3 pesos,
or about $3.75, for a 4-ounce can. The average wage in Cuba is
little over a peso an hour.
   To the extent there are hardships, the average Cuban confronts
them with grace and humor.
   And to Castro, the alternative is the ``egotistical, brutal and
inhumane'' capitalist system, as he said last Wednesday. Don't tell
that to Miguel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
