<FIRST>r a PM-BlastedTown     07-31 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blasted Town,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town with Dozen Residents Battles Mining Company in David-Goliath
Struggle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dozen or so residents of an 1870s Nevada
boomtown, calling themselves Davids to a small mining company's
Goliath, are fighting for their homes _ and town _ as the company
moves to level buildings in a gold hunt.
   Homeowners in Tuscarora, a flyspeck on the map 250 miles
northeast of Reno, have been told ``we are nothing more than
squatters,'' Richard Schupbach said at a news conference last week.
   ``The people out there are being run roughshod over simply
because there's only a handful of people,'' said environmentalist
Bob Fulkerson. ``This is a classic David and Goliath issue.''
   Bob Jones, of Horizon Gold Shares of Denver, called it ``a David
vs. David battle.''
   The company, which has about 100 employees, plans to dig a pit
mine that would consume half the community.
   ``The problem is, it's a town and we can't move,'' Schupbach
said. ``And once they mine it, it will be gone, and gone forever.''
   The dozen year-round residents and two dozen homeowners are
asking the Elko County Commission to grant historic status to
buildings in the community, which would give them some protection
from development plans.
   In the 1870s the northeastern Nevada community had 4,000
residents, drawn by the historic Dexter Mine.
   The commission plans to meet Aug. 15 in Tuscarora to discuss the
proposal.
   Under state law, mining companies can condemn property. But
Horizon President John Watson has said the company would use
eminent domain only as a last resort.
   Jones, general manager of the mining operation, said in a
telephone interview from Tuscarora the company has invested $8
million in the operation and has offered to buy out homeowners,
even though it owns the land. Top price for the homes is $50,000,
he said.
   Jones said Horizon plans to file legal papers in August to take
over the land.
   ``We think the residents are overreacting,'' Jones said. ``They
are on privately-owned land _ ours. We're not even sure they have
anything to sell. Basically, they have very little legal ground to
stand on. ... Most of them came in the 1960s and kind of squatted
here.''
   Residents disagree. Many said they have legal documentation to
prove they own the buildings.
   Fulkerson, executive director of Citizen Alert, an environmental
group, said Horizon Gold Shares came to Tuscarora in 1987 ``to
rape, pillage and plunder'' by digging a 400-by-800 foot wide,
150-foot deep open pit mine just south of the town.
   Residents complain that the mining exploratory work has cracked
home foundations and caused other damage.
   Elko County Manager George Boucher said Tuscarora homeowners are
at the mercy of the mining company because the town does not have a
legal status. ``When Tuscarora was created, somebody forgot to file
the map.''
   But Fulkerson said residents have always paid property taxes to
the county, establishing Tuscarora as a real town.
   Schupbach, a Stanford University professor, said he plans to
retire to ghost-town life in Tuscarora _ ``if the town still
exists.''
   Another resident, Dennis Parks, moved to Tuscarora in 1966 to
start a pottery school. Now he wonders if he'll be moving out soon.
   ``It seemed like a safe place to live,'' he lamented. ``It
certainly looked like all industrial activity was in the past.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
