<FIRST>r a PM-PlaneCrash     07-31 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Crash,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Planes Collide Near Airport; 7 Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two small airplanes collided only moments
after one had dropped parachutists at a hot air balloon festival,
and all seven people aboard the planes were killed, authorities
said.
   One person on the ground was injured slightly from falling
debris, officials said.
   ``They were flying one over the other, then one flew up and hit
the other,'' said Frank Kosh, a witness.
   The planes collided Sunday over a shopping mall about a mile
southwest of the Queen City Airport, which was hosting the balloon
festival, said Bill Vogel, area supervisor for the Federal Aviation
Administration.
   FAA spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen said the plane that carried the
parachutists crashed near the mall with its left wing missing.
   Airport spokeswoman Joan Wildman identified the craft as a
Cessna 182. The other plane was a Beechcraft Bonanza, according to
officials.
   The Beechcraft crashed at a car dealership across the street,
officials said.
   Vogel declined to speculate on how the 1:34 p.m. crash occurred.
   One man on the ground suffered minor injuries when his car was
struck by debris, but he did not require hospitalization, police
said.
   Kosh said the plane at the dealership ``was all in pieces. The
pilot was in the flames burning.''
   The plane destroyed one car and damaged another, Salisbury
police officer Brian Klimowicz said.
   The planes collided as they were returning to the airport,
Klimowicz said. He said the Cessna had just dropped two
parachutists and was returning to the airport. The parachutists
landed safely, officials said.
   ``For some unknown reason, it appeared that the Cessna just
continued to bank and struck the Beechcraft,'' he said.
   Lehigh County Coroner Wayne Snyder identified the Cessna 182
pilot as 47-year-old Peter C. Miller. He was the only person aboard
the Cessna.
   The Beechcraft pilot was identified as Dr. Abdul Kahn, 43. Also
on board were Dr. Muhammad A. Malik, 45, and his 12-year-old son,
Raymond Malik, Snyder said.
   Malik was the head of a trauma team at the Lehigh Valley
Hospital Center.
   The two doctors recently bought the Beechcraft and were ``up on
a check-out flight with an instructor and were heading toward the
airport,'' Snyder said.
   Continental Airlines pilot and flight instructor Stephen Remo,
42, his wife, Kathleen, and their 3-year-old daughter, Alicia, also
died in the Beechcraft. Snyder said he did not know Mrs. Remo's age.
   The Federal Aviation Administration said the planes had been
flying at an altitude of 1,500 to 2,000 feet.
   Airport spokeswoman Lori Remaley said the balloon festival,
which ran from Friday to Sunday, involved 40 to 45 hot-air
balloons. No balloons were in the air at the time of the collision,
she said.
</TEXT>
