<FIRST>r a PM-RootInterview     07-31 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Root Interview,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Root Says He's `Just a Guy'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHELBY, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas Root, the lawyer who made a
mysterious 800-mile flight and then crashed in the Atlantic, says
he's just a guy who passed out at the controls.
   Root, 36, was flying from Washington, D.C., to Rocky Mount,
N.C., on July 13 when he says he passed out. The plane flew on
autopilot until it ran out of gas and ditched off the Bahamas.
Doctors at Hollywood, Fla., hospital discovered a bullet wound in
Root's abdomen after the crash.
   Root, who said he can not explain the bullet wound, says the
crash generated a lot of ``hoopla.''
   ``People can't help but read all this stuff and ... think what
kind of criminal is this guy?'' he said in an interview Saturday
with radio station WSWR in Shelby, which he owns. ``My response is:
no kind of criminal, just a guy that was going to a deposition and
... something happened.''
   Root, who was interviewed at his parents' house in Plymouth, 50
miles southeast of Cleveland, where he has been recovering,
returned Saturday to his home in Arlington, Va.
   Although blood tests for carbon monoxide were negative, Root
said he believes a carbon dioxide buildup may have caused him to
black out during the flight.
   Root said he was unaware he had been shot until doctors at the
hospital told him. He said the loaded revolver he kept in the
plane's glove compartment may have gone off on impact _ a theory
the manufacturer of the .32-caliber Smith &amp; Wesson disputed.
   Root was sued in federal court in New Orleans last week by a
group of investors who allege he lost them $125,000 in 1987 by
misrepresenting them in a bid to obtain a Federal Communications
Commission license to build a radio station.
</TEXT>
