<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 0638EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChristianChurch     07-31 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Christian Church,0408</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Disciples Unite with United Church of Christ ^By DENISE BEZICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of two Christian denominations that
have entered into a working partnership say members will be
encouraged to worship together, but local congregations will
maintain their own identities.
   About 6,000 delegates to the Christian Church (Disciples of
Christ) General Assembly agreed Saturday to enter into full
communion, including mutual recognition of members and clergy, with
the United Church of Christ.
   The resolution means the two churches will recognize each
other's members as joint believers in a common faith and will make
an effort to coordinate their social services, missionary work and
community functions, said Paul Crow Jr., president of the Council
on Christian Unity.
   The United Church of Christ adopted a similar resolution at its
convention in Fort Worth, Texas, a month ago.
   The granting of full communion, Crow said, makes the two
churches ``brothers'' rather than ``cousins.''
   ``This is not a merger. It's not a uniting of the churches'
structure,'' Crow said at the convention which continues through
Wednesday. ``This is setting up a common acknowledgement of each
other.''
   Saturday's endorsement came despite criticism from some members
of the Christian Church that the United Church of Christ is too
liberal.
   The two churches base their faith on the same Christian
doctrine, Crow said. But they differ in some worship practices and
church policies, he said.
   For example, the United Church of Christ forbids churches from
considering sexual orientation in the hiring of ministers. That
means the church officially allows homosexuals to become ministers
and forbids member churches from discriminating against them.
   ``In putting our stamp of approval on this, we are putting our
stamp of approval on homosexuality,'' said Bethel Nason of Topeka,
Kansas.
   Another delegate, Mike Wolfe of Spearman, Texas, charged the
United Church of Christ is ``far to the left, both political and
ecumenically.''
   But Crow says the differences in social beliefs are as common
within the Christian Church as they are between the two
denominations.
   ``The Christian Church allows for unity in diversity, but that
diversity need not divide us,'' he said.
   The Christian Church (Disciples of Christ) was formed in 1832 as
part of an early frontier movement to unify Christians. The United
Church of Christ was formed in 1961 when the Evangelical and
Reformed Church merged with the Congregational Christian Churches.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
