<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: To CORRECT closing dollar rate in Tokyo, SUB 13th graf, `In Tokyo
... 137.80 yen.' Picks up 14th, `In London ...'</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slid in light trading in Europe today
following a spate of selling in Asian markets and a general lack of
interest in the U.S. currency. Gold prices were mixed.
   Dealers said the early momentum toward a lower U.S. currency
began in East Asia, where a large sell order from a banking
institution prompted other selling.
   In a market thinned by summer vacations, even a moderate-sized
order can greatly influence exchange rates, said a West German
banker.
   Traders predicted the dollar would continue to trade in a
holding pattern between 1.8700 West German marks and 1.8800 marks.
   In London, the British pound rose to 1.6600 dollars from 1.6455
dollars late Friday.
   Other mid-morning dollar rates in Europe compared with late
Friday:
   _1.8715 West German marks, down from 1.8845
   _1.6115 Swiss francs, down from 1.6180
   _6.3385 French francs, down from 6.3825
   _2.1130 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1240
   _1,346.50 Italian lire, down from 1,354.00
   _1.1825 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1838
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before European markets
open, the dollar fell 1.05 yen to close at 138.40 Japanese yen.
Later, in London, the dollar fell to 137.80 yen.
   In London, gold opened at a bid price of $368.35 a troy ounce,
down from $369.20 bid late Friday. At mid-morning, London dealers
fixed a recommended price of $369.10.
   In Zurich, it fell to $368.50 bid, down from $369.75 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose 86 cents an ounce to close at
$369.64.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid of $5.16 a troy
ounce from $5.14 bid late Friday.
