<FIRST>r a PM-AntarcticaExpedition     07-31 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Antarctica Expedition,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expedition Encounters First Big Crevasse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spirits were reported high among members
of a trans-Antarctica expedition after the six adventurers detoured
around the first gaping crevasse encountered on the trek.
   The expedition, led by Minnesotan Will Steger and Frenchman
Jean-Louis Etienne, made radio contact with their support crew at
an Antarctic research base and in Punta Arenas, Chile, on Sunday.
It was the second report since they began the 4,000-mile,
seven-month trip on skis and dog sleds last week.
   ``The dogs are very wild. They want to keep pulling to the South
Pole right now,'' said Steger, 44.
   The adventurers also talked to an ABC sports commentator for a
Sunday night special on the expedition.
   Steger reported that the St. Paul-based expedition would spend
several extra hours today photographing equipment supplied by
sponsors of the $11 million expedition.
   Steger hopes to draw worldwide attention to his exploits and
raise awareness of ecological threats to the frozen continent.
   On Saturday, the group came up to a ``very, very big crevasse,
longer than the dogs and sleds combined,'' radioed Etienne, a
French physician. He said the men backed away and went around it.
   The team had unobstructed travel Sunday, with a 25 mph crosswind
and daytime temperatures a mild 26 degrees. The surface of the
Larsen Ice Shelf, a plateau of permanent sea ice, is hard and
windblown, making travel fast.
   The expedition covered two miles after taking off Thursday, five
miles on Friday, 10 Saturday and 13 Sunday. The pace is expected to
quicken after a French film crew accompanying the explorers drops
off.
   The six-man team will have to cover 20 to 30 miles a day to
complete the crossing in seven months.
</TEXT>
