<FIRST>r a PM-TropicalWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0504 07-31 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tropical Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0504,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Depression Watched In South-Central Gulf</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with another tropical depression
detected. PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `Two depressions ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As one tropical depression gained strength and
speed on its march toward the Gulf Coast today, satellite images
showed another tropical depression taking shape over the
mid-Atlantic, forecasters said.
   People on the Gulf Coast west of the Florida Panhandle should
closely monitor the progress of first depression, advised Bob Case,
a forecaster at the National Hurricane Center in Coral Gables, a
suburb of Miami.
   At 6 a.m. EDT the storm system, the Atlantic hurricane season's
fourth tropical depression, had top sustained winds of 35 mph with
gusts to 45 mph. Its center was about 280 miles southeast of
Galveston, Texas.
   The system was moving north by northwest at about 12 mph and was
expected to grow stronger throughout today, the center said.
   Forecasters issued a tropical storm watch early today for the
Gulf Coast from Port O'Connor, Texas, to the mouth of the
Mississippi River. An Air Force reconnaissance plane was scheduled
to explore the depression later in the day.
   Meanwhile, in the middle of the Atlantic, satellite imagery
showed another tropical depression forming.
   By 8 a.m. EDT, the fifth tropical depression of the season had
top sustained winds of 35 mph and was centered 1,500 miles east of
the Lesser Antilles.
   It was moving west at about 18 mph and was expected to gain
strength and hold its course today, forecasters said.
   The next depression to reach top sustained speeds of 39 mph will
be named Tropical Storm Chantal, followed by Tropical Storm Dean.
Hurricanes have winds of 74 mph.
   Two depressions have formed into named storms since the 1989
Atlantic hurricane season began June 1.
   Tropical Storm Allison, the first, caused widespread flooding in
Texas and Louisiana in June. Storm Barry lived briefly in the open
Atlantic in mid-July before being downgraded to a tropical
depression and then dissipating.
</TEXT>
