<FIRST>r a PM-DetectiveSlaying     07-31 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detective Slaying,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Convicted of Racketeering in Detective's Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS F. McELROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three reputed Mafia figures who escaped
conviction on state charges of murdering a New York City detective
have been found guilty in federal court of racketeering in the 1986
slaying.
   Frederico ``Fritzy'' Giovanelli, 56; Steven Maltese, 57, and
Carmine ``Buddy'' Gualtiere, 55, of New York City, were convicted
Sunday of violating the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organizations Act.
   Detective Anthony J. Venditti, 34, was shot to death and his
partner, Detective Kathleen Burke, was injured in 1986 outside a
diner during mob surveillance.
   ``Tony Venditti can finally rest in peace,'' Burke said after
the 11-week trial.
   The defendants were charged with murder, but the first trial in
1987 ended in a hung jury and the second in 1988 resulted in
Gualtiere's acquittal and a deadlock over charges against
Giovanelli and Maltese.
   Prosecutors then turned to federal court, charging the men under
the RICO Act.
   ``It demonstrates our resolve to use every legal means available
to us to bring to justice those responsible for the murder of a
police officer,'' said U.S. Attorney Benito Romano.
   ``It also demonstrates the extraordinary value of the RICO
statutes to allow us, in this case, to place in context the murder
of Police Officer Venditti as part of a pattern of crime engaged in
to protect a large-scale gambling operation.''
   The jury found the three guilty of racketeering, loansharking,
interstate travel in aid of the racketeering enterprise and tax
charges. Under the racketeering charges, the three also were
convicted of murder and attempted murder.
   The three reputed associates of the Genovese crime family did
not know Venditti was a police officer and were afraid they were
going to be ``ripped off,'' Romano said.
   The verdict came on the fifth day of deliberations.
   Giovanelli faces 70 years in prison, Maltese 75 years and
Gualtiere 50. Each could be fined more than $1 million. Sentencing
was set for Oct. 18.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
