<FIRST>u a PM-TropicalWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0504 07-31 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tropical Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0504,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tropical Storm Develops; Hurricane Warnings Posted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with tropical storm developing, hurricane
warnings posted. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The third tropical storm of the Atlantic hurricane
season developed in the Gulf of Mexico today bearing 50 mph winds,
prompting hurricane warnings along the Texas and Louisiana coast.
   At 9 a.m. EDT, Tropical Storm Chantal was centered about 260
miles southeast of Galveston, Texas, moving northwest near 8 mph,
and was expected to move ashore Tuesday with high tides and heavy
rain, forecasters said.
   The storm was expected to build into a hurricane tonight or
Tuesday, said Bob Sheets, director of the National Hurricane Center
in suburban Coral Gables. Hurricanes have winds of at least 74 mph.
   Hurricane warnings were posted from Freeport, Texas, to Morgan
City, La. Tropical storm warnings were went up from Port O'Connor,
Texas, to Freeport and from Morgan City to Mobile, Ala.
   Tides of 5 to 7 feet above normal were expected over the
hurricane warning area and up to 7 to 10 feet above normal near and
to the right of where the center hits land. Small craft were
advised to remain in port.
   Chantal formed from the fourth tropical depression of the
Atlantic season.
   As Chantal gained strength, satellite images showed another
tropical depression taking shape in the mid-Atlantic. By 9 a.m.
EDT, it had top sustained winds of 35 mph and was centered 1,500
miles east of the Lesser Antilles.
   That depression was moving west at about 18 mph and was expected
to gain strength and hold its course today.
   If its winds hit a sustained speed of 39 mph, it will be named
Tropical Storm Dean.
   Two depressions have formed into named storms since the 1989
Atlantic hurricane season began June 1.
   Tropical Storm Allison, the first, caused widespread flooding in
Texas and Louisiana in June. Storm Barry lived briefly in the open
Atlantic in mid-July before dissipating.
</TEXT>
