<FIRST>r a PM-GroceryStrike     07-31 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grocery Strike,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seattle-Area Supermarket Strike Ends</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA DE LA CRUZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 8,000 grocery clerks and meat
cutters agreed to end an 81-day strike that forced Puget Sound
supermarkets to cut back their hours.
   Members of the Food and Commercial Workers union voted Sunday
night to accept a three-year contract that provides raises and
continues Sunday premium pay, which employers had sought to cut,
said union spokeswoman Sandi Hubler.
   Grocers also withdrew a proposal for drug testing, she said.
   The workers, who walked out May 11, were expected to begin
returning today.
   The agreement with Allied Employers Inc., the industry group
that conducted negotiations, ends a strike at Safeway, Albertson's,
Food Giant, Fred Meyer, Mega Foods and other chains in King, Pierce
and Snohomish counties.
   Markets had hired workers to replace the strikers, but many
stores were forced to cut back their hours.
   The contract is expected to set a pattern for agreements
covering about 25,000 workers at virtually all markets in the Puget
Sound area.
   Four union locals that revealed vote counts reported lopsided
voting in favor of the pact. At the big Seattle Local 1105, the
vote was 1,605 to 235.
   Employees must report their availability within 24 hours,
enabling employers to recall workers as needed, said Don King,
executive director of the management group.
   The agreement gives raises to workers in all classifications,
said Jay Murphy, a union business agent. Pay for top-scale clerks
will rise to $11.45 an hour from $11.15, he said. Top-scale meat
cutters make slightly more.
</TEXT>
