<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1250EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Abduction 2ndLd-Writethru a0547 07-31 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Abduction, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0547,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israelis Say They Have No Confirmation on Higgins</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout with Israel saying it has no confirmation of Higgins
being executed, Israeli offer still stands; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli officials said today they received no
immediate confirmation of a claim from a Moslem Shiite group that
it executed a U.S. Marine hostage to retaliate for the Israeli
abduction of a Moslem cleric.
   They also reiterated their offer made earlier today to trade all
Israel's Shiite Moslem captives for all captured Israeli soldiers
and foreign hostages held by Shiite groups in Lebanon.
   A pro-Iranian Organization of the Oppressed on Earth said it
executed Lt. Col. William R. Higgins today after a deadline passed
for their demand that the abducted cleric be released.
   Higgins was head of an unarmed U.N. observer group in Lebanon
when he was abducted in February 1988 in south Lebanon.
   ``At this point, we have no confirmation that, indeed, Colonel
Higgins was murdered,'' said Avi Pazner, spokesman for Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   ``We have to be very cautious with a possible reaction because
you remember a year ago the same organization said that they
executed Col. Higgins after the accidental shooting-down of an
Iranian airplane by the U.S. Navy.
   ``So we will have to look for further evidence to confirm where
such an odious and criminal act has been perpetrated,'' he told The
Associated Press.
   Sources in Lebanon have said the United Nations received
unconfirmed reports earlier this year that Higgins was killed after
an Iranian airliner was shot down by a U.S. warship on July 3, 1988.
   Spokesmen for Israel's defense and foreign ministries refused to
comment immediately on the report of Higgins' death.
   In making the Israeli offer today, Defense Minister Yitzhak
Rabin said, ``Israel repeats its call for the release of Israeli
and other hostages held by Shiite groups in Lebanon. Israel is
offering to trade prisoners, detainees and hostages.''
   His statement to reporters in Tel Aviv, read from a prepared
text, was also broadcast on state-run Israel radio. Pazner later
said the offer was made on behalf of the government.
   ``According to this proposal, all the Israeli prisoners and
foreign hostages held by Shiite groups in Lebanon would be swapped
for all the Shiite prisoners kept by Israel, including Sheik Abdel
Karim Obeid, Jawad Kasfi and others,'' Rabin said.
   He said such an exchange would be conducted through the
International Red Cross.
   Pazner said the offer stands despite the claim that Higgins had
been executed.
   Obeid is an influential Shiite Moslem cleric kidnapped by
Israeli commandos Friday in south Lebanon, and Kasfi is another
Lebanese Shiite seized by Israeli forces in Lebanon last December.
   Obeid is the reputed spiritual leader of the Shiite Moslem
Hezbollah militia in south Lebanon, the umbrella group for factions
believed to be holding 17 foreign hostages in Lebanon. Nine are
American.
   Security sources estimate 50 to 60 Shiite Moslems from Lebanon
are held in Israeli prisons.
   The Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militia, which helps
patrol Israel's self-declared security zone in south Lebanon, holds
about 300 Shiites in a prison at Khiam in south Lebanon. It was not
immediately clear if this group would be part of the deal.
   Deputy Prime Minister Shimon Peres had said earlier today that
Israeli officials hoped Obeid could be swapped for three Israeli
soldiers missing in Lebanon since 1986 and believed held by
Hezbollah.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
