<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1257EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-VonRaab     07-31 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Von Raab,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customs Chief Leaves With a Blast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Customs Commissioner William von Raab
took the occasion of the Custom Service's 200th anniversary today
to announce his resignation and take some parting shots at those in
government he considers not as committed as he to the war on drugs.
   ``When we exposed the tin-horned dictator (Manuel) Noriega (of
Panama) as a drug king, the mildest phrase some used on us was
`out-of-control,''' von Raab told Customs officials gathered near
the Washington Monument.
   ``They attacked us, not him, but now they agree,'' said von
Raab, who was denied reappointment to the post he has held for
eight years and has been harshly critical of government colleagues
in recent interviews.
   ``When DEA (Drug Enforcement Administration) agent Kiki Camarena
was murdered in Mexico, we showed this country's outrage by
cracking down hard on the border. Mexico's Foreign Minister
Sepulveda attacked us; some in our own government actually joined
him,'' von Raab said.
   ``If we dared to speak out, it was because those in our own
government were too scared to speak up.''
   Von Raab, who said his resignation was effective at midnight
tonight, was praised at the 200th anniversary celebration by
lawmakers on opposite sides of the political spectrum for his
outspokenness on the drug war and the infighting between government
agencies.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., called von Raab ``a man of courage,
integrity and forthrightness,'' while Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y.,
said von Raab ``leaves a tradition and a standard for the rest of
us to follow.''
   The Customs Service included in its press package for the
anniversary celebration a copy of von Raab's letter of resignation,
sent today to President Bush, in which he blasted a failure of the
federal government to work together in the drug war.
   While praising William J. Bennett, director of the Office of
National Drug Control Policy, as a ``courageous man,'' von Raab
said he was ``deeply concerned by what I have witnessed within the
bureaucracy over the past months.
   ``The political jockeying, backstabbing and malaise that has
crept into the current effort have frustrated me, and are
threatening the antidrug efforts and successes of the past years,''
von Raab said in the letter.
   He also took a sharp hit at the Treasury Department, which
oversees the Customs Service, saying that many Treasury officials
``have shown at best a distinct lack of interest in the drug
efforts of the Customs Service, and at worst, an outright demotion
of Customs in relation to other Treasury priorities.''
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, who spoke last at the
ceremony, did not mention von Raab's imminent departure, focusing
instead on the hard work by Customs employees, cooperation among
Cabinet members in the antidrug effort and saying that the drug war
``is a war we are going to win.''
   At the close of the ceremony, von Raab shook hands with many of
the officials gathered on stage, but not with Brady.
   At a post-ceremony news conference, von Raab called Brady ``an
honorable man'' but said, ``I'm quitting, obviously, because I'm
not getting along with Secretary Brady.''
   Von Raab said he couldn't understand why Brady did not mention
him in his remarks and that he had toned down his own comments at
the request of the Treasury Department.
   He said he had heard rumors he would be fired, possibly in
response to similar blasts he has made at his department and others
in media interviews in previous weeks.
   Asked later whether it wasn't disingenuous of him to claim he
couldn't understand Brady's lack of warmth toward him in light of
his statements, von Raab simply shrugged, smiled and walked away.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
