<DOCNO> AP890731-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1400EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Strike     07-31 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Strike,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dock Strike Fizzles As Workers Return to Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3-week-old national dock workers' strike fizzled
Monday as more workers returned to their jobs after employers
threatened to fire those who stayed away.
   In Bristol, however, 480 dock workers voted to continue to stay
out over government plans to abolish guaranteed lifelong employment.
   Port employers said the returns meant that 3,668, or 57 percent,
of those affected by the job guarantee program were working and
2,741 remained on strike. Forty of the 60 ports affected by the
strike were operating normally, they said.
   ``Clearly more than 50 percent of dockers are back at work. They
have voted with their feet and I hope the Transport and General
Workers' Union will heed their wishes and call off this strike,''
said Nick Finney, director of the National Association of Port
Employers.
   But opposition Labor Party lawmaker Michael Meacher said Sunday:
``The reason is not lack of support for the cause, but the
intimidation and blackmail involved in threats of sackings.''
   The swing away from the strike came after union leaders voted
Friday to intensify the dispute and try to get more workers to
rejoin the strike.
   About 750 workers at the key ports of Southampton and Hull
defied their national leaders to return to the waterfronts Monday.
   Associated British Ports, one of Britain's biggest dock owners,
had threatened to fire Southampton, Hull and Fleetwood workers if
they stayed away Monday.
   The union leadership was due to meet Tuesday to discuss tactics.
</TEXT>
