<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Hostage-Sister, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0552,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Higgins' Relatives React to Report of his Killing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede OKOLONA, Ky.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with comment from relatives, friends. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon-Hostage, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of Lt. Col. William R. Higgins reacted with shock,
anger and disbelief today after pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems
announced the Marine had been hanged.
   In Lancaster, Ky., where Higgins spent summers as a youth, his
aunt, Leona Huffman, said she saw TV reports of the purported
killing, but after 1{ years of uncertainty about her nephew's fate,
she remained skeptical.
   ``I'm just not going to believe anything until I hear direct,''
said Mrs. Huffman, sister of Higgins' late mother, Ethel.
   Higgins, who was born in Danville, Ky., and grew up near
Louisville, was serving as head of an observer group attached to
the U.N. peacekeeping force in south Lebanon when he was seized in
February 1988. His captors accused him of spying for the CIA.
   Pro-Iranian Moslems today said he was executed in retaliation
for Israel's kidnapping of a Moslem cleric.
   Mrs. Huffman blamed the kidnappers for the death in February of
her brother, a retired judge.
   ``Unless you would go through something like this, you'd have no
idea what this has been to us,'' she said. ``My brother that
worshipped this child _ I think what killed him ... was grief.''
   Higgins' sister Mary Fisher said the State Department had called
her in the Louisville, Ky., suburb of Okolona. ``I will not reveal
what they said,'' said Ms. Fischer said.``Right now, I'm in a state
of shock. I just don't know.''
   Linda Lee Miller, another of Higgins' sisters who lives in the
Memphis, Tenn., suburb of Bartlett, said she would have a statement
later in the day.
   In Knoxville, Tenn., Leonard Smith, a cousin of Higgins, said of
the report, ``That's just appalling.''
   Smith said he last saw Higgins in the spring of 1987, a few
months before he left for the Middle East. Smith said Higgins was
optimistic about going. m``I don't think he considered it a
particularly high-risk job,'' Smith said.
   Yellow ribbons still fluttered from trees, doors, churches and
schools around Lancaster today _ the town's continuing sign of
sympathy for the hostage and his family.
   ``We just hope that, maybe, what we're hearing is not a fact,''
said florist Julian Moss, a childhood friend of Higgins who helped
launch the ribbon display.
</TEXT>
