<FIRST>r i AM-Palme     07-31 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palme,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister's Convicted Killer Appeals Verdict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christer Pettersson, convicted of
killing Prime Minister Olof Palme and sentenced to life in prison,
asked an appeals court Monday to overturn the judgement.
   The move was widely expected. Arne Liljeros, Pettersson's
attorney, had said he would appeal when the verdict and sentence
were announced Thursday in Stockholm District Court.
   Birgitta Blom, president of Svea Court Of Appeals, said the case
could be heard as early as Sept. 7, the national news agency TT
reported.
   The report gave no specific reason for the appeal, and details
were not expected to be made public until the official documents
reached the appelate court Tuesday or Wednesday.
   Palme, the leading figure in Swedish politics for two decades,
was shot to death Feb. 28, 1986, while walking home with his wife
from a late movie in downtown Stockholm. Pettersson was arrested in
December and convicted after a five-week trial that began June 5.
   Six of the eight-member jury voted to convict. The two
professional judges on the jury, who had equal votes, dissented on
grounds there was not enough hard evidence against Pettersson.
   Several witnesses, including Palme's widow, said they saw
Pettersson shadowing the couple as they left the theater. Lisbeth
Palme identified Pettersson as the man standing near her husband
when he crumpled to the pavement with a fatal wound.
   Jurors said Mrs. Palme's testimony was decisive.
   However, no one testified to seeing Pettersson fire the shots
that killed Palme and grazed his wife. The weapon, a .357-Magnum
revolver, was never found, and no motive for the killing was
established.
   Pettersson, 42, has a record of more than 60 criminal
convictions, including a conviction for manslaughter. He is an
admitted abuser of amphetamines and alcohol who repeatedly was
ordered into psychiatric care.
   ``We want the evidence to be heard again,'' said Lars Ekman,
another Pettersson attorney. ``In the first place that means that
we want all witnesses to be called again,'' including Lisbeth
Palme, he said.
</TEXT>
