<FIRST>r a PM-ChainedSmoker     07-31 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chained Smoker,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Chain Comes Off, and Smoker is Nicotine-Free</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who chained himself to his sofa
for three weeks to stop smoking is a free man today and says it
feels wonderful to have kicked the habit.
   Thomas Warren, 42, on Sunday unlocked the 25-foot steel cable
that had been attached to a 280-pound sofa in his living room and
fashioned around his neck like a dog collar.
   He celebrated his freedom by going out to dinner with friends
and running two miles at midnight.
   ``During the run I felt like a bird,'' said Warren, a former
marathon runner who developed severe respiratory problems from 20
years of smoking. ``My breathing afterward felt smooth and
controlled. You just can't beat that. I feel great.''
   Warren, an artist, dog trainer and drug counselor, had his
friends chain him July 9. He had tried several methods to break his
pack-a-day habit, including acupuncture, Smokers Anonymous and
meditation.
   ``In my hometown, everyone who knew me laughed and thought I
really was a ridiculous person for doing this,'' Warren said. ``But
the reward is what this did for other people around the world with
smoking addictions. I feel like a millionaire.''
   Warren conceded it will be a daily fight to quit smoking for
good.
   ``But I'm not going to allow myself to,'' he said. ``I have the
power to say no.''
</TEXT>
