<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1329EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-JailedLawmaker Bjt   07-31 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jailed Lawmaker, Bjt,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jailed Lawmaker Represents Michigan's Third-Largest City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY HAYNES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARREN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twice a day, state Rep. Dennis Dutko picks
up a pay phone in the Ingham County Jail and calls his office to
check on the latest from the Capitol or his constituents.
   Since his one-year sentence began May 24 for a third drunken
driving conviction, the eight-term Democrat has represented his
suburban Detroit district from his jail cell.
   Even his staff questions how effective he is from behind bars.
   ``Because he doesn't have a vote, to tell you that he does have
an impact on the House would be to distort the situation,'' Dutko
aide Paul Mendelsohn said.
   Upon conviction, the 45-year-old bachelor was stripped of his
chairmanship of the House committee on colleges and universities
and the chairmanship of a subcommittee on long-term and
supplemental Medicare insurance.
   A week after being jailed, Dutko said he would resign July 1. He
then reneged, saying he would wait until the legislature returns to
Lansing on Sept. 15, after a recess that began last Fridy.
Meanwhile, attorneys are trying to appeal his convictions.
   Dutko still receives his $42,670 annual salary, but has said he
will donate it to alcohol treatment programs while he's in jail.
The Michigan Legislature is a full-time job, and he had no other
employment.
   Dutko's House colleagues urged him to step down after he was
jailed, but they have avoided trying to oust him, apparently
reluctant to break ranks.
   ``My view is he's an embarrassment to the city,'' said GOP
precinct delegate William Sears, who started an effort to have
Dutko recalled. ``The city has been without a voice in Lansing. He
did not even participate in the state budget.''
   But the recall petition drive has suffered from a lack of
interest. A dozen people showed up for the first informational
meeting.
   State Attorney General Frank Kelley says that because Dutko was
convicted of a misdemeanor instead of a felony, no state law forces
him to quit the legislature.
   Dutko is believed to be the nation's only legislator holding
onto his job while serving a jail sentence, according to Rich
Jones, director of legislative programs for the National Conference
of State Legislatures in Denver.
   Mendelsohn and another aide, Darren Campbell, sign their own
names when responding to letters written to Dutko's office. They
also are producing a district newsletter Dutko used to write.
   ``We've been handed a lot of control over what happens in the
office,'' Mendelsohn said. Dutko refused comment.
   Paper work and briefing material must be mailed to Dutko. The
only hand-delivered packages he can accept contain white socks and
underwear.
   The Michigan chapter of Mothers Against Drunk Driving and a
small faction of constituents circulating the recall petition have
been vocal about Dutko's actions.
   But most people express little interest in the case.
   ``It's something that people have been reading about, but it's
not something they are upset about,'' said Michael Raveane, editor
of the Warren Weekly, distributed free to 60,000 homes.
   Raveane says a majority of letters to the editor on Dutko's
incarceration have been sympathetic.
   ``I don't condone what he's doing, but I don't like to see his
career ruined over it,'' said Tom Calder, 29, an attorney. ``If he
can't do his job properly from jail, he should give it up. But it's
a shame he would have to give it up that way.''
   Dutko's 30 minutes of visiting time per week usually is reserved
for his mother, Phyllis. House Speaker Lewis Dodak and some other
colleagues also have visited.
   Like any other inmate, Dutko has unlimited phone access, as long
as the calls are local or collect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
