<FIRST>r w AM-Knauss     07-31 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Knauss,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Knauss Welcomed by Senate Committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators offered John A. Knauss a cordial
welcome on Monday and urged him to be aggressive as head of the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
   ``The average NOAA administrator has been chosen because he
could keep his mouth shut. I hope you will get excited. ...'' Sen.
Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., told the University of Rhode Island
professor.
   Knauss told the Committee on Commerce, Science and
Transportation that he hopes to press a broad ocean-coastal
initiative and to encourage research on global warming, the ozone
hole and other atmospheric problems.
   ``Never have NOAA's responsibilities been more important than
they are today. ... For an earth scientist, these are exciting
times as we try to understand and predict the ecological
consequences of the actions of the world's rapidly increasing
population,'' Knauss told the committee.
   Scientific research on the effects of the Alaskan oil spill
could last as long as five years, Knauss confirmed.
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, urged him to give close attention to
the costs of such work, with the aim of making sure that those
responsible for spills are charged for the costs.
   NOAA scientists have done an excellent job in assisting in
easing the impacts of spills in Alaska, Delaware, Texas and
elsewhere, said Stevens. But the costs for this work need to be
borne by those at fault, he added.
   Hollings said money is a major factor in this era of tight
budgets, and he indicated that he feels that the Commerce
Department _ parent agency for NOAA _ may not be aggressive enough
in seeking funds for the weather and environmental agency.
   ``You've got to be a promoter and get the public and the
endowments and particularly the administration interested in your
endeavors,'' Hollings encouraged Knauss.
   Hollings said he hopes that the nomination of Knauss to head
NOAA can be voted on this week.
   Knauss, an oceanographer, was a member of the commission that
recommended creation of NOAA nearly two decades ago.
   NOAA, with a $1 billion budget, operates the National Weather
Service, conducts climate, weather and ocean research, manages the
Sea Grant college program, and includes the National Ocean Service,
National Marine Fisheries Service, the Sea Grant college program
and National Environmental Satellite, Data and Information Service.
