<HEAD>Lone Ranger Statue Proposed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Who was that masked man?
   For 13 years it was favorite son Brace Beemer who shouted
``Hi-ho, Silver!'' as radio's Lone Ranger, and an official wants to
make sure that Oxford visitors know it.
   Village Attorney Robert Bunting has proposed an equestrian
statue honoring Beemer, who lived on a farm outside Oxford until
his death in 1965. The community, 40 miles northwest of Detroit,
already has a museum displaying a white hat, silver spurs and black
mask.
   ``It's a worthwhile American legend, and I'd like to see it
promoted,'' said Bunting, who is trying to raise $65,000 for a
bronze statue of the Lone Ranger and his horse, Silver, by Florida
sculptor Frank Varga. Bunting already has 16 $1,000 pledges.
   The Lone Ranger began its two-decade radio run in 1933,
originating from WXYZ in Detroit. Beemer played the character from
1941-54.
