<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-UN-Lebanon     07-31 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Lebanon,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Of Higgins' Death Provokes Outrage; Hostage-Taking Resolution</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon-Hostage, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Claims by Lebanese kidnappers that they
hanged U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins, a U.N. peacekeeper,
provoked ``outrage and revulsion'' today from Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   Also today, the Security Council unanimously passed a resolution
that ``condemns unequivocally all acts of hostage-taking and
abduction,'' and U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
denounced Israel's capture of a Shiite cleric.
   The Security Council was also scheduled today to extend for six
months the mandate of its peacekeepers in Lebanon, the U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon.
   Higgins' Shiite captors announced today that they carried out
their threat to hang him and issued a videotape purporting to show
his slaying.
   The U.N. chief's spokesman, Juan-Carlos Brandt, said that if the
report is confirmed, ``the secretary-general can only express his
outrage and revulsion at the fact that an innocent man serving the
United Nations in the cause of peace should be murdered in this
fashion,'' said Brandt.
   The resolution, which has been debated in private in the council
for weeks, ``demands the immediate safe release of all hostages and
abducted persons wherever and by whomever they are being held.''
   It calls on all nations to use their political influence for the
release of hostages, and urges international cooperation to
``facilitate the prevention, prosecution and punishment of all acts
of hostage-taking and abduction as manifestations of terrorism.''
   Higgins, 44, was serving as head of an observer group attached
to the U.N. peacekeeping force in south Lebanon when he was seized
Feb. 17, 1988.
   Higgins' captors, a shadowy pro-Iranian group called the
Organization of the Oppressed on Earth, accused him of spying for
the CIA.
   The kidnappers said they would hang him today unless Israel
freed Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, an influential Shiite Moslem cleric
captured by Israeli troops three days ago. Perez de Cuellar
condemned Obeid's capture.
   Obeid is the reputed spiritual leader of the Shiite Moslem
Hezbollah militia in south Lebanon, the umbrella group for factions
believed to be holding 17 foreign hostages in Lebanon, nine of them
Americans.
   Lebanese security sources and Israeli officials say Obeid played
a role in the kidnapping of Higgins last year, but Obeid denies it.
</TEXT>
