<FIRST>r p PM-NYCMayoral     07-31 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Mayoral,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koch Gains in Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch has drawn closer to
Democratic challenger David Dinkins in the mayoral race, while
support for Republican Rudolph W. Giuliani has declined, a poll has
found.
   Koch continued to be rated unfavorably by more New Yorkers than
rated him favorably in the Gallup poll conducted July 21-24 for New
York Newsday. But his approval rating rose for the first time in
the Newsday poll since December.
   For the Democratic nomination, Manhattan Borough President
Dinkins had 41 percent support to 34 percent for Koch, 7 percent
for City Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin and 4 percent for former
transit chief Richard Ravitch. Fourteen percent were undecided.
   The Dinkins-Koch split was within the margin of error of 4
points for the 671 Democrats polled. Dinkins led Koch 38-28 in a
Newsday poll in late April and early May, and 45-31 in a Daily
News-Eyewitness News poll in early July.
   Giuliani, the frontrunner for the GOP nomination, was in a
statistical dead heat with Koch in a hypothetical matchup, with 40
percent support for Koch and 37 percent for Giuliani. The former
federal prosecutor led Koch 49-33 in the early July poll and 51-27
in the April-May survey.
   Among the 1,014 registered voters in the new poll, 36 percent
approved of the way Koch was doing his job as mayor, while 44
percent disapproved. The rest had no opinion. That rating was
improved from 28-52 percent in the April-May poll. In the early
July poll, Koch's approval rating was 37-58.
   A Koch spokesman, Larry Simonberg, said the mayor's TV
advertising and campaign appearances had improved his standing.
``When people get a chance to talk with him in the flesh, the
effect is very positive for the mayor,'' Simonberg said.
   Giuliani spokesman Charles Perkins told Newsday that $8 million
in negative advertising by Republican rival Ronald Lauder had hurt
Giuliani. Giuliani led Lauder strongly nonetheless.
   The primary is Sept. 12.
</TEXT>
