<FIRST>u a PM-FiresRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0574 07-31 0903</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires Rdp, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0574,0926</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Wildfires Rage in Idaho, California, Oregon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 24 grafs to UPDATE with details of fire that destroyed
Idaho town, Army called in. PICKS UP 23rd graf pvs, `Firefighters also
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire bosses called in the Army today to help battle blazes that
have overrun a mountain hamlet in Idaho, menaced remote Oregon
ranches and destroyed thousands of acres of forest and range
elsewhere in the West.
   Hundreds of wildfires _ most caused by lightning last week _
have blackened about 90,000 acres in five states since Wednesday.
   More than 9,700 firefighters were on the lines around the
biggest blazes, said the Boise (Idaho) Interagency Fire Center, the
nation's wildfire command post.
   With firefighting forces in the West almost completely
mobilized, the agency called on the Army and crews from other
regions for reinforcements.
   Hundreds of firefighters were being flown into the command
center from Alaska, the East, Southeast and Southwest, spokesman
Ron Smith said. Soldiers from Fort Lewis, Wash., were sent to Boise
for training before being dispatched to the fire lines.
   Residents of Lowman, Idaho, were finally allowed to return to
the tiny mountain retreat today.
   A firestorm that swept through the Boise National Forest late
Saturday and early Sunday destroyed 25 structures in the town,
which has a year-round population of about 15 but attracts summer
visitors from Boise, 60 miles to the southwest.
   A combination motel, campground and convenience store was lost,
as were houses, trailer homes and outbuildings.
   ``My husband left in shorts and no shirt,'' said 70-year-old
Daisy Oliver, whose mobile home was reduced to blackened metal
scrap. ``We didn't get anything, just what we had on our backs. ...
I don't know where we'll go from here.''
   No injuries were reported in the fire, one of several big blazes
burning out of control in Idaho. The fires consumed a total of
40,000 acres of forest and range and were being fought today by
4,000 firefighters.
   The Oregon fire, near Baker and about 50 miles from the Idaho
state line, grew from about 5,000 acres on Saturday to at least
17,000 acres today. It was one of five major fires out of control
in eastern Oregon.
   ``You look out the window here and there's columns of smoke in
every direction,'' Kathy Aplin, spokeswoman for the Oregon
Department of Forestry in Baker, said Sunday evening.
   About 30 families were evacuated Saturday night, but all but 10
were allowed to return today. Gusts to 22 mph threatened to spread
flames to those homes, said Kathy Aplin, spokeswoman for the Oregon
Department of Forestry.
   Ranchers cut fences and opened gates to let their cattle and
sheep escape as flames threatened grazing lands, said Ken Dunleavy,
a spokesman for the Baker County sheriff.
   ``They're trying to get their livestock out of there like
crazy,'' he said.
   About 1,200 firefighters battled the fire. An air tanker dropped
fire retardant on one ranch home, and a bulldozer plowed a
firebreak through the front yard of another.
   Some 2,000 firefighters fought at least four other major forest
fires and several smaller blazes in eastern Oregon. A 1,300-acre
fire threatened the watershed that is the main water supply for La
Grande, a community of 11,000 in northeastern Oregon. In all, fire
burned about 42,000 acres in Oregon in recent days.
   In the central Sierra Nevada foothills of California,
investigators said an arsonist lit a fire that has raged out of
control for three days, destroying seven homes and filling the area
around Auberry with thick smoke.
   The blaze, dubbed the Powerhouse fire, about 200 miles east of
San Francisco, also destroyed 16 outbuildings and scorched 11,350
tinder-dry acres.
   By late Sunday, about 1,900 firefighters had encircled 60
percent of the blaze and expected containment by evening. Three
firefighters were injured, none seriously.
   Some of the 2,500 people forced to evacuate were allowed back in
their homes. Many roads remained closed.
   A fire in the Balch Camp area, 15 to 20 miles southeast of the
Powerhouse fire, had blackened about 23,000 acres since it flared
up Saturday. It was only 5 percent contained Sunday but threatened
no buildings in the remote wildland area on rough terrain, said
U.S. Forest Service spokeswoman Becky Armstrong.
   In southern California, a 5,700-acre wildfire in the Cleveland
National Forest raged out of control early today, but a 1,200-acre
brush fire about 30 miles northwest of Los Angeles that had earlier
forced 100 people was brought under control.
   The Los Angeles County fire on Sunday burned a hog farm that had
previously been used as a toxic waste dump.
   Firefighters also mopped up a stubborn 10,500-acre wildfire near
Atascadero, in central California, that had burned since late last
week. It was expected to be controlled sometime today.
   About 900 firefighters saved 13 homes and structures in the
Cleveland forest blaze Sunday, said U.S. Forest Service spokeswoman
Rosalinda Ewen. A house and a trailer were destroyed.
   In Washington, a forest fire in the northern Cascade mountains
was held to 800 acres Sunday. Firefighters reported the blaze in
the Okanogan National Forest 55 percent contained, said U.S. Forest
Service spokesman Greg Thayer.
   In western Montana, near the Idaho state line, lightning set
several dozen small fires over the weekend. The largest blaze, near
the Idaho border, grew to about 60 acres overnight, forest
dispatcher Nick Nicholson said today.
</TEXT>
