<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--LexingtonEditor     07-31 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Lexington Editor,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lexington Newspaper Names Executive Editor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tim Kelly, managing editor of the Orange
County (Calif.) Register since 1987, will become executive editor
of the Lexington Herald-Leader, said John S. Carroll, editor of the
Lexington newspaper.
   Kelly, 41, will oversee day-to-day news coverage beginning next
month.
   Kelly began his career at the Ashland Daily Independent in the
mid-1960s. He was executive sports editor of the Philadelphia
Inquirer in the early 1970s.
   From 1975 to 1984, he worked for Times Mirror Newspapers. He was
news editor, assistant managing editor and deputy managing editor
of the Dallas Times Herald. He was later managing editor of The
Denver Post.
   Kelly was editor of the Daily News in Los Angeles from 1984 to
1987.
   Kelly, an Ashland native, said he was looking forward to
returning to Kentucky. ``It's something that I have been attempting
to do off and on for the past 14 years, so obviously I'm thrilled
about it,'' Kelly said.
   Kelly succeeds Joel Rawson, who left the Herald-Leader this
month to become deputy executive editor of the Providence (R.I.)
Journal-Bulletin.
</TEXT>
