<FIRST>r a BC-FreedHostages     07-31 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Freed Hostages,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Since 1984, Five American Hostages Have Been Freed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Hostages Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Besides eight Americans still held
hostage and at least two who were killed, five other Americans were
kidnapped in Lebanon over the past 5{ years and eventually gained
their freedom.
   Here is a brief review:
   _Frank Regier, an engineering professor at the American
University of Beirut, was abducted Feb. 10, 1984, near the west
Beirut campus. On April 15, 1984, he and another kidnap victim,
Christian Joubert, a French housing specialist, were freed. Members
of Lebanon's Shiite Amal militia said they had rescued the pair,
but the circumstances of their release and the identity of their
captors were never made clear.
   _Jeremy Levin, Beirut bureau chief for Cable News Network, was
kidnapped March 7, 1984, as he walked to work in west Beirut. The
pro-Iranian group Islamic Jihad claimed responsibility. On Feb. 14,
1985, Levin turned up in Damascus, Syria, and said he had escaped
from solitary confinement in east Lebanon's Bekaa Valley. But
Islamic Jihad asserted it actually had released the TV
correspondent.
   _Presbyterian pastor Benjamin Weir was kidnapped May 8, 1984, on
a west Beirut street. On Sept. 9, 1985, Weir was freed by his
Islamic Jihad captors, bearing a message calling for urgent U.S.
action to meet demands for the release of 17 Islamic Jihad comrades
jailed in Kuwait for the December 1983 bombing of the U.S. and
French embassies there.
   _The Rev. Lawrence Jenco, a Roman Catholic priest, was abducted
from his car in Beirut on Jan. 8, 1985. He was released by Islamic
Jihad on July 26, 1986, bringing with him a videotape in which
fellow hostage David P. Jacobsen appealed for the U.S. government
to negotiate with the kidnappers.
   _David P. Jacobsen, American director of American University
Hospital, was kidnapped May 28, 1985, as he walked to work in west
Beirut. He was released by Islamic Jihad on Nov. 2, 1986.
Jacobsen's release led to disclosures that the Reagan
administration had been negotiating for the hostages' freedom and
had arranged secret arms shipments to Iran, a development that
provoked a political storm in Washington that became known as the
Iran-Contra affair.
   In addition, over the past 5{ years at least 34 other
foreigners, including French, West German and British nationals,
have been kidnapped in Lebanon and either were freed, escaped or
were rescued.
</TEXT>
