<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1544EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     07-31 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is a surgeon on the mound, a
pediatrician and neonatologist in the outfield and a lung
specialist with a bulletlike throw at shortstop. On the bench are a
cellular phone and a dozen beepers.
   The ball players are members of the ``the Dox,'' a softball team
of 13 doctors from Memorial Hospital in South Bend.
   So far this season, the Dox have shown more brains than brawn,
with a record of 5-7.
   But winning's not the point.
   ``It's a pressure relief valve. We're coming to have a good
time. We try to avoid getting hurt. We really don't expect to win,
but when we do it's a bonus,'' said Dr. Robert White, a
neonatologist who was exhausted during a recent game because he was
up most of the night delivering a baby.
   The Dox have come a long way from their first season in 1982,
when they finished 1-15 and were widely hailed as the worst team in
South Bend's worst softball league.
   The Dox never practice during the season and their only
preseason drill consists of the team captain hitting balls to a
couple of players.
   ``It's no lie that for many guys the first ball they hit in a
year is the first ball that's pitched to them the first game of the
season,'' said Dr. Joe Caruso, the team captain and a
family-practice physician.
   Team practice is impractical, he explained, because of the
doctors' busy schedules.
   And thanks to the beepers and the cellular phone, the Dox
occasionally have to forfeit a game when their bench loses too many
players who must respond to emergencies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWBURYPORT, Mass (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Usually, they are ashamed. But scores
of people with unusually smelly feet turned out for a contest to
see whose sneakers were the most disgusting of all.
   Herbert ``Buddy'' Lapidus, head of research for Combe Inc.,
developer of Odor-Eaters shoe inserts and corporate sponsor of the
event, said he was looking for sneakers that would satisfy his
``10-foot formula.''
   ``If I can smell them from 10 feet away, they're in the running;
15 feet, a definite contender; 20 feet, a ferocious shoe-in,'' he
said.
   The winner of Sunday's contest was 13-year-old Jason Koch of
Salisbury, who brought the pair of sneakers he wears while riding
his dirt bike on hot summer days.
   ``They were filthy, rotten, dirty, full of holes and they stunk
really bad,'' said Joan Martin, co-chairwoman of the event.
   Lapidus said the panel of three judges consisted of true experts
in rotten sneakers: a mother, a junior high school athletic coach,
and a dog.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WAYNESBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The weather didn't cooperate with the
spirit of the festivities, but residents put up with the sunshine
and 80-degree temperature to celebrate their annual ``Rain Day.''
   Rain has fallen on July 29 in 94 out of the past 114 years in
Waynesburg, a community of 5,000 about 35 miles south of
Pittsburgh. Of the rainless Rain Days, six occurred in the last
seven years, said Melody Longstreth, executive secretary of the
local Chamber of Commerce, which helps organize the celebration.
   Saturday's festivities included a rain dance, an umbrella
contest and a 113-foot-long banana split.
