<FIRST>u a PM-RoseInvestigation 1stLd-Writethru a0619 07-31 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rose Investigation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0619,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rose Dealt a Setback, Case to Be Decided in Federal Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last two grafs pvs, `Rose has ...' with 7 grafs with lawyers'
comment, background, appeal expected. A version also moved on sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pete Rose suffered a setback today when a
federal judge decided his lawsuit against baseball Commissioner A.
Bartlett Giamatti belongs in federal court.
   U.S. District Judge John D. Holschuh refused to return Rose's
case to Hamilton County Common Pleas Court, where Rose had won an
order tying Giamatti's hands in deciding whether the Cincinnati
Reds manager bet on ballgames.
   Baseball wanted the case heard in federal court, where judges
have upheld the commissioner's broad powers in previous legal
challenges.
   Rose had asked that the matter be kept in Common Pleas Court in
the Reds' hometown, where Judge Norbert A. Nadel has shown a
willingness to go into what he termed ``uncharted waters'' in
making his decisions.
   ``It's certainly a victory that puts the case in the right
court,'' said Louis L. Hoynes Jr., baseball's chief lawyer. ``One
hopes that we can dispose of the case now.''
   Rose has been accused of betting on his own team, an offense
that could get him banned from baseball for life. But Nadel ruled
that Giamatti had already made up his mind against Rose and could
not give him a fair disciplinary hearing.
   Holschuh's decision takes the case away from Nadel. Holschuh
also extended until at least Aug. 14 Rose's protection against
firing or suspension over the gambling allegations.
   The judge scheduled a hearing for that day on whether to extend
the proection indefinitely.
   Rose's lawyers were expected to appeal to the 6th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Cincinnati.
   Baseball's lawyers accused Rose of trying to have the case
decided in the court that is ``most subject to the influence of
local pressures produced by his fame, notoriety and close
identification with the city of Cincinnati.''
</TEXT>
