<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan 3rdLd-Writethru a0609 07-31 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0609,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockets Pound Capital, 21 Die; Guerrillas Say Rivals Kill 59</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with dead at 21, new government-rebel
fighting reported; CORRECT bicycle factory to auto workshop; pickup graf
19 pvs `In Stockholm...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barrage of rockets hit a hospital, a
crowded bus stop and an auto repair shop today in the capital,
killing 21 people and injuring at least 22, the government and
hospital sources said.
   In Islamabad, Pakistan, a guerrilla radio official said one
guerrilla faction attacked a rival guerrilla group and killed 59
people, mostly women and children. No date was given for the
attack, which the purported attackers denied.
   In Stockholm, Sweden, U.S. and Soviet delegations began two days
of talks on Afghanistan. It was the first superpower meeting on the
10-year Afghan war since the last Soviet troops, who were allied
with the Kabul government, left the country Feb. 15.
   U.S.-backed guerrillas are fighting to overthrow the
Soviet-backed Marxist government.
   Some homes were also hit today in the shower of 14 rockets,
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said.
   Amani said nine people were killed and 22 injured in separate
attacks at Avicenna Hospital, its auto workshop and a nearby bus
stop. But hospital officials put the total killed in those three
attacks at 17 and said four other people died elsewhere.
   The casualties raised to at least 200 the number of people
killed in rocket attacks on the capital this month.
   Amani on Saturday accused the guerrillas of increasing rocket
attacks on Kabul to ``have something in their hand'' for the start
of U.S.-Soviet talks on Afghanistan in Stockholm today.
   Soviet troops withdrew from Afghanistan this year under a
U.N.-sponsored accord after a nine-year intervention to prop up the
pro-Soviet regime.
   In Islamabad, Qaribur Rehman Saeed, who runs the
rebel-controlled Afghan News Agency, said the Jamiat-e-Islami
guerrilla group attacked the village of Qochi Quba in the northern
Afghan province of Kunduz. He said they killed four rival field
commanders as well as 55 women and children.
   ``They surrounded the village and just began shooting with heavy
artillery and missiles,'' he said. He gave no date for the attack,
which could not be independently confirmed.
   He said the slain field commanders were from the rival
Hezb-e-Islami faction.
   However, Mohammad Shaoib, a spokesman for Jamiat in the
Pakistani city of Peshawar, said, ``We think this is baseless. ...
We haven't heard anything.''
   Amani also said today that government troops ambushed an enemy
ammunition convoy southeast of Jalalabad, killing 75 guerrillas and
injuring 112. He gave no date for the attack.
   In Stockholm, the U.S delegation was led by Assistant Secretary
of State John Kelly. The Soviet delegation was headed by Ambassador
Nicolai Kozyrev.
   An American official in Washington said the Soviet arms supply
to the ruling communists in Kabul will dominate discussions.
   Officials in Stockholm said no issues other than Afghanistan
were on the agenda. However, Jim Borup, a U.S. Embassy spokesman,
did not rule out the possibility that other issues might come up.
   An American official in Washington said Friday the United States
would ask the Soviets for help in trying to win the release of
Americans held hostage in Lebanon by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems.
   In Islamabad, the Afghan rebels' government-in-exile said
Washington should not make any agreements at the Stockholm talks.
   Rasul Sayyaf, prime minister of the government-in-exile, said in
a statement to the Afghan News Agency, ``Neither of the two
superpowers can dictate their policies to us.''
</TEXT>
