<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1907EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ChineseStudents     07-31 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chinese Students,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Approves Bill Allowing Students to Forestall Return to China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a new reaction to China's crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators in June, the House on Monday approved a
measure that would allow thousands of Chinese students in the
United States to forestall their return to their homeland.
   The measure, adopted by voice vote, was sent to the Senate for
further action.
   The legislation would affect 32,000 of the 40,000 Chinese
students in the United States, those who hold ``exchange visitor''
visas. Those visas require students to return to China for at least
two years following their time in the United States before being
able to return or go elsewhere.
   They are intended primarily for promising students whose
educations are funded by the government, in an effort to address
the ``brain drain'' problem.
   The bill, sponsored by Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., would waive
the requirement that they return home for two years.
   Passage of the measure followed the addition by the House of
several sanctions against China to a foreign aid bill a month ago.
   Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn., chairman of the House Judiciary
immigration subcommittee, acknowledged that the legislation carries
with it a risk that the Chinese government will curtail student
exchanges.
   ``But the people who govern China need to understand the
principles of liberty and democracy in action,'' he said. ``All we
are doing is saying that if the People's Republic of China wishes
these students to come home it must do so by bringing them back by
its own behavior. It must be a voluntary return, not one forced by
the laws of the United States.''
</TEXT>
