<FIRST>r a AM-GovernorsReax     07-31 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Governors Reax,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governors Voice Complaints With President</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's governors on Monday welcomed
President Bush's call to meet with him this fall on education, even
as they pressed concerns about spending on transportation and
Medicaid.
   Bush formally announced plans for a summit on education with the
governors in late September during an appearance before the annual
meeting of the National Governors' Association. The meeting on
education was one of several the governors had asked for in a
private meeting with the president in May.
   ``We're impressed with the accessiblity and indications of a
cooperative attitude'' from Bush, said Virginia Gov. Gerald
Baliles, a Democrat and chairman of the governors association.
   Democrat Bill Clinton of Arkansas said the summit will keep
education and child-related issues on the public agenda.
   But Ohio Gov. Richard Celeste, a Democrat who has indicated
presidential ambitions, said Bush's remarks were too little
considering Bush's campaign claim to be ``the education president.''
   ``I thought it was a rather uninspired and uninspiring
presentation of the president's priorities, with which no one is
going to disagree,'' Celeste said in an interview. ``It lacked any
real vision or any real voltage in terms of getting us moving now.''
   Celeste said one issue in the education meeting would be what he
said was a dampening effect on state and local education
initiatives created by the budget climate and Bush's flat
opposition to new taxes.
   ``The president's posture last year in the election really
chilled efforts at education reform and education finance in many
parts of this country,'' Celeste said. ``The president is in a
unique position to sound the trumpet _ and I didn't hear any brass
this morning.''
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the Democratic presidential
nominee who lost to Bush last year, shook hands with Bush and spoke
briefly. But to reporters, Dukakis complained about ``Washington's
inability to deal with this deficit'' and pointed to his own tax
increases and budget cuts in Massachusetts.
   ``I had to cut and cut deeply,'' Dukakis said.
   ``Governors will tell you we'll do everything we can to try to
help Congress and the administraion deal with it _ but we've been
doing that since 1983,'' Dukakis said.
   Governors of both parties met in private over breakfast before
Bush's address, and several governors said later that the major
concern voiced in the meeting was federal Medicaid requirements
that force states to spend more on health care, without
compensation from the federal government. Those so-called mandates
include requirements for additional types of coverage.
   In a question-and-answer session with Bush, Celeste asked the
president to consider a two-year moratorium on additional Medicaid
mandates, which he later described as the fastest growing spending
item in his state budget.
   Bush did not commit himself to such a moratorium but said: ``I'd
like to consider it, and certainly we're trying to hold the line on
spiraling costs.''
   Bush and Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner, who later
addressed the governors, both suggested they were sympathetic with
the governors on the issue of surplus federal transportation trust
funds, another major concern the governors voiced during the
meeting.
   The trust funds for highways and airport facilities contain as
much as $19 billion, according to governors, who contend much of
that is not obligated to specific projects and is being withheld
from the states so it can count against the deficit in the federal
budget.
   ``I know the frustration around this table,'' Bush said, ``when
you see this tremendous highway trust fund and wonder why those
funds aren't immediately available for the purposes for which they
are earmarked. The answer obviously is budgetary.''
   Baliles said he pressed the point with Skinner in private.
Skinner drew applause later when he voiced sympathy and suggested
that Congress was to blame _ without promising any money.
   Baliles said later that the issue was ``being discussed at
different levels.'' But Celeste complained, ``It seems to me we
have a long way to go to get to the point where we have the money
we need.''
</TEXT>
