<FIRST>r a AM-SwallowedEvidence     07-31 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swallowed Evidence,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Suspect Gave Up Evidence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILKINSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say the stolen evidence was
within sight _ on the X-ray of the suspect's stomach _ and the only
question was how to recover the two diamond rings.
   So R.C. Wright, 29, of Pittsburgh, decided to ``regurgitate the
rings'' Sunday night, said Officer Robert Tuite. ``It was voluntary
on his part.''
   Police who responded to a report of a break-in at a house
ordered the intruder to surrender, and he eventually did,
authorities said.
   The homeowner said a .32-caliber revolver and two rings _ a
half-carat diamond ring worth about $600 and a smaller diamond ring
worth about $300 _ were missing, police said. They found the
pistol, but concluded their suspect must have swallowed the rings,
authorities said.
   Police got a search warrant and took Wright to a hospital, where
X-rays showed the rings clearly, police said.
   Police said doctors said the rings could be recovered through
stomach pumping or surgery or by waiting for him to pass them.
   ``As it turned out, he knew that things weren't going to be all
that comfortable for him anyway, so he decided to cough them up,''
said Sgt. Dan Rearick. ``He just said, `Wait a minute.' Then he
coughed up the rings.''
   Rearick said the suspect handed the rings to police.
   Wright was arraigned Sunday night on charges of burglary,
criminal attempt, possession of an instrument of crime, recklessly
endangering another person and a firearms violation.
   He was being held in the Allegheny County Jail on $25,000 bail,
authorities said.
</TEXT>
