<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1659EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People     07-31 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty years after he helped launch the
Newport Folk Festival, Pete Seeger returned to lead fans in singing
his familiar repertoire of folk classics and protest songs.
   Some of the 5,500 people who heard the 70-year-old singer at the
close of the two-day festival Sunday remembered his first
appearance there in 1959.
   The music hasn't changed much, said Joe Salviulo, 48, of
Southbridge Mass. But the audience has.
   ``Everybody was a little bit more spaced-out back then,''
Salviulo recalled. ``It was more like Woodstock. This is like a
Sunday in the park in comparison.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LUCERNE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irish flautist James Galway offered
a reward Monday for the return of five stolen gold flutes, three of
which are studded with diamonds.
   The musician said he hopes the thief will have trouble selling
the distinctive instruments, which disappeared Wednesday from a
railway station along with luggage he was unloading.
   ``It's like somebody trying to sell a Formula One car,'' Galway
said. ``Of course it can be sold but you have to find somebody who
is not going to drive in the Indianapolis 500, otherwise it would
be spotted immediately.''
   Four of the flutes were 14-carat gold, one was 9-carat gold and
three had diamonds in the end. Galway, who values the instruments
at about $30,000 each, said he would pay a reward of 10 percent for
their return.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRAINERD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steve Hall, the voice of the mustachioed
television puppet Shotgun Red, wants $50,000 from his manager and a
toy maker in a dispute over Shotgun Red dolls.
   Hall's demand comes in response to a lawsuit that accused him of
defrauding the manager and manufacturer in deals involving
promotional items based on Shotgun Red.
   Hall is the voice and operator of the puppet, which plays host
to country music shows on The Nashville Network programming carried
by cable TV companies around the country and has appeared on ``Hee
Haw'' and other shows.
   Hall's manager, Richard Davis, and Greg Knox of Creative
Marketing Services of Madison, Tenn., sued Hall in Crow Wing
County, Minn., District Court, seeking $175,000 in the dispute.
   In a counterclaim filed recently, Hall says Davis competed with
him by selling Shotgun Red dolls and other items in violation of
the licensing agreement. He says he and his wife, Daisy, are owed
$175,000 for Shotgun Red dolls and other items.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School board members aren't sure they want
actor Rob Lowe giving anti-drug lectures in classrooms under a
court-ordered community-service sentence.
   ``We will want a guarantee for the parents of our children that
children are protected,'' said Los Angeles Unified School District
board President Jackie Goldberg. ``It appears on the surface he
has, at minimum, dubious judgment.''
   Lowe, 25, was accused of sexual exploitation of a minor after he
allegedly videotaped sexual encounters with a 16-year-old girl in
an Atlanta hotel room in 1988.
   On Friday, the actor agreed with the Fulton County Court in
Georgia to perform 20 hours of community service, warning high
school students of the dangers of drugs. The agreement _ made under
a special program for young first offenders _ spares the star of
``St. Elmo's Fire'' and other movies of being charged in the case,
and he doesn't admit guilt.
   Fulton County District Attorney Lewis R. Slaton suggested Lowe
speak in high schools in Los Angeles, where he lives, and in Ohio,
his home state.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mick Jagger's Rolling Stones changed their
North American tour schedule Monday so the band will begin its
travels with a concert in Philadelphia rather than in Buffalo, N.Y.
   The Stones were originally to appear at Philadelphia's John F.
Kennedy Stadium on Sept. 21 _ well after the opening concert set
for Sept. 1 in Buffalo. But the Philadelphia stop was canceled when
the city closed the stadium for safety reasons.
   Another change was made and the Stones will now open the tour
with a pair of concerts Aug. 31 and Sept. 1 at Philadelphia's
Veterans Stadium, said Joe Owens of Concert Productions
International, the Toronto-based promoter of the tour.
   That forced cancellation of the Buffalo concert, said Owens, who
promised: ``Several special options to accommodate Buffalo fans are
in the works and an announcement is expected shortly.''
