<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-31 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockets Kill 21 in Kabul; U.S.-Soviet Talks Begin in Stockholm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen rockets struck Kabul Monday,
killing 21 people and wounding 58 at a U.S.-built hospital, a bus
stop, an auto repair shop and several homes, hospital officials
reported.
   In Stockholm, U.S. and Soviet officials began talks on the
Afghan civil war between Washington-backed anti-communist
guerrillas and Afghanistan's Marxist government supported by Moscow.
   Afghan Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said nine
people were killed and 22 injured by rockets that hit the Avicenna
Chest Hospital, the hospital's auto shop and a nearby bus stop. But
hospital officials put the total killed in those three attacks at
17 and said four people were killed in other attacks.
   Rocket explosions could be heard in Kabul throughout the day and
Amani said some of the missiles fell in the diplomatic quarter and
on houses in the old city and western Kabul.
   ``Again today misery-stricken Kabul city is victim of severe
rocket attacks by the brutal extremists,'' Amani said.
   No group cliamed responsibility for the latest attacks but
guerrillas have acknowledged previous attacks on the capital.
   Amani on Saturday claimed the guerrillas, who call themselves
mujahedeen or Islamic holy warriors, were increasing rocket attacks
on Kabul to ``have something in their hand'' when the U.S.-Soviet
talks started in Stockholm.
   United Nations sources said that from June 25 to July 30,
rockets killed 257 people and injured 687 in Kabul.
   Amani said an average of 15 rockets were being fired daily into
the capital, most by remote control or timers, from mountains,
villages and wooded areas where they are difficult to detect. He
said some rockets had been found in search operations in northern
Kabul.
   The summer school vacation, which lasts about two weeks and was
scheduled to end July 29, has been extended for two weeks because
of the rocketing, Amani said.
   He said that in recent weeks rockets hit seven schools and if
classes had been in session ``the number of victims would have been
much higher.''
   Elsewhere, Amani said government troops ambushed an enemy
ammunition convoy southeast of Jalalabad, killing 75 guerrillas and
wounding 112. Large quantities of arms and ammunition were seized
and destroyed, he said.
   The report could not be independently confirmed. Both sides in
the war have been known to inflate casualty figures.
   Jalalabad, 75 miles east of Kabul and 45 miles west of the
Pakistani border, has been the scene of fierce fighting since the
withdrawal of the last of 110,000 Soviet troops on Feb. 15. The
guerrillas have been repulsed twice in their attempts to take the
city.
</TEXT>
