<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     07-31 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Who Met Shamir Threatened by Radicals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall slogans have appeared in the occupied West
Bank, threatening a Palestinian lawyer who held talks with Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel.
   The lawyer said he also has been threatened by someone he
believes to be an Israeli extremist.
   In the Israeli-occupied lands, two Palestinian youths were shot
to death Monday in stone-throwing clashes with Israeli troops. In
Jerusalem, a Palestinian laborer stabbed and wounded his foreman, a
Jewish settler.
   The Palestinian attorney, Jamil Tarifi, of the West Bank town of
Ramallah, said last week he recently met with Shamir. The prime
minister has held a series of meetings with Palestinians from the
occupied territories, but Tarifi is the only one who has
acknowledged attending the sessions.
   Israel is trying to find Palestinians with no links to the
Palestine Liberation Organization who will cooperate with its plan
to hold elections on limited autonomy for the occupied territories.
   Late last year, Bethlehem Mayor Elias Freij was threatened by
PLO officials, including group leader Yasser Arafat, forcing him to
back off from his call for a one-year suspension of the Palestinian
uprising in the occupied lands.
   Slogans painted in black on walls in the West Bank town of
Ramallah condemned the meeting between Shamir and Tarifi.
   ``A meeting with Shamir is a bullet shot in the back of the
intefadeh,'' or Palestinian uprising, one said. ``Shame on Jamil
Tarifi and all those who meet the murderers of our people,''
another read.
   Tarifi, 42, said one wall message was signed by the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a Marxist faction of the PLO
led by George Habash.
   The group wants to escalate the 19-month Palestinian rebellion
in the occupied lands and rejects what it views as compromise
offers to Israel from PLO chairman Yasser Arafat, who leads the
PLO's mainstream Fatah wing.
   ``There are political differences between the mainstream in the
PLO and the PFLP,'' Tarifi said. But he said he was not sure the
threats actually came from the Marxist faction.
   ``It is sufficient for me that Yasser Arafat and (Fatah's No. 2
man) Salah Khalaf and the great majority of Palestinians backed my
meeting with Shamir,'' he said.
   Shamir said Monday that any threat ``is regrettable.'' He added
that Palestinian extremists were ``trying to prevent Palestinians
from speaking openly.''
   Tarifi said he also was threatened by an anonymous phone caller
whom he described as an Israeli extremist.
   ``An Israeli speaking Hebrew mixed with broken Arabic told me
yesterday and the day before that my life is at risk,'' he said.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, 15-year-old Mahmoud Yasin Saraj was
fatally shot in the neck by Israeli soldiers during a confrontation
with Israeli soldiers in the Bureij refugee camp, Arab reporters
said.
   In the Balata refugee camp in the occupied West Bank, police on
patrol opened fire when they were stoned, killing 12-year-old
Sultan Mohammed Abu Musallem, Palestinian journalists said.
   The army confirmed both deaths and said paramilitary border
police opened fire on Abu Musallem after he threw a cinderblock at
a policeman.
   The deaths raised to 527 the number of Palestinians killed by
Israeli troops and settlers since the Palestinian uprising began.
Thirty-eight Israelis have also died.
   Hospital officials also said Monday that at least 15
Palestinians suffered gunshot wounds over the previous 24 hours in
clashes around the occupied territories.
   In Jerusalem, a 28-year-old Palestinian laborer from the West
Bank village of Bir Zeit was accused of stabbing his Jewish foreman
and then fleeing, police said.
   The foreman, Eliezer Sobol, was treated at Jerusalem's Hadassah
Hospital for wounds that included chest cuts and a ripped muscle.
Police said they detained Mohammed Awad Shartah in Ramallah on
suspicion of stabbing Sobol, 39.
   ``It was a worker who has been with me since 1982-83. He came
into my office and said, `I can't come to work tomorrow.' When I
asked him why, he took out a knife and stabbed me,'' Sobol told
Israel radio.
</TEXT>
