<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Shopping     07-31 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Shopping,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Polish Consumers: Bare Shelves, Long Lines</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The scene was bleak at Food Store No. 68
at 12:30 p.m. Monday.
   There was no bread, little milk, no flour, no cheese. The meager
daily deliveries had been sold out.
   ``Maybe there's a war coming,'' said one shopper after walking
in, looking at the bare shelves, and walking out.
   ``I haven't had any breakfast because I couldn't get any
bread,'' complained an office worker.
   ``We will have some bread later,'' the shop attendant in the
state-owned store said. He had no answer when he was asked when.
   ``And I'll end up eating my breakfast together with supper,''
said a woman who left.
   There were a few things left to buy in the store: Ketchup and
bottled beets, fruit preserves, yogurt, four jars of a sour milk
beverage called kefir, hard candy, cocoa and a few packages of
pretzel sticks.
   One woman said it was fortunate her family was on vacation in
the countryside, where supplies were a little more abundant. All
she had found to put in her shopping basket Monday was kefir and a
head of cauliflower.
   ``I'll be on a diet,'' she said.
   Food shortages have become more widespread in Poland in recent
months. Monday, many more shoppers than usual came out to buy goods
before price controls are lifted Tuesday and prices soar under a
controversial government program.
   Meat rationing is also being abolished, meaning families will no
longer have the right to buy 5.5 pounds of meat per person monthly
at relatively low, government-subsidized prices. Consumers have had
to stand several hours in line waiting for meat deliveries.
   The government has blamed the shortages on decisions by Poland's
mainly private farmers to cut meat and grain deliveries to the
state this summer. The farmers have said the deliveries are
unprofitable because the prices the government pays are too low.
   As meat became scarce, consumers bought more dairy products,
fish and flour, which they use to make dumplings for meatless
meals. Sugar also is in short supply because it is used in
preserving the season's fruit for later in the year.
   Under the new program intended to improve supplies, farmers are
to be freed to sell their produce to whoever they want at whatever
prices they can get.
   Government food subsidies will remain stable, however.
State-owned stores and food processors are supposed to pass their
added purchasing costs to consumers.
   Politburo member Wladyslaw Baka, who opposed introducing the
program at this time, estimated it could raise prices 300 to 400
percent.
   ``I don't care what the prices are anymore,'' said a teacher who
refused to stand in a three-hour line for bread at another Warsaw
shop. ``Let them raise them. I simply want to be able to buy what I
need.''
   But other consumers were worried about price increases.
   ``If I make from 24,000 to 30,000 (zloties a month or about $29
to $36), I can't even dream of buying better meat or a piece of
ham,'' said one elderly woman interviewed on state television.
   The average monthly wage in Poland is about $127 dollars. On the
private market, meat can cost up to $4.30 a pound.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
