<FIRST>r w AM-CatastrophicIllness     07-31 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic Illness,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fawell Changing Plans in Attempt to Gain House Action</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman said Monday he is changing plans
in a bid to gain more support for House action on his proposal to
delay implementation of major parts of the Medicare catastrophic
health program.
   The delay bill introduced by Rep. Harris W. Fawell, R-Ill., is
among various measures in Congress to revise or repeal the Medicare
expansion which is being phased in over the three years that
started Jan. 1.
   However, Fawell is the only legislator who has filed a formal
petition to force his bill directly onto the House floor rather
than going through the Ways and Means Committee, which deals with
such legislation.
   His parliamentary maneuver requires 218 signatures to succeed,
enough to pass a bill on the House floor.
   In what he said was largely an appeal to fellow members, Fawell
held a news conference to announce that he was revising the
proposed rule of action, under which his legislation would be taken
up, to specifically allow for four amendments to be debated on the
House floor.
   Fawell said he hoped that would encourage House members to sign
his petition to gain full debate of the issue even if they don't
necessarily support his call for a one-year delay.
