<FIRST>u w AM-Higgins-Relatives 1stLd-Writethru a0664 07-31 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Higgins-Relatives, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0664,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wife Says She Doesn't Know Whether Reports of Higgins' Death Are
True</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs last 3 grafs with 11 to update with comment by hostage
sister Peggy Say and Higgins relatives.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Higgins, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robin Higgins, wife of Marine Lt. Col. William
R. Higgins, said Monday reports from Lebanon that her husband had
been executed were ``not pleasant'' but she did not know whether
they are true.
   President Bush told Mrs. Higgins that ``reports concerning
Rich's death are not confirmed,'' she said in a statement released
by her attorney, Gregory Craig.
   ``One thing I have learned over the past 17 months is that the
truth is hard to find, and it remains so,'' said Mrs. Higgins, 37,
who is a major in the Marine Corps and works at the Pentagon as a
public information officer.
   Mrs. Higgins did not come to work Monday, but arrived at the
building at midmorning with Higgins' 19-year-old daughter, Chrissy.
They remained secluded, out of reporters' sight.
   In her office, Mrs. Higgins' co-workers anxiously watched
television monitors for the latest news from Lebanon.
   In Chicago, Bush canceled plans to travel to Nevada and
Oklahoma, and returned to Washington to deal with the situation.
   ``I have been contacted by President Bush, who has offered his
personal support during this time of trial for the Higgins
family,'' Mrs. Higgins said, adding that Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney had also pledged his support.
   Bush described Mrs. Higgins as a ``stoic individual who is going
through sheer hell.''
   ``Needless to say, the news from Beirut is not pleasant,'' Mrs.
Higgins said. ``I must, however, await confirmation. I have seen
the reports and have not reached any conclusion myself.'' She urged
Americans not to draw any premature conclusions ``during this
terrible time of uncertainty.''
   Television networks broadcast a videotape Monday showing
pictures of a dead body purporting to be that of Higgins, 44.
Higgins is one of nine Americans held hostage by pro-Iranian Shiite
Moslems in Lebanon.
   Peggy Say, the sister of another Lebanon hostage, Associated
Press Correspondent Terry Anderson, urged American officials to
respond cautiously to Higgins' reported death.
   ``What we have witnessed, in the Israeli retaliation in kind for
the kidnapping of their people, (is) that violence truly does beget
violence and that I hope the United States will use this
opportunity for reconciliation rather than retaliation,'' Mrs. Say
said in an interview from her home near Cadiz, Ky.
   ``An eye for an eye only leaves both sides blind.''
   In her statement, Mrs. Higgins appealed to those holding Higgins
to ``put an end to this needless cycle of violence and
victimization by releasing my husband right now and sending him
home.''
   Craig said Mrs. Higgins wanted to be left alone by reporters and
he urged outsiders to show ``respect for the Higgins' privacy.''
   Cheney's spokesman, Pete Williams, said Mrs. Higgins met with
the defense secretary on Saturday at the Pentagon before both spoke
to a group of families whose relatives who are prisoners of war or
are missing in Southeast Asia.
   Higgins' sister, Mary Fisher, said from her home in the
Louisville, Ky., suburb of Okolona that she believed Higgins'
probably was dead even before she saw the videotape. ``How can I
doubt it,'' she said.
   Mrs. Fisher said she had spoken with officials with the State
Department but would not reveal what she was told.
   Higgins' aunt, Leona Huffman, awaited some official confirmation
at her home in Lancaster, Ky.
   ``I'm just not going to believe anything until I hear direct,''
said Mrs. Huffman, sister of the colonel's late mother.
</TEXT>
