<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Customs,0107</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customs Chief Says Book Restrictions to be Loosened</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bibles and books written by Soviet emigres will no
longer be barred from entry to the Soviet Union as of Aug. 15,
customs chief Vitaly Boyarov said Monday.
   The new customs regulations will bar only publications
containing pornography or advocating overthrow of the Soviet
government, Boyarov said. Objects of religious cults will be
permitted free entry, without customs duties or quantitative limits.
   The Soviet Union has begun publishing many of the banned books
of Soviet authors, and even Alexander Solzhenitsyn's ``The Gulag
Archipelago'' is due for printing in a magazine soon.
