<FIRST>r a AM-ChainedSmoker     07-31 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chained Smoker,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Three Weeks, The Chain Comes Off And Smoker Is Nicotine-Free</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY NACHTIGAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who chained himself in his home
for three weeks to stop smoking said Monday it was worth it to
break his 20-year habit.
   Thomas Warren, 42, celebrated the removal Sunday of the thin,
25-foot steel cable _ which stretched from a 280-pound sofa in his
living room to form a collar around his neck _ by dining with
friends and later jogged two miles.
   A former marathon runner, Warren developed severe respiratory
problems from smoking cigarettes.
   Warren, an artist, dog trainer and drug counselor, said he
unsuccessfully tried everything to end his nicotine addiction. He
finally resorted to having his friends chain him up on July 9 and
rid his home of tobacco.
   Warren said some people laughed at his plan.
   ``I had some people who said sarcastically, `Couldn't you do it
on your own?' There are some people who can't do it on their own.
They need to be tied up or in treatment,'' he said.
   Warren, who beat a cocaine addiction 12 years ago, says a number
of current and former smokers telephoned or wrote.
   ``I had people call and say, `I gave up drugs years ago, I gave
up everything, but I'm still smoking and I know what you're going
through,''' Warren said.
   And Warren says it will be a daily battle not to light up again.
   Warren said Harvard researchers told him he has only a 10
percent chance of going two years without smoking because of his
``Type A'' personality and former drug addiction.
   ``That's baloney to me,'' he said. ``I'm not run by my desires
anymore. I have the power to say no. I'm not going to allow any
mistakes to occur.''
   Warren said sometimes during his ordeal he felt embarrassed
about being on a leash.
   ``Even though some people thought I was a fool, and I felt like
a foolish person at times, that's OK,'' he said. ``If there's any
smokers out there who think this was funny and laughed about it,
just remember: I bet I have the last breath.''
</TEXT>
