<FIRST>r i AM-Solzhenitsyn     07-31 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Solzhenitsyn,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Newspaper Publishes Solzhenitsyn's Criticism of Lenin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet newspaper reprinted a Time magazine
interview with exiled author Alexander I. Solzhenitsyn in which he
calls Vladimir Lenin ``evil'' _ a shocking description for those
who consider the Soviet founder a virtual god.
   Publication of the article in this week's mass-circulation Za
Rubezhom is remarkable both in its criticism of Lenin and as an
interview with Solzhenitsyn, whose writings were banned in the
Soviet Union from 1962 until March this year.
   In the past four months Soviet journals have published two
Solzhenitsyn essays. Novy Mir, the nation's leading literary
magazine, is preparing to publish excerpts of ``The Gulag
Archipelago,'' Solzhenitsyn's account of Soviet political prison
camps.
   In the Time interview, Solzhenitsyn said Lenin was ``uncommonly
evil.'' When asked what he meant by evil, Solzhenitsyn replied,
``The absence of any mercy, the absence of any humanity in his
approach to the people, the masses, to anyone who did not follow
him precisely.''
   Za Rubezhom carried a comment on that reply.
   An adjacent article, signed by historian A.M. Sovokin, said
Solzhenitsyn must have ``defective sight'' to ascribe such
characteristics to Lenin. Solzhenitsyn writes of Lenin and the
Bolshevik Revolution ``in a spirit of prejudice and intolerance,''
Sovokin said.
   Under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost or
openness, former Soviet leaders Josef Stalin and Leonid Brezhnev
have been blamed for many of the country's problems. But Lenin _
whose statue holds a prominent place in every Soviet city _ was
above criticism until June.
   At that time, a magazine published the late Vasily Grossman's
short novel, ``Forever Flowing,'' in which he accuseds Lenin of
contempt for freedom and cruelty to his opponents.
   The Za Rubezhom article also told Soviets that Solzhenitsyn
still faces criminal charges for treason in his homeland.
   In the Time interview Solzhenitsyn described the Bolshevik
Revolution as a ``coup d'etat'' and said the Bolsheviks themselves
called it the ``October coup'' through the 1920s.
   The Nobel Literature prize winner, who was exiled in 1974, lives
in Cavendish, Vt. He said in the interview that he will not return
to his homeland until his Soviet history, ``The Red Wheel,'' is
published and available in every bookstore in the Soviet Union.
   However, sources in the Soviet Writers' Union, which reinstated
him in July, said they expect Solzhenitsyn to visit his homeland,
possibly as soon as autumn.
   The Soviet government has moved toward rehabilitating
Solzhenitsyn, who is seen by some countrymen as a prophet of free
speech and by others as an embodiment of of Russian nationalism.
The Writers' Union, which publishes Novy Mir, has urged the
government to reinstate his citizenship.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
