<FIRST>u w AM-ALPO-Ralston     07-31 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ALPO-Ralston,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Against Ralston Purina in Puppy Food Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has awarded $10.4 million in
damages to ALPO Petfoods Inc. after ruling that Ralston Purina Co.
made false advertising claims touting the benefits of Purina Puppy
Chow.
   U.S. District Court Judge Stanley Sporkin ruled against
Ralston's marketing campaign, begun in 1985, in which the company
contended that its Puppy Chow products helped promote proper hip
joint development.
   Ralston will appeal the judgment, the company said Monday in a
statement from its St. Louis, Mo., headquarters.
   Sporkin also found that ALPO made false claims when it
advertised that veterinarians preferred ALPO's formula for puppy
food by a 2-to-1 margin over that of the leading brand, which was
Purina's Puppy Chow. He didn't order ALPO to pay any damages, but
enjoined both firms from engaging in false advertising.
   Ralston said its Puppy Chow diet helped reduce the incidence of
degenerative joint disease and canine hip dysplasia, which is
incurable and difficult to treat.
   ``With the exception of Ralston's own faulty research, there is
no valid scientific support for the proposition that the
nutritional balance in a dog's diet can affect'' hip joint
conditions, Sporkin said in a 54-page ruling.
   The ``overwhelming weight of scientific research indicates''
that the conditions ``are hereditary in nature and are unaffected
by the nutritional balance of a dog's diet,'' said the judge. He
called the research in support of the company's claim ``inadequate
and distorted.''
   Ralston launched a $5.2 million advertising campaign, declaring
that ``Puppy Chow helps prevent CHD.''
   Sporkin said the company had ``withheld vital information about
its research from the public, from government agencies and from the
court.
   At least one Ralston official, said the judge, ``ordered that
certain adverse information by destroyed.''
   ``We believe Judge Sporkin simply failed to grasp either the
facts or the relevant law in this case,'' Ralston spokesman Patrick
Farrell said in a statement. He said the decision would have ``a
chilling effect on corporate research'' if allowed to stand.
   In connection with ALPO's false claim that veterinarians
preferred its product, Sporkin said the firm ``lacked
substantiation'' for the assertion, which was based on a company
survey. Internal company documents prepared in June 1986
acknowledged that ALPO could no longer sustain its 2-to-1
preference claim, the judge noted.
   Sporkin also ordered both companies to send out corrective
information and to pay attorneys' fees.
   The judge's ruling, made Friday and issued publicly Monday, came
in a lawsuit filed by ALPO, which is the second-largest seller of
puppy food in the country, and a counterclaim filed by Ralston.
Ralston has been the leading puppy food seller in the country since
1964.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890731-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1952EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LexingtonManners     07-31 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lexington Manners,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>It's `Yes, Please' to Courtesy in Town That Cradled American Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mom always told you that a smile and a
kind word go a long way. But in Lexington, good manners could help
you keep your job.
   Courtesy is the new municipal watchword in this town that once
cradled the American Revolution and now prides itself on efficient,
accountable government.
   ``It kind of puts our best foot forward,'' fire dispatcher John
Soares said after giving an unannounced visitor a very polite
welcome Monday. ``It's looking at taxpayers as customers.''
   Over the next year, all 285 town employees will be required to
take a courtesy course that includes telephone etiquette, grooming
tips and how to make the public feel like a valued client.
   Employees transferring telephone calls, for example, are taught
to give a quick briefing on the caller to help minimize frustration.
   ``When you pick up the call, you use the person's name and you
try to paraphrase the problem so they don't feel they have to
repeat their story over and over again,'' said Fire Chief John D.
Bergeron, a graduate of the course.
   ``Nice talking to you,'' he said cheerfully at the end of a
telephone interview.
   Lexington employees are getting the sort of training in customer
service that's used by such businesses as Motorola Corp.,
Northwestern Airlines and the Papa Gino's pizza chain, said Maya
Ollson, president of the Evergreen Training and Development Inc.
   The program is costing $50,000, said Town Manager Richard D.
White, who is preparing to mail cards to all 30,000 residents to
find out whether they're satisfied with service from city agencies.
   ``This is more than a courtesy issue, it's a whole system of
management,'' said White. ``We may get some pretty decent ideas
from people as to what services we provide are absolutely essential
and which aren't.''
   Ollson said although people may have gripes, they don't report
them because ``they don't know how or they don't think it'll do any
good.''
   Because of the state budget crisis, the town expects to see its
state aid cut by more than one-sixth this year. White said cutbacks
and layoffs may be inevitable.
   Customer satisfaction will be a factor when deciding where to
cut.
   ``If you're an agency that has a lot of complaints, you're
obviously a target when it comes to budget reductions,'' Bergeron
said.
   Some town residents polled said they had never been treated
rudely but they welcomed the reminders.
   ``I think people who work in the public like that could always
use a dose of treating people nicely _ especially over the phone,''
said Phyllis Cusanelli.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890731-0126 </DOCNO>
