<FIRST>r w AM-AgricultureArrests     07-31 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agriculture Arrests,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Says 18 Indicted on Tobacco-Related Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department said Monday that 18
people have been indicted on tobacco-related charges, ranging from
conspiracy to false identification of tobacco, and federal agents
have started making arrests in the cases.
   The indictments, charging a total of 138 violations, stemmed
from a two-year investigation involving tobacco warehouse owners
who were accused of falsely identifying and marketing tobacco by
using illegally acquired marketing cards, USDA Deputy Inspector
General Leon Snead said in a statement.
   ``One warehouse owner was charged with using illegally obtained
marketing cards and his tobacco dealer card to sell excess tobacco
that he had purchased illegally from tobacco producers or stolen
from the warehouse floor,'' he said.
   The arrests Monday were made by agents of the USDA's office of
inspector general, the U.S. Marshals Service and Internal Revenue
Service.
   If convicted, the defendants could face fines of up to $10,000
and five years imprisonment on each count. They also could face
USDA administrative penalties.
   According to the USDA, the federal indictments were against
Glenn S. Martin Jr., 41, tobacco dealer and owner of Big Burley
Tobacco Warehouse, Johnson City, Tenn.; Graham Cole, 55, Moultrie,
Ga., tobacco dealer and owner of Planters Brick Tobacco Warehouse,
Pelham, Ga., and Peachtree Tobacco Co., Moultrie, Ga.
   Gordon Cox, 53, Billy Crain, 27, Jimmy Fender, 36, Fred A. King,
37, Bruno Guillen, 25, Mark Dawson, 26, Kenneth Dawson, 28, all of
Johnson City, Tenn.; Robert Nelson, 54, Kenneth Roberts, 42, both
of Jonesboro, Tenn.; Kenneth Meredith, 55, Elizabethton, Tenn.;
