<FIRST>r a AM-WellsFargo     07-31 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wells Fargo,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Sentenced to One Year in Prison in Wells Fargo Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDD EVERHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer was sentenced Monday to one year
in prison and fined $1,000 for his role in the $7.1 million robbery
of a Wells Fargo bank, believed to be the second-largest cash heist
in history.
   Paul S. Weinberg of Springfield, Mass., pleaded guilty last
September to a misdemeanor charge of aiding in the transportation
of stolen money.
   U.S. District Judge T. Emmet Clarie imposed the maximum sentence
and ordered Weinberg, 40, to surrender Aug. 28. He remains free on
$200,000 bond.
   The mastermind of the robbery, Harvard-educated Juan Segarra
Palmer of Puerto Rico, was sentenced in June to 65 years in prison
and fined $500,000. Segarra, a leader of a militant Puerto Rican
independence group, and three other Puerto Rican nationalists were
convicted in the 1983 threst of a half-ton of money from the
armored-car company's depot in West Hartford.
   Only $80,000 has been recovered.
   Weinberg got involved in the robbery conspiracy through his
friendship with Segarra, to whom Weinberg has admitted loaning
vehicles. Weinberg said he later suspected the vehicles were used
to tranport some of the stolen money.
   His guilty plea was part of an agreement between Weinberg and
federal prosecutors, who in turn dismissed four felony charges.
   Also, as part of the agreement, Weinberg promised to cooperate
with the government and to testify against defendants still
awaiting trial.
   ``You must realize there are consequences,'' Claire told
Weinberg. ``It's a serious matter, that's what I want to impress
upon you. It's not some trivia.''
   Clarie said Weinberg's plea to a misdemeanor count would not
disbar him in Massachusetts.
   Niether Weinberg nor his attorney, F. Mac Buckley, would comment
after the proceeding.
   U.S. Attorney Stanley A. Twardy Jr. said after sentencing that
other charges could still be lodged against Weinberg, including
obstruction of justice, perjury and making a false statement to a
federal official.
   Those issues, Twardy said, ``should be wrapped up this fall.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
