<FIRST>r w AM-CrackBabies     07-31 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crack Babies,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Urged to Spend More on Crack-Addicted Newborns and Mothers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More federal money is needed to combat crack
addiction among pregnant women and to provide care for addicted
newborns and their mothers, witnesses told a Senate panel Monday.
   ``As a country we have fostered a spiraling legacy of addicts
giving birth to addicts,'' Philadelphia social worker Teresa Ann
Hagan told the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee. ``Must this
generation and future generations suffer due to our unwillingness
to act with urgency?''
   Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., chairman of the session, said the $7.5
million in federal spending on model treatment programs this year
amounts to $10 each for mother and child.
   ``The Department of Defense spends $35 million every single
hour,'' Kohl said. ``What has happened to our priorities here?''
   Kohl said three to six cocaine babies are born daily in
Milwaukee alone and at one of the city's hospitals, 35 percent of
those born this year will test positive for cocaine. Hagan said a
recent survey indicated that 16 percent of births in Philadelphia
hospitals were ``drug related.''
   Gregory L. Coler, secretary of the Florida Department of Health
and Rehabilitative Services, said that in his state 2,000 people
are waiting for treatment at any given time and some simply give up
and return to drug abuse.
   He said the problem for infants born to addicted mothers is
serious.
   ``We see miscarriages, malformed limbs and eight-week-old babies
who have not gained weight since birth,'' he said.
   Sherry Agnos, wife of San Francisco's mayor, told the panel more
than 700 drug-exposed infants will be born in that city this year,
7 percent of all births citywide. She said 18 percent of newborns
at San Francisco General Hospital test positive for crack.
   She said San Francisco ``created a world model to confront the
AIDS epidemic'' and ``it paid off.'' She said AIDS costs are lower
per capita in San Francisco than anywhere else in the United States.
   ``We can do the same with crack cocaine if we are given the
support we need,'' she said.
   Hagan, program and clinical coordinator at the Family Center at
Thomas Jefferson University, said addition repeats itself from one
generation to the next and is deeply rooted in the nation's social
problems.
   She cited a Family Center study showing nearly 70 percent of
drug addicted women were abused sexually before the age of 16
compared to 15 percent of non-addicted women.
   Eighty-three percent of addicted women had a chemically
dependent parent, with 75 percent of those parents alcoholic. In
contrast, 35 percent of the non-addicted women had a chemically
dependent parent.
   She was accompanied by Elaina Wilcox, a patient at the Family
Center, who said that she had started using narcotics at age 15
after being abused and ``filtered through the child welfare
system.''
   ``Drug addicted mothers love their children just like any other
mother,'' she said.
   Minnie Thomas, an Oakland, Calif., social worker, told the
committee that her Mandela house treatment center has only six beds
for mothers and six beds for newborns and that young women
sometimes call her on the telephone and beg for a chance to get
into her drug program, even if it means sleeping on the couch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
