<FIRST>u w AM-VonRaab     07-31 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Von Raab,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customs Chief Leaves With a Blast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outgoing Customs Commissioner William von Raab
took a few last jabs Monday at colleagues who, he says, are not
sufficiently committed to the war on drugs.
   At the 200th anniversary celebration of the Customs Service, in
his letter of resignation, an interview and a news conference, von
Raab zinged:
   _Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, his boss, for allegedly not
supporting him.
   _Unidentified State Department bureaucrats and their ``quest to
make the world safe for cocktail parties.''
   _``Political jockeying, backstabbing and malaise'' in the
anti-drug effort.
   And von Raab said he toned his speech down at Brady's request.
   Including parts of his resignation letter in his speech, von
Raab said, `Maybe it is time for the war on drugs to take its place
as our nation's top priority _ to interfere with other interests
such as banking and Third World debt.''
   About the only person exempted from von Raab's lash was William
Bennett, whom he praised as ``a courageous man.''
   In his own defense, von Raab said, ``If we dared to speak out,
it was because those in our own government were too scared to speak
up'' about drug trafficking by those such as Gen. Manuel Noriega of
Panama.
   Brady sat expressionless on stage through von Raab's remarks,
staring at the Washington Monument. In his own comments, Brady
praised interagency cooperation and said the drug war ``is a war we
are going to win.''
   Von Raab did not shake hands with Brady at the close of the
ceremony, though he did with many others.
   The customs commissioner, denied reappointment by President Bush
to the job he has held for eight years, has been sharply critical
of other officials in recent interviews. He said Monday was his
last day on the job.
   ``I'm quitting, obviously, because I'm not getting along with
Secretary Brady,'' von Raab told reporters.
   The commissioner said Brady had stopped the policy of ``zero
tolerance'' of drug users and traffickers that had resulted in one
case in the seizure of a yacht because of the presence of one
marijuana cigarette.
   In addition, von Raab said, Brady had refused to go along with
his plan to offer a bounty for the seizure of drug kingpins abroad,
and he criticized the lack of discussion of the drug problem when
the United States and Mexico negotiated a debt-relief plan.
   But Assistant Secretary of the Treasury Roger Bolton said in an
interview that Congress, not Brady, modified the zero tolerance
policy, and a Treasury official has forwarded von Raab's bounty
proposal ``with a pretty strong recommendation'' to Bennett.
   Bolton confirmed that the drug issue did not come up in the
Mexican debt negotiations.
   Although von Raab said Brady is ``an honorable man, he's a
gentleman,'' he noted that Brady did not mention his imminent
departure during the ceremony.
   Asked later whether it wasn't disingenuous of him to claim he
couldn't understand Brady's lack of warmth in light of his recent
statements and his resignation letter, von Raab simply shrugged,
smiled and walked away.
   Bolton confirmed that Brady asked von Raab to soften his speech.
An early draft, he said, included ``direct criticism of other
departments, such as State, Commerce and Justice, which were not
the Treasury Department's views.''
   Von Raab said he plans to take a month off, then return to
Washington ``to see if anybody wants to employ me.'' He did not
respond when asked if he planned to run for office.
</TEXT>
