<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Tornado     07-31 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Tornado,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tornado Kills 5 in Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tornado swept through a shanty
district early Monday, killing at least five people, as monsoon
rains and strong winds buffeted Manila and the main Philippine
island of Luzon, officials said.
   At least six other people were injured when the cyclone swept
through the suburb of Malabon, blowing down walls and ripping roofs
off shanties, the Office of Civil Defense reported.
   The bodies of a man, his wife and two daughters aged 4 and 6
were found in the debris of a shanty after the storm blew down the
firewall of an adjacent factory, the office said.
   Another man who was injured in the incident died later, said
spokeswoman Emilia Tadeo. At least 18 houses were flattened while
the roofs of 30 more houses were blown off, and 25 families were
evacuated to schools in the area.
   In San Fernando, 140 miles north of Manila, officials issued
flood warnings for residents along the Agno river in Pangasinan
province.
   Officials said water levels in the river rose dramatically
Sunday after seven floodgates in the Binga dam were opened
following heavy rains.
   Radio stations reported flooding in at least three towns in the
province.
   Red Cross officials said monsoon rains spawned by two tropical
storms which skirted the northern Philippines over the weekend
caused floods and triggered landslides in northern Luzon.
   Ireneo Zabala, Red Cross relief supervisor, said houses in
coastal towns of Cavite province near Manila were also destroyed by
strong winds.
   The state-run Philippines News Agency said heavy rains weakened
bridge supports in northwestern Luzon, stranding thousands of
motorists.
</TEXT>
