<DOCNO> AP890731-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 2045EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     07-31 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hashimoto Drops Out of Contention for Prime Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liberal Democratic Party leader Ryutaro Hashimoto,
who was considered the top contender to replace Prime Minister
Sousuke Uno, said Monday he would not seek that office, according
to news reports.
   Hashimoto, secretary general of the governing party, made his
statement after leaders of a key party faction decided not to make
him their candidate, the Japan Broadcasting Corp. and several
newspapers reported.
   The leader of the Liberal Democrats customarily becomes prime
minister because of the party's majority in Parliament's lower
house.
   Leaders of three factions made their decision not to back any
current or former faction members during a three-hour meeting
Sunday at the home of Shin Kanemaru, said Hiroaki Toshinari, a
party spokesman.
   Kanemaru is former Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's mentor.
Takeshita and Hashimoto resigned from their party faction as part
of reforms during an influence-buying scandal that forced Takeshita
to resign on June 2.
   The decision not to back anyone was made by Kanemaru, who heads
the faction, and senior members Ichiro Ozawa and Keiwa Okuda. Okuda
heads the party's Parliamentary Policy Committee and Ozawa is a
former party deputy secretary general.
   They made the decision because the faction had played a crucial
role in choosing Uno and his Cabinet when Takeshita resigned,
Toshinari said. Uno announced July 24 he too would step down
because of the party's losses in Senate elections the previous day.
There also were reports he paid geishas for sex.
   The faction leaders also reportedly decided not to support
Hashimoto because he lacks a strong following within the faction.
Hashimoto, who at 52 is the youngest man ever to hold the party's
No. 2 post, has been criticized as inexperienced.
   A replacement for Uno is expected to be chosen Aug. 8 in a
meeting of the party's parliamentary caucus.
   Takeshita's former faction is by far the largest of six major
factions within the party.
</TEXT>
