<FIRST>u i AM-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru a0660 07-31 0784</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,0809</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Peace Talks Split Over Khmer Rouge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to update with closed door sessions running into
trouble; EDITS to trim; No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bitter accusations against the Khmer Rouge
dominated the Cambodian peace talks Monday with Vietnam calling the
radical communist group ``the most barbarous regime ever known.''
   Khmer Rouge leader Khieu Samphan in turn claimed that Vietnam
plans to ``exterminate'' the Cambodian people and has no intention
of withdrawing its troops from Cambodia in September as promised.
   Diplomats from 20 countries joined in calling for a
comprehensive peace plan, but none of their speeches Sunday and
Monday offered new proposals to end the nation's two decades of
conflict.
   The conference, expected to last a month, continued behind
closed doors later Monday and immediately ran into trouble over how
to begin work, officials reported. Delegates had expressed hope for
progress in the closed sessions.
   Points of conflict included disagreement over whether a
committee should be established to hasten an end to the conflcit,
officials said. Vietnam and the Vietnamese-backed government in
Cambodia contend the conflict is exclusively their affair.
   French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jean Gueguinou said delegates
would hold informal talks and reconvene Tuesday when committee
discussions of specific issues begin.
   Emerging as a critical point was the future role of the Khmer
Rouge, the strongest of three resistance groups fighting the
Vietnamese and the Cambodian government.
   The resistance coalition is supported by China and led by
neutralist Prince Norodom Sihanouk, who believes having the Khmer
Rouge participate in the government would be better than fighting
them in the jungles.
   Almost all delegates at the conference reviled the Khmer Rouge,
which was ousted when Vietnam invaded the country in December 1978.
The Khmer Rouge came to power in April 1975, defeating the
U.S.-backed government, and killed hundreds of thousands of
civilians in a nationwide purge.
   ``The genocidal Pol Pot regime is the most barbarous regime ever
known in human history,'' Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Co
Thach told the conference.
   He said the Khmer Rouge should be ``eradicated definitively'' as
were the German Nazis after World War II. Pol Pot was the Khmer
Rouge leader during the massacres in the 1970s. He has resigned
from most of his posts.
   Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen cautioned that excluding
any party from an interim government would be ``dangerous.''
   ``The reality in Cambodia today is the simultaneous presence of
four political parties, each possessing its own armed forces,'' he
said.
   Qian called for the Vietnamese troop withdrawal under
international supervision to be followed by a four-party interim
government headed by Sihanouk. The parties would be the present
Cambodian government and the coalition of the Khmer Rouge,
Sihanouk's followers and an anti-communist force. Japan, the West
and non-communist Southeast Asian countries agree on that approach.
Vietnam, the Soviet Union and the Cambodian government reject
inclusion of the Khmer Rouge.
   If the procedural impasse is worked out, three or four
committees will focus on specific aspects of the peace process in
closed door sesions.
   The delegates reportedly have agreed on three committees. Those
committees would discuss an ``international control mechanism'' to
monitor the Vietnamese withdrawal, work out international aspects
of the conflict and set up programs for returning refugees and
post-war reconstruction.
   Disagreements were reported over a proposed fourth committee on
an internal settlement to the conflict, over who should head the
committees and on a proposal to send a fact-finding mission to
Cambodia.
   Several conference sources said on condition of anonymity that
the Khmer Rouge were blocking agreement on a number of these points.
   ``The atmosphere in the conference room is one of optimism.
There is a strong current toward a solution,'' Sihanouk told
reporters.
   On Sunday, Secretary of State James A. Baker III said: ``We know
the path to Cambodian internal reconciliation is likely to be long
and arduous. But today we take the first steps.''
   Sihanouk singled out China as the linchpin.
   ``China can do a lot. China can choose to stick with Khmer
Rouge. It is for China to decide,'' he said.
   Western sources said that while it may be impossible to
reconcile the Cambodian parties in Paris, progress could be
achieved on forming an international body to monitor the Vietnamese
pullout.
   Several ministers, including those of China, Australia and
Japan, backed a recommendation by U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar to dispatch a ``reconnaissance mission'' to
Cambodia immediately to lay the groundwork for an ``international
control mechanism.''
   Most nations favor U.N. leadership of such a group. But the
Cambodian government and Vietnam oppose it. The United Nations gave
the country's seat at the world body to Sihanouk's coalition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
