<FIRST>r w AM-Steelworkers     07-31 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steelworkers,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Blames Chinese Government in Delaware Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Steelworkers Union holds the
Chinese government responsible for alleged unfair hiring at the
nation's oldest steelmaker, union President Lynn Williams said
Monday as he led a rally at the Chinese Embassy.
   Williams opened the international union's annual legislative
conference with a speech, then picked up a bullhorn and led 750
steelworkers to the embassy during the evening rush hour to protest
hiring actions at the former Phoenix Steel Co. of Claymont, Del.
   China International Trust and Investment Corp., a Beijing-based
arm of the Chinese government, bought the shut-down plant last year
and named it CitiSteel USA. It was CITIC's first U.S. manufacturing
venture.
   The steelworkers' union initially welcomed the takeover, but now
claims the new owners reneged on a commitment to hire former
Phoenix Steel workers.
   Of the 250 former Phoenix workers who applied for jobs,
CitiSteel hired 38 of them for skilled positions, the union said.
It said in a statement that the firm did not hire Phoenix employees
``for the less skilled jobs that make up the majority of jobs in
the plant.''
   The National Labor Relations Board is investigating the
steelworkers' complaint that CitiSteel has refused collective
bargaining with the union, and has refused to hire people because
they are union members.
   Like the June army massacre of students and other pro-democracy
demonstrators in Beijing, the CitiSteel case is an example of
Chinese government ``ruthlessness,'' Williams said in an interview.
   ``It is clear that the Chinese government in the end is
responsible. CITIC is their corporation,'' Williams said.
   ``People's opportunities have been taken away from them. They've
denied employment to people who have given their lives to the
predecessor company and to building the steel mill,'' he said.
   In a news release, CitiSteel acknowledged the protest but said
the union had ``incorrectly'' claimed that the company was obliged
to hire former Phoenix employees.
   CitiSteel said it needed ``flexibility'' in shaping its work
force. Nevertheless, it said 60 percent of its skilled hourly
workers had been employed by Phoenix, and that it would recruit
others for unskilled jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
