<FIRST>r w AM-Post-GuildContract     07-31 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Post-Guild Contract,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Post Employees to Vote on Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspaper guild employees at The Washington
Post who have been without a contract for three years will vote
Wednesday on an agreement that would raise salaries an average of
$165 a week over five years, a union official said Monday.
   Sandi Polaski, chief negotiator for the Washington-Baltimore
Newspaper Guild Local 31, said the guild's bargaining committee was
recommending approval by the 1,420 newsroom and other white collar
employees covered by the pact.
   ``It's not everything we wanted,'' Polaski said, but it contains
``substantial improvements'' in wages and guild representation.
   The tentative agreement was reached Friday following all-night
talks. The previous contract expired three years ago and Post
management had declared an impasse two years ago. Post reporters
resorted to two byline strikes on the anniversaries of the expired
pact.
   In addition to newsroom workers, the contract covers employees
in the accounting, advertising, circulation and data-processing and
other business departments of the Post's 3,000-member workforce.
   The new contract would raise salaries between 4 percent and 6
percent a year, with lower-paid workers receiving a higher
percentage increase along with improvements in minimum salary
scales.
   Employees who make more than $50,000 a year, which includes most
of the paper's reporters, will get average raises of $42.50 a week
during each of the first three years of the contract, with similar
raises expected in the final two years.
   The pact also calls for improvements in the Post's pension and
disability-insurance plans, and better medical and dental coverage,
but at higher cost to employees.
   The additional salary and pension provisions will cost the
company about $15 million over the life of the contract, according
to Frank Havlicek, the newspaper's chief negotiator.
   The agreement also contains provisions for resolving
worker-management disputes and a no-strike, no-lockout clause.
</TEXT>
