<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 2143EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ColdDrug     07-31 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cold Drug,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Asked Not to Let Promethazine Hydrochloride Go Over-the-Counter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advisory committee on Monday recommended
that the Food and Drug Administration reverse plans to allow
nonprescription sales of a cough-cold drug because of its possible
association with sudden infant death syndrome.
   The agency had planned to allow over-the-counter sales of the
drug, promethazine hydrochloride, in multi-ingredient cold products
for short-term use.
   But the FDA asked its Pulmonary Drugs Advisory Committee to
review the issue in light of a petition from the Public Citizen
Health Research Group and the University of Maryland Sudden Infant
Death Syndrome Institute.
   The groups said the drug, which has been sold in prescription
products since 1951, may contribute to some cases of the syndrome
known as SIDS. Though it is not recommended for use in young
children, doctors do prescribe it for them, for colic, the groups
said.
   The advisory committee voted 7-1 to recommend that the drug
remain a prescription ingredient, said Susan Cruzan, an FDA
spokeswoman.
   She said committee members were concerned about a possible
relationship between the drug and SIDS and that more study was
needed to prove conclusively whether the drug plays a role in the
syndrome.
   The panel was also concerned about possible brain damage from
the drug.
   ``The FDA will consider the committee's recommendation,'' she
said. ``The FDA has to decide what the next step is.''
   The drug is an active ingredient in products sold under the
trade name Phenergan, made by Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories of
Philadelphia. Wyeth-Ayerst and other makers of prescription
products using the drug agreed to withhold nonprescription
marketing pending review by the advisory committee.
   The health group and SIDS institute said that although Phenergan
is not recommended for children under 2 years old, doctors wrote
175,000 prescriptions for the drug for that age group in 1985.
   The groups feared the drug would become even more widely used in
children if it were sold over the counter, even though it would be
labeled for use only by adults and children over 6.
</TEXT>
