<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 2048EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ColliderReports     07-31 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Collider Reports,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Audit Hits Size, Cost of Mailing Report on Super Collider</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lot of people have asked, Just what was the
Energy Department thinking of when it spent $344,000 mailing a
26-pound report on the super collider to 16,800 people?
   It wasn't money, but rather a take-no-chances-attitude,
congressional auditors reported Monday.
   ``Cost was not the primary constraint considered. Other
priorities such as the desire to demonstrate full compliance with
the regulations, avoid public criticism or lawsuits, and the desire
to meet its ... timetable represented overriding considerations,''
the audit concluded.
   ``An overriding factor ... was to err on the side of least
risk.''
   The super collider report, which analyzed the environmental
impact of the $4.4 billion atom smasher, was sent to governors,
reporters, school children, libraries, property owners _ nearly
anyone who had written the department about the project, signed a
petition or even an attendance sheet at public meetings.
   ``I'm sure most of them ended up in the trash,'' said Rep.
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., ``or at least holding up the Christmas
tree, or doing something.''
   Hastert asked the General Accounting Office to determine if the
large mailing was necessary to comply with federal rules on
environmental reports.
   The GAO suggested the Energy Department could have saved more
than $200,000 in mailing costs and prevented a lot of sore backs if
it had trimmed the 8,000-page document, limited the distribution
and picked a cheaper form of delivery.
   Energy Department spokesman Jeff Sherwood did not return phone
calls requesting comment.
   The report, which cost $1.36 million to print, bind and mail, is
an environmental impact statement on possible sites for the super
collider in Arizona, Colorado, Illinois, Michigan, North Carolina,
Tennessee and Texas.
   The super collider is a 53-mile, underground ring of magnets
which would whip proton beams together with 20 times the force of
the most powerful exisiting atom smasher.
   Scientists hope to learn more about the nature of matter from
studying subatomic particles created by the proton collisions.
Texas was awarded the project last November.
   Hastert, whose district was considered for the super collider,
said constituents started complaining nine days before Christmas
when about half of the 16,000 reports sent around the country
started arriving in suburban Chicago.
   ``One morning I received a panicked call from the postmaster in
St. Charles, Illinois, and he virtually had truckloads of this
thing,'' the congressman said. ``He had to rent a U-Haul and hire
two people to get them around.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
