<FIRST>u a AM-CapsizedRig 1stLd-Writethru a0682 07-31 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capsized Rig, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0682,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rig Capsizes; 10 Workers Missing, Four Rescued</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with search suspended; 10 missing, sted 9;
CORRECTS ownership of vessel; DELETES outdated quotes on air pockets; ADDS
details on rig operations, report of second rig listing; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue divers lost their fight with time and
hurricane seas Monday and had to give up their search for 10
offshore oil workers missing in a capsized rig in the Gulf of
Mexico.
   ``As soon as possible we will have people back on the scene, but
there is no way to do anything with the conditions out there,''
said Coast Guard Lt. Pat Philbin.
   The rescuers were stymied by 12-foot seas, heavy rains and
60-mph winds on the fringes of tropical storm Chantal, which was
upgraded to hurricane status Monday evening.
   Officials refused to speculate on the chances of survival for
those who may have found air pockets in the capsized rig, lying on
its side in about 25 feet of water, Philbin said.
   The Chevron-leased rig was headed to shore early Monday to
escape the storm when it capsized about 20 miles off the Louisiana
coast near Morgan City, said company spokesman Jonathan Lifa.
   Four of the 14 workers aboard were plucked from the water by
fishermen and a Coast Guard helicopter, said Chief Petty Officer
Michael Robling.
   An air bubble trapped in watertight compartments would be the
only oxygen for any survivors, said Lt. Steve Hardy, but he did not
estimate how long any trapped crewmen could survive.
   Divers were unable to search the rig because of the storm, he
said. The dive boat and a Coast Guard cutter stood nearby, but the
bad weather forced helicopters back to shore.
   Three survivors were taken aboard the fishing vessel Spar Royale
for a trip to Wine Island Pass, and one person was taken by
helicopter to Grand Isle, Hardy said. None of the four was
seriously injured, officials said.
   The Coast Guard, said the rig, a 72-foot self-propelled barge
with jack-up legs, was owned by Avis Boug Co. of Folsom and leased
by Chevron Oil Corp.
   The Coast Guard recently began inspections of such vessels
because of the ``significant casualty rate'' and Monday was the
deadline for applying for an inspection. This company had applied,
Lifa said.
   The barge had been in 50 to 60 feet of water, working on oil
pipes on the seabottom. The rig's legs, which extend 100 feet down
when when it is working, are lifted above the vessel when it is
underway, Hardy said.
   Elsewhere, a worker on a Chevron platform in the Gulf south of
New Orleans died Monday after he fell into the water while trying
to board a crew boat, but five other workers safely evacuated a
dangerously tilted jackup rig off Grand Isle.
   The jackup rig, owned by Atlantic &amp; Pacific Marine Inc. of
Houston, was listing at a 12 degree angle at 5 p.m. Monday.
``That's a pretty good angle. I'd say it's going over,'' Hardy said.
</TEXT>
