<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0724,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chantal Nears Hurricane Strength With Heavy Rain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to reflect that storm has been upgraded to
a hurricane.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain and thunderstorms were scattered east of the Mississippi
River on Monday, and Hurricane Chantal headed toward shore with
heavier rain and high wind.
   The center of the hurricane was expected to hit land Tuesday,
and hurricane warnings were posted for the upper Texas and
Louisiana Gulf coasts, from Freeport, Texas, to Morgan City, La.
   Widespread rain and thunderstorms from the central Gulf Coast
into northwestern Florida were associated with the first band of
thunderstorms spiraling outward from Chantal.
   Isolated tornadoes and rainfall amounts of 10 to 15 inches were
possible from eastern Texas through Louisiana into southern
Mississippi during Tuesday and Wednesday.
   Oil rigs along the Louisiana coast reported wind gusting to 50
mph.
   Squalls on the edge of the storm dumped heavy rain on New
Orleans and forced closure of the 24-mile long causeway across Lake
Pontchartrain.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from the lower
Mississippi into the lower Ohio valleys. Thunderstorms also
developed from Georgia into the Carolinas and Virginia.
   Elsewhere, a cold front curved over the Pacific Ocean off the
northern Pacific Coast, and showers moved into coastal regions of
Oregon and extreme northern California.
   Bakersfield, Calif., tied its record low for the date of 60
degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57
degrees at Crescent City, Calif., to 107 at Palm Springs, Calif.
Monday's low in the Lower 48 states was 39 at Houlton, Maine, and
Burns, Ore.
   For Tuesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from southern and eastern parts of Texas through the lower
Mississippi and Tennessee valleys and the Gulf Coast states to the
southern Atlantic Coast. Scattered showers were forecast across the
Pacific Northwest. Afternoon showers and thunderstorms were
forecast from the Colorado Rockies into northern Arizona and New
Mexico, and over parts of southern New England.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted along the central and northern
Pacific Coast region, and from parts of the northern Great Lakes
into New England; between 100 and 115 across the desert Southwest;
and in the 80s or 90s across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
