<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0583 07-31 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0583,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coastal Highway Clogged as Thousands Flee Shelling</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th pvs, ``Since then...'' to UPDATE with
car bombing; ADDS byline; Pickup 6th, ``Police said...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cars jammed the coastal highway leading
south from Beirut as thousands more residents fled Monday to escape
shelling duels between Christians and Syrians that killed eight
people and wounded 92 overnight.
   ``I'm not going to return unless it's all over this time,'' said
Samiha Rashdan, a Sunni Moslem leaving with her husband and three
teen-age sons. ``We returned from south Lebanon last week only to
get caught in the new mad shelling.''
   Mattresses, beds and other household goods balanced high on the
roofs of many cars, indicating residents do not plan early returns.
   Police estimated only 200,000 of the city's 1.5 million
inhabitants remain in the capital. The rest have fled since Syrian
troops based in Lebanon started battling Gen. Michel Aoun's mainly
Christian troops on March 8.
   Since then, 510 people have been killed and 2,158 wounded.
   Late Monday, a car bomb exploded in Moslem west Beirut, police
said. There were no injuries after the black Mercedes-Benz, loaded
with 88 pounds of TNT and parked near a highway intersection,
exploded and burst into flames, they said.
   A short time later, heavy gunfire broke out around Beirut's
central prison, about one mile from the car bomb. But police said
they could not immediately determine what caused the shooting.
   Police said the overnight battle that rained shells on nearly
every neighborhood of the divided city was one of the worst in
Lebanon's 14-year civil war.
   ``It looks like both sides are bent on destroying Beirut. This
is a scorched-earth bombardment rarely matched in previous civil
war rounds,'' said the spokesman, who cannot be named under
standing regulations.
   Two hospitals in Christian east Beirut as well as the Turkish
Embassy and the Belgian ambassador's residence near Aoun's palace
took direct hits in the bombardment from 5 p.m. Sunday to 4 a.m.
Monday, said the spokesman. No casualties were reported there.
   The presidential palace in suburban Baabda, east of Beirut, was
battered with sustained barrages from BM-21 Syrian launchers that
spew 40 rockets a minute. Aoun, 54, lives in the palace bunker and
was not hurt, the spokesman said.
   Christian gunners struck back with savage barrages from 155mm
howitzers that set three gas stations ablaze in different
residential areas of Moslem west Beirut.
   ``The burning stations spewed balls of flames like firecrackers
on nearby apartment buildings, forcing residents to flee, even from
basements,'' the spokesman said.
   Hundreds of stores and cars were gutted. Streets were carpeted
with glass shards and debris. Broken electric power poles
barricaded alleyways. Traffic was scarce.
   Among the wounded were six members of a Sunni Moslem family
whose sixth floor apartment was struck by a 155mm shell.
   ``We were all injured,'' said Issam Ramadan, 30.
   His 9-month-old daughter Leila started bleeding badly. ``I had
to carry her in my arms and run for about two miles to the American
University hospital with shells exploding around me,'' he said.
   Hospital officials said the baby was recovering well after her
head and facial wounds were stitched. Other family members were
discharged.
   West Beirut residents, meanwhile, observed a strike to protest
Israel's abduction Friday of Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, a Shiite
Moslem cleric in south Lebanon. The strike was ignored in the
capital's eastern Christian sector as residents packed groceries,
butcher shops and bakeries to lay in food supplies.
   Prosecutor General Joseph Freiha said Monday that Aoun has
ordered a court-martial of those responsible for a report by the
privately owned Akhbar Lubanan news agency that his troops have
acquired surface-to-surface Frog missiles from Iraq.
   The agency is accused of distributing ``a false statement''
quoting Lebanon's ambassador to Baghdad, Hikmat Awad.
   The report, which said the arms are intended to boost Aoun's
battle to chase the Syrian troops from Lebanon, was published by
several Beirut newspapers Sunday.
   The Frog-7 has a range of more than 40 miles and its warhead of
1,210 pounds of high explosives could hit the Syrian capital,
Damascus, if fired from the central Lebanese mountains in the
Christian heartland.
   Iraq and Syria are traditional rivals in the Arab world and
Iraqi President Sadam Hussein is arming Aoun's 20,000 troops, far
outnumbered by the 40,000 Syrian troops which first came to Lebanon
in 1976 under an Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
</TEXT>
