<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 2205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-IndianStandoff     07-31 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Standoff,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indians, State Reach Tentative Accord To Ease Reservation Tension</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GERMAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mohawk leaders and state police agreed
Monday to ease a tense, 10-day-old standoff at the blockaded St.
Regis Indian Reservation, and a leader of the Mohawk warrior
society was released on bail, officials said.
   More than 200 state troopers have blocked roads to keep
outsiders off Indian land since a July 20 raid by 225 state police
and FBI agents on the reservation's illegal casinos.
   Five Mohawk leaders met with state police, members of Gov. Mario
Cuomo's staff and a U.S. Bureau of Indian Affairs agent to resolve
tensions on the reservation, which straddles the St. Lawrence River
on the U.S.-Canadian border.
   ``We have reached a tentative agreement which assures everyone's
safety,'' said Mohawk Chief Harold Tarbell.
   State police began removing some of their concrete roadblocks
Monday night, said state trooper Richard Garcia.
   ``We will be scaling down the checkpoints and allowing the
motoring public onto the reservation,'' he said. ``We're hopeful
this will ease the tension.''
   Garcia said state police would post informational barricades for
an indefinite period, to explain the situation on the reservation
to motorists, giving them the option to enter the Indian land or
turn back, he said.
   ``The casinos are still closed. I'm personally hoping they will
stay closed because of their illegal nature,'' Tarbell said. Mohawk
leaders have scheduled a mid-August vote on whether reservation
residents want to legalize gambling.
   Also Monday, Art Montour, 47, a leader of the Mohawk Sovereign
Security Force, was freed on $50,000 bail after a week in jail,
charged with obstructing justice during the July 20 raid.
   Montour, accused of using a gun to keep police from searching a
casino during the raid, was released in Syracuse after posting
$5,000. He was to appear again in court Aug. 16.
   Gambling has divided the Mohawks. After two raids in the past
two months, the reservation's warrior faction protested, claiming
police have no jurisdiction on Mohawk land and that the raids
violated their sovereignty.
   Montour's allies erected blockades on state Route 37 inside the
reservation, state police barricaded the road to keep outsiders out.
   Eleven people were injured July 24, when about 75 Mohawks
stepped off the reservation and tried to prevent Montour's arrest
when state police moved in.
</TEXT>
