<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 2251EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Japan     07-31 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle to Visit Asian Nations in the Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle will make a 10-day
trip to South Korea, Japan and the Philippines in late September,
his office said Monday.
   The vice president's office announced the Asian visit after
Quayle met Monday with Michio Ochi, a Japanese cabinet minister in
charge of that nation's Economic Planning Agency.
   Quayle plans to leave Sept. 18 for Seoul and to spend Sept.
22-24 in Japan before continuing to Manila, spokesman David
Beckwith said.
   The Centerpiece of the tour will be the fourth party leaders'
meeting in Tokyo of the International Democratic Union, a global
association of political parties of democratic countries, Beckwith
said.
   Quayle's half-hour meeting with Ochi was described by Beckwith
as the first of a series of briefings in preparation for Quayle's
talks with leaders of the three Asian countries he will visit.
   Quayle visited Southeast Asia, the South Pacific and Australia
in April on his first overseas tour as vice president, and he
visited Japan as a senator.
</TEXT>
