<DOCNO> AP890731-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 0847EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:ComedyCasinos Adv04   07-31 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Comedy Casinos, Adv 04,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, Aug 4 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cheap Laughs Replacing High-Priced Shows as Casino Entertainment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In-house comedy clubs are catching on as
Nevada casinos turn to low-priced new comics to give gamblers a few
laughs between forays at the slot machines and gaming tables.
   ``This is definitely a trend that we've hopped onto,'' said Jim
Johnson, marketng director for the Flamingo Hilton Reno which
recently opened a new comedy club.
   ``There's been a resurgence of comedy all over the country. It
used to be, in the times of Jack Benny and Bob Hope, that comedy
was big in entertainment. Now, I think we're back to that.''
   The lone exception to the comedy clubs' recent success story is
Rodney Dangerfield, who got no respect in Las Vegas.
   Rodney's Place, a joint venture between the veteran comedian and
the Tropicana Resort and Casino, closed June 25, six months after
it opened, when Dangerfield and the club couldn't agree on a new
contract.
   ``We haven't given up on the idea of opening it up again as a
comedy club,'' said Larry Lee, director of entertainment at the
Tropicana. ``We're talking with six national comedy chains. We
could go with something else, but we're leaning toward comedy now
because it worked so well.''
   The idea of using laughter to ease losing gamblers' pain isn't
new. Comedians have been opening for big-name headliners such as
Frank Sinatra and Sammy Davis Jr. for decades. Comics who started
out in Nevada casinos and still play their showrooms include Joan
Rivers, Bill Cosby and Jay Leno.
   More traditional production shows with their showgirls in
sequins, elaborate headdresses and little else also use comedy acts
to break up song and dance routines.
   But a few years ago in Las Vegas, in-house casino comedy clubs
began popping up to feed a nationwide appetite for laughter. The
trend now has invaded northern Nevada where casinos are leaning
away from multimillion dollar headliners and production shows in
favor of cheap laughs.
   Most unknown comics make a few hundred dollars for an appearance
while better-known entertainers, such as ``Saturday Night Live''
regular Kevin Nealon and ``Night Court'' bailiff Marsha Warfield
receive paychecks in the thousands.
   ``We were looking for a way to keep the customers on the
property longer and to attract locals to the club,'' said Michael
Opton, marketing director for Reno's Ramada Inn hotel casino, which
houses the Comedy Circuit.
   ``At first we looked at a production show. But we didn't have
the room. And, we thought, `why not try comedy? It's cheaper, too.'
''
   The Reno Ramada has run the Comedy Circuit for the past eight
months and now has competition from the Flamingo Hilton Reno, which
opened its Comedy Club July 4.
   Caesars Tahoe at Stateline, Nev., on Lake Tahoe's south shore
has been showcasing young comics for the past few years in its Laff
Trax. Bally's-Reno, where the spectacular ``Hello Hollywood,
Hello'' production closed out an 11-year run in April, is thinking
of opening a Catch a Rising Star as an outlet of the New York
comedy club where amateurs are welcome to try out.
   Johnson said the Reno Hilton is giving the Comedy Club a trial
through the summer to determine if it will attract enough customers.
   ``We've seen slow, steady growth since it opened,'' Johnson
said. ``But we're not getting the traditional crowd _ out-of-town
tourists in their 50s. We're getting a much younger crowd and some
repeat business.''
   In Las Vegas, casino comedy tickles gamblers in such venues as
Catch a Rising Star at Bally's and The Comedy Store at the Dunes.
   Most of the casino comedy clubs rotate well-known and new
comedians every one or two weeks, with two to three comics a night
for a standard show lasting 90 minutes.
   Admission generally runs $8-$10 and includes one or two drinks.
That's slightly more expensive than the two-drink price of a normal
caberet show but far less than a showroom production where dinner
and drinks can leave two people with a three-digit bill at the end
of the night.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri Aug. 4</NOTE>
