<DOCNO> AP890731-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1033EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-RuralViolence Adv07   07-31 1092</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rural Violence, Adv 07,1121</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday PMs, Aug. 7, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>No Escape From Violence; Murder Rate High in the Country</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This story continues a series, `Rural Crossroads'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAHAM, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was not yet 7 a.m., and a morning chill
hung over the green meadows and gardens of this quiet town near
snow-capped Mount Rainier.
   Roosters crowed, and old dogs on front porches yawned to greet
another summer day. Dairy farmer Tom LaCrosse was in his barn,
already hard at work, with no reason to doubt he'd be around to
savor the warmth of noon.
   A few minutes later, a distraught man named Kenneth Gehring
stormed into the farmyard with a rifle in his hand. A few minutes
later still, four people lay dying: LaCrosse and his wife, Rutheda;
milk truck driver Kirby Hull; and Gehring, who turned the gun on
himself when he saw what he had done.
   The violence was not confined to the LaCrosse farm. It shocked
this town of 3,500, touching everyone who knew the victims,
stealing from everyone who had cherished a peaceful life away from
urban woes.
   ``In a small community like this, when someone is taken, it
takes a piece out of everyone here,'' said neighbor Karen Stannard.
   Moving to the country does not guarantee a safe and sheltered
life.
   FBI statistics show that while big cities still suffer the
nation's highest murder rates, rural counties consistently place
second, with a per-capita murder rate outstripping the suburbs and
smaller cities.
   And that's just the average. Certain rural areas _ gripped by
poverty, low education levels and disruptive social change _ have
developed what some sociologists call a ``culture of violence''
that sends murder rates rising high above national norms. Areas
singled out include those populated by minorities that have
historically been oppressed: the black South, Hispanic Southwest,
and the Indian country of Western reservations and Alaska.
   The latest FBI numbers available show that the nation's rural
counties reported 1,233 murder arrests in 1987, for a rate of 5.7
murders for 100,000 residents. The average rate for all U.S. cities
was 10.2 while the average for suburbs was 4.9.
   Rural murder shatters the idyllic image that many have of
country life, and indeed, it bucks the trend of most crime. Most
rural places have lower rates of theft, vandalism, rape and assault
than do more populous areas.
   Murder statistics may differ, sociologists suggest, because
killing can be a very personal affair.
   ``Homicide is something that typically occurs among people who
have a close relationship with each other,'' said Kenneth
Wilkinson, a rural sociologist at Pennsylvania State University.
   One theory holds that in rural areas, people have a higher
proportion of primary relationships _ an academic way of saying
that everybody knows everybody else's business. When life turns
sour, an individual may lash out at people he knows well, and that
can be almost anyone in the area.
   Wilkinson offered another possible cause: the erosion of
community bonds in rural areas.
   ``The romantic images of the rural past indicate a closeness of
community,'' he said. ``In contrast to our image of the way things
used to be, rural areas tend to have weak community relationships.''
   The small town once may have supplied most of a person's social,
emotional and economic needs, but now country dwellers often must
travel far to urban centers to satisfy those needs _ or leave them
unsatisfied until that leads to violence.
   Such theories are unsatisfying when the statistics turn specific
and the incomprehensible happens close to home. Such was the case
June 7 in Graham.
   Tom and Rutheda LaCrosse, both 63, were well-liked and ran their
farms as cleanly as their personal lives. Tom had operated his
400-cow dairy, one of the county's largest, for 23 years. Rutheda
was judged young enough at heart to be elected queen of this year's
Pierce County Fair.
   Neighbors say they were people who wouldn't hesitate to help a
friend in trouble, and such a friend was Eileen May Gehring. She
had problems with her estranged husband, Kenneth Gehring, who was
ignoring a judge's order to stay away from his wife. On June 6,
while his wife visited the LaCrosses, Gehring arrived and drove her
car away. A sheriff's deputy gave her a ride home.
   Gehring returned the next morning, apparently looking for his
wife. According to sheriff's reports, Gehring drove into the
farmyard and confronted truck driver Kirby Hull outside the milking
barn. After some angry words, Gehring shot Hull.
   Tom LaCrosse and a farm worker rushed from the barn's office to
find Gehring holding a .22-caliber rifle. Gehring forced LaCrosse
into the farmhouse, and there he killed the farmer and Mrs.
LaCrosse, then shot himself in the head.
   Investigators said Gehring had no criminal history, and there
was no indication the slayings were motivated by anything but
unresolved anger over his impending divorce.
   The frightening frequency of urban slayings has conditioned many
people to expect such grisly events in big cities. But it's just
not supposed to happen in a place like Graham. The rural murder
rate, while high, spreads itself across huge and sparsely populated
areas, making murder in any one small town a rare event.
   It can breed fear of crime and fear of strangers, which
Wilkinson said is not only unfortunate but misdirected, ``because
when trouble arises, usually the killer is someone you know.''
After a slaying, voters seeking a scapegoat have been known to oust
the local sheriff, who may be more used to investigating bicycle
thefts than homicide.
   ``In rural areas where homicides happen, it's wrenching,''
Wilkinson said. ``People wonder, `What's happening to our
community?'''
   Down at Graham Auto Parts, manager Bob Sorenson mourns the
farmer who used to grab him playfully in a headlock until Sorenson
grew old enough to put the hold on LaCrosse.
   ``It's hard to believe you could know somebody that long, and
that he could go so quickly,'' Sorenson said.
   The funeral was weeks ago now, and talk at the post office and
Sorenson's store is back to the county fair and carburetors. But
Graham will never be quite the same. A measure of its innocence was
stolen that day in June.
   ``It has made us more cautious,'' said Karen Stannard. ``I think
there are doors being locked now that were never locked before.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   David Foster is the AP Northwest regional
reporter, based in Seattle.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday PMs, Aug. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
