<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1038EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-RuralHousing-Success Adv08   07-31 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rural Housing-Success, Adv 08,0814</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday PMs, Aug. 8, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Homes and Hope for Folks `On the Fringe'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Rural Housing</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLIVE HILL, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Carew is an ambassador in the hollows
and hills of central Appalachia. His credentials are hammer and
nail. His assignment: wipe out Third World living conditions.
   It seems a daunting task in this corner of eastern Kentucky
where dirt floors, leaking tar-paper roofs and rickety outhouses
aren't Dust Bowl memories, but modern-day realities. For some
folks, heat is a luxury, hot water a convenience beyond their
modest dreams.
   ``They're on the fringe of the economy,'' said Carew, director
of Frontier Housing Inc., a non-profit agency for low-income
people. ``It's Third World living.
   ``When you're living in a cold, lousy, dangerous house, how
happy can you be?'' he added. ``You've got to put up with your
basic survival everyday.''
   Carew's agency is among hundreds of groups across rural America
that build homes and bring hope to people whose shelter often is
little more than a shack insulated with rotting cardboard,
illuminated by a bare bulb.
   Since 1974, Frontier Housing has built 165 homes and
rehabilitated 75 others in a four-county farming and timber area
where poverty rates range from 23 percent to 39 percent.
   It's just a start, considering that in parts of this region one
of every four or five houses is substandard, Carew said. ``If we're
building 20 houses a year, it's going to take a long time.''
   Still, there are plenty of successes.
   Take Ethel Ward, a feisty 64-year-old woman who lives in this
tiny community with her son, daughter-in-law and granddaughter in a
neat-as-a-pin three-bedroom home Frontier built in 1988.
   They only have to look in their backyard to see how far they've
come. There sits what's left of their old frame home _ two dark
rooms with a roof that was caving in, roaches, rats, one electrical
circuit, no hot water, tub, shower or toilet.
   ``We didn't have enough room to turn around in. I was afraid the
house was going to burn,'' she said. ``... But what could I do
about it? I wasn't drawing much income. My boy (a sawmill employee)
wasn't working much.''
   Her daughter-in-law, Maggie Davis, said there was no privacy
because the rooms had no doors, no place for her 14-year-old to
study and no way to keep the house dry or clean because of leaks
and bugs she feared would crawl on her at night.
   ``When you don't have any hot water, it's kind of hard to do
anything,'' added Mrs. Davis, who suffers from high blood pressure.
``You felt like your child wasn't clean enough. ... She never did
bring no one home; (she felt) they'd go off and say something.''
   Gayle and Billy Williams, who live in a converted smokehouse
about 30 miles away in Midland, also will see a change in their
surroundings this summer when Frontier remodels their house and
adds a bathroom.
   It will be Mrs. Williams' first indoor toilet. She's 61.
   ``We've managed it OK, but now we're getting older,'' she said.
   Carew said many people in substandard housing rationalize their
plight. ``If you start telling yourself there's a better way to
live, you do yourself in,'' he said. ``It's a means of survival.''
   Helen Barker knew life had more to offer, but it always seemed
beyond her grasp.
   Now, Frontier has built a house for her, her husband, Danny, a
seasonal truck driver, and their five children. For 10 years, they
rented apartments, some with broken pipes and without toilets.
   ``After you have moved around so much, the stability of a home
means so much,'' she said. ``It takes so much worry off your mind.
Seeing it built, it's like a dream come true ... knowing it's going
to be mine. It tickles me to death.''
   The Barkers struggle to pay their $150 monthly rent. Their
monthly mortgage payments will be about $100. Frontier, which
receives state and federal funds, will pay one-third of the
payments up to five years. The Barkers and many other families
Frontier helps receive mortgages through the Farmers Home
Administration.
   For months, Danny Barker would make nightly stops to check on
the progress of the house and report back to his wife. A few weeks
ago, they settled in their new home on a hill deep among the sturdy
Kentucky oaks.
   Mrs. Barker has many plans but says, ``I'll probably sit around
with a smile on my face for the first two months.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sharon Cohen is the AP Midwest regional
reporter, based in Chicago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tuesday PMs, Aug. 8</NOTE>
