<FIRST>a a PM-RuralWomen-ReachingOut Adv09   07-31 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rural Women-Reaching Out, Adv 09,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday PMs, Aug. 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Farm Wife Finds New Reward in Public Service</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Rural Women-Entrepreneurs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVEN, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A traditional farm wife and mom, Lois
Schlickau paid her public service dues with the library board and
4-H kids, the Cow-belles and Hereford Auxiliary.
   Now, as the first woman president in the 117-year history of the
Kansas Board of Agriculture, she's a pro at Robert's Rules of Order
and the political sidestep.
   The mother of four children chairs the board responsible for
regulating Kansas' farm industries. It also sets policy for the
state Department of Agriculture and appoints its secretary. Under
Mrs. Schlickau's leadership the board has sponsored seminars for
producers on the Farm Credit System and Latin American debt.
   ``She brings thoroughness, leadership, and credibility to the
post,'' said Kansas Gov. Mike Hayden. ``Lois has been a strong
leader... and she commands respect from throughout the agricultural
community.''
   Mrs. Schlickau cites her partnership with her husband, George,
in running the family's cattle operation, as her training ground
for leadership.
   ``There are a lot of women already involved in ag policy,'' said
Mrs. Schlickau, 55. ``If you really are interested and want to
accept the challenge, the opportunities are there.
   ``Agriculture is changing and we have to be willing to change
with the times. If you stay on the farm you can't be content to
just sit on the tractor, then take your crops in and say, `What
will you give me?' We have to be involved in marketing and
promotion and new ideas.''
   A director and past president of the Kansas Hereford Auxiliary,
director of the Kansas Agri-Women, a member of the Kansas Farm
Bureau, and on the 4-H Advisory Board, she stuck to traditional
female jobs ``because I'm not a woman's libber'' until a friend
suggested she run for the state agriculture board.
   ``I said to him, `You know women don't serve on that board.' But
he told me, `Lois, it doesn't matter whether you're a woman or a
man, you are a capable person,''' she recalled.
   ``So I ran. And I won.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Aug. 9</NOTE>
