<SECOND>BC-History, Adv06,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 6</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, Aug. 6, the 218th day of 1989. There are 147
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Aug. 6, 1945, the United States dropped the atomic bomb on
Hiroshima, Japan, killing an estimated 80,000 people outright and
obliterating more than half the city in the first use of a nuclear
weapon in warfare.
   On this date:
   In 1787, the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia began to
debate the articles contained in a draft of the U.S. Constitution.
   In 1806, the Holy Roman Empire went out of existence as Emperor
Francis I abdicated.
   In 1825, Bolivia declared its independence from Peru.
   In 1890, the electric chair was first used, at a prison in
Auburn, N.Y. The execution of convicted murderer William Kemmler
raised a storm of controversy over whether the method was humane.
   In 1914, Austria-Hungary declared war against Russia and Serbia
declared war against Germany.
   In 1926, Warner Brothers premiered its ``Vitaphone''
sound-on-disc movie system in New York, with the feature film,
``Don Juan.''
   In 1926, Gertrude Ederle of New York became the first American
woman to swim the English channel, in some 14{ hours.
   In 1948, Bob Mathias won the decathlon at the London Olympics.
   In 1962, Jamaica became an independent dominion within the
British Commonwealth.
   In 1965, President Lyndon B. Johnson signed the Voting Rights
Act into law.
   In 1978, Pope Paul VI died of a heart attack in his summer
residence at Castel Gandolfo at age 80.
   In 1986, William J. Schroeder, the world's longest-surviving
recipient of a permanent artificial heart, died after living 620
days with the Jarvik 7 pump.
   Ten years ago: An earthquake measuring 5.9 on the Richter scale
shook the San Francisco Bay area, toppling lights, knocking out
power and shaking skyscrapers.
   Five years ago: Carl Lewis won his second gold medal of the 1984
Summer Olympics, this one in the long jump, as he leapt a distance
of 28 feet, \ inch.
   One year ago: Efforts to bring peace to the Persian Gulf war got
an important boost as Iraq's president said his country would agree
to a cease-fire with Iran provided the Iranians promised to hold
direct talks immediately after the truce took effect.
   Today's Birthdays: Actor Robert Mitchum is 72. Entrepeneur Sir
Freddie Laker is 67. Actor Peter Bonerz is 51. Actress Soleil Moon
Frye is 13.
   Thought for Today: ``The Atomic Age is here to stay _ but are
we?'' _ Bennett Cerf, American publisher (1898-1971).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance Sunday, Aug. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
