<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1624EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-RuralWomen-SettlingIn Adv09   07-31 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rural Women-Settling In, Adv 09,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday AMs, Aug. 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eastern Activist Becomes Montana Farm Wife</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Rural-Stress on Women</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FROID, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The granddaughter, daughter, and sister of
lawyers, Annie Debevoise thought she'd take some time off working
in the West before returning to law school in Vermont.
   In 1987, she hired on as a $9,000-a-year organizer with the
Northern Plains Resource Council, a grassroots rural advocacy group
based in Billings, Mont.
   Single at 26, she took a lot of kidding from cowboys and their
wives, who were always trying to fix her up. One day a bunch of
them standing around at the Froid grain elevator dared her to drive
the 16 miles of backroads over to Andy Ostby's house and introduce
herself.
   She did. And now, at 28, she's Mrs. Andy Ostby, ranch wife.
   Instead of learning about torts and statutes, Mrs. Ostby now
knows how to brand cattle, help birth calves, and properly load up
a pack horse.
   There's no vacation in the winter because the cattle have to be
fed, none in the spring because the calves are being born, and no
time off in the summer, either, because the crops have to be
harvested.
   ``Andy's told me we might squeeze in a week in November,'' Mrs.
Ostby said.
   As hundreds of farm women throughout Montana seek employment off
the land to earn extra money, she says she feels lucky to be able
to stay home and learn about her new life.
   ``I take it one day at a time,'' she said, sitting on the porch
of her 37-year-old husband's family home. The house is surrounded
by the rolling green of wheat and grass. Neighbors are out of sight
over the next rise.
   ``I want to learn everything I can, I want to be Andy's partner,
I want to help make this the best ranch it can be.''
   She is a stranger who came into the conservative, slow-to-change
Montana prairie country as an Eastern liberal outsider. She tries
to win acceptance by working hard and keeping quiet.
   She now reads farm journals cover-to-cover. This spring she
bought her own bull.
   ``I was the only woman at the sale. I didn't have any idea how
to load him into the truck, but some of the other ranchers helped
me. When I got home, I figured out how to get him out of the truck
by myself. I'm making progress.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Aug. 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
