<DOCNO> AP890731-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1409EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   07-31 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0792</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Salaam Bombay!'' (Virgin Vision, Inc., English subtitles.
VHS-Beta, $79.95)
   
   ``Salaam Bombay!'' is a heartrending look at the homeless street
children of Bombay, India. But its meanings and nuances transcend
that exotic locale.
   The film, which won a number of international film awards in
1988, is a rivetting portrayal of how 20th-century societies,
including so-called civilized ones, are devouring their young,
alternately selling them, or selling them short.
   Producer-director Mira Nair traveled the streets of Bombay,
fascinated by the resilience of the thousands of children who
survive by their wits in a squalid world of dirt, drugs and
prostitution.
   She decided to tell their story, not with actors, but with
children she gathered from those very backstreets.
   ``Salaam Bombay!'' is the story of 10-year-old Krishna.
Abandoned first by his mother, then by the traveling circus he
joins, he travels to Bombay hoping to earn 500 rupees to take back
to his mother.
   Krishna acquires street wisdom and a toughness that even leads
to a murder. But somehow, almost miraculously, he keeps a
child-like empathy even as he is failing in his own hopes. He
befriends a desperate drug addict, and comforts an abject
16-year-old sold by her own mother to a brothel.
   The film's producers decided to use proceeds to establish
learning centers for the street children of Bombay and Delhi.
   ``Salaam Bombay!'' is not rated. It has no objectionable
language or sexual encounters, but the themes of street life are
nonetheless unvarnished.
   It is a truly exceptional film.
   _ By Lee Mitgang, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Crusoe'' (Virgin Vision. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated PG-13.)
   
   ``Crusoe,'' based on the tale of a shipwreck on a tropical
island, is a lush and aesthectically pleasing movie, and as ripe
with moral dilemmas as the burdened coconut trees swaying on the
beach.
   In ``Crusoe,'' values come crashing down and savagely splinter
the beliefs of the movie's star, Aidan Quinn.
   Quinn plays a greedy young 19th-century slave trader who tempts
fate by taking one final and risky expedition to round up more
blacks from Africa. But his ship becomes ensnared in a vicious
autumn storm and all aboard perish, except for Quinn, who winds up
sprawled on a desolate beach.
   Crusoe learns to endure the solitude and fashions a comfortable
shelter for himself on the picturesque island.
   Before long his isolation is interrupted by visiting natives. He
rescues one from a human sacrifice and decides keep him as a slave.
But the native later escapes and is killed.
   In a provocative twist, Crusoe becomes the hunted and is trapped
by another islander. But the two men reach an accord and build
something of a friendship.
   The film's ending is the final test of Crusoe's new respect for
the man he once wanted to enslave.
   Director Caleb Deschanel so effectively captures the panoramic
beauty of the island setting _ with its creamy white sand beaches,
dense verdant forests and crystal blue tide pools _ one can almost
taste the salt spray in the breeze.
   There also is very little dialogue, but the engrossing visuals
and the moral struggles make for compelling viewing.
   _ By Patricia Bibby, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Thrilled to Death'' (Republic. VHS-Beta, $79.95. Rated R)
   
   B-movie fans, beware. ``Thrilled to Death'' is an A, as in
absolutely awlful.
   The script is bad, the acting terrible and even the filming is
poor with washed-out colors and fuzziness.
   It's a movie that uses the backdrop of a swingers' club to
unravel a tale of murder and drug dealing. Along the way, there's
some nudity, strong language and graphic violence.
   Two couples meet and become friends. Only one couple has set up
the other to take a fall in a drug-and-murder doublecross.
   Cliff Bahner and Rebecca Lynn play a mystery novelist and his
wife; Richard Maris and Christine Moore are the bad guys.
   _ By Chris French Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
