<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1418EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReview Adv00   07-31 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Review, Adv 00,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Good Evening'' (Warner Bros.) _ Marshall Crenshaw
   
   Marshall Crenshaw has spent a meandering solo career trying to
live up to the promise of his sparkling 1982 debut. He's finally
done it on ``Good Evening,'' largely because he's changed many of
the elements that made him a success in the first place.
   That debut was a pristine piece of pop-rock, hearkening back to
the days of Buddy Holly. But the stripped-down sound eventually
became a trap.
   ``Good Evening'' has Crenshaw significantly toughening and
filling out his sound with the help of slide and pedal steel
guitarists such as David Lindley, Sonny Landreth and James Burton.
John Mellencamp drummer Kenny Aronoff completes the rock 'n' roll
kick.
   It's welcome power behind a guy who, rightly or wrongly, had
developed a reputation as a rock 'n' roll wimp, mostly because of
his sweet voice and sweet songs.
   Crenshaw also recognizes his limitations as a writer for the
first time. He's always been able to create a couple of catchy
tunes per record, but is unable to sustain interest through a full
album.
   Here he interprets songs by Richard Thompson, John Hiatt, Bobby
Fuller and the Isley Brothers. He even seeks co-writing help on
some of his own songs. The welcome diversity of voices make his own
contributions, particularly ``She Hates to Go Home,'' sound that
much better.
   The cliche-ridden ``Radio Girl'' is really the only mistake on
this 10-song album. The Thompson-written ``Valerie'' and ``Good
Hearts'' are particularly appealing.
   It took some time _ probably too much _ for Crenshaw to find
what's right for him. But the rewards here are plentiful.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
