<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 0550EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Home:Victorian     07-31 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Home: Victorian,0810</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Furnishings: Victorian</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY700, NY701</HEAD>
<HEAD>By BARBARA MAYER</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROWAYTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Over its 100-year existence, Wendy and
John Wheat's Victorian house has undergone many renovations _ not
all of them fortunate.
   ``The worst thing done to the house was to put asbestos shingles
up. They're known as the skin disease of house renovation,'' says
Mrs. Wheat. Though the Wheats hated the shingles, they liked the
lines, interior arrangement and location of the four-bedroom house
in Rowayton when they bought it four years ago.
   Today, what was once an unprepossessing home is now a charming
restored Victorian decorated with a pleasing mix of American
country, Victorian and contemporary furnishings.
   The Wheats have given the house a new lease on life with a
structural and decorative facelift, which has included new exterior
siding and insulation, the addition of architectural elements, and
new paint and wallpaper.
   Substituting better quality and more architecturally interesting
doors and windows has made a subtle but substantial difference in
the appearance of their home. The change has brought out the
original character of the Victorian and provided a greater sense of
quality for a relatively small outlay.
   The couple spent about $60,000 on the renovation, which they
financed through a home equity loan and an inheritance.
   The largest and most costly job involved removing the shingles
and putting up new clapboard siding with Victorian fish scale
shingles in the peaks. The resurfacing and installation of
appropriate architectural trim has exposed the good lines of the
original house. The most spectacular interior improvement has been
redoing the master bedroom, bath and dressing area.
   The Wheats hired a professional designer to help them. ``We knew
it would be a little more expensive to use a decorator, but we felt
that we would end up with a better job and that it would add more
value to the house,'' says Mrs. Wheat, a recreational therapist who
works with seniors. Her husband works in marketing for a bank.
   They chose Westport decorator Beverly Ellsley, whose work they
had seen and liked in showhouses and magazines.
   ``After only 10 minutes, she pointed out every single thing that
bothered me about the house, and all her suggestions were just
right. As a professional, she was able to cut corners in some
places and she did come in at budget. She did not impose her own
taste,'' says Mrs. Wheat.
   The home is furnished with an eclectic mix of American country
and antique furniture, English scrubbed pine, a few Victorian
pieces and a contemporary sofa. Much of the place's charm comes
from mementos and artwork which mean a great deal to them.
   Paintings by Wheat's father, a profesional artist, coexist
comfortably with his own artworks in wood as well as crafts the
couple has collected during travels in Mexico and Greece.
   The Wheats exercised frugality by selecting furnishings
judiciously and by doing some of the work themselves. For example,
they splurged on built-in custom cabinetry in the master bedroom,
but pickled the white pine cabinetry themselves, saving about
$1,500 to $2,000.
   The bed in the eclectic Victorian-contemporary country room is
covered in several layers of expensive sheets by Ralph Lauren. But
Mrs. Wheat bought some of the sheets in an outlet shop. She used
material from a flat king-sized sheet that cost about $100 to sew a
border on a plain white sheet. Leftover fabric from that sheet
eventually will be used to cover throw pillows. Lace curtains at
the windows in the living room are inexpensive panels purchased for
about $4 each in a craft supplies outlet.
   The bedroom-dressing area was remodeled to provide more storage
and better light. Three unmatched windows were replaced with two on
each side of the room that match and a new half-round window
framing a sunburst design, set dramatically high above the bed at
the ceiling line.
   A king-sized bed is now placed against the pine bookshelf wall
with built-in nightstands. Opposite the bed, a wall of built-in
cabinetry has mirrored doors above and drawers below. Normally
inaccessible high open shelves in both units are used for
decorative storage.
   The couple retiled the bathroom with a blue and white
checkerboard floor and installed a new shower.
   Now that the major work is done, the Wheats say they are
content. Some day they hope to redo the deck as a Victorian porch,
add a second screened porch and possibly do over the kitchen.
   A dream is to put in a small home gym, say the couple, who have
been married 13 years. But meanwhile, ``it's nice to look around
and be really satisfied with what we see,'' says Mrs. Wheat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
