<DOCNO> AP890731-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 0604EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Home:Fakes     07-31 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Home: Fakes,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Furnishings: Fakes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY705</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA MAYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   There may not be more phony antiques than there used to be, but
Americans are certainly more aware of them, says Samuel Pennington,
editor of the Maine Antique Digest.
   However, consumers can protect themselves, according to
Pennington and Myrna Kaye, an authority on antique American
furniture.
   Keep an open mind and bring a bright light when you go shopping
for antique furniture, says Kaye, author of ``Fake, Fraud or
Genuine? Identifying Authentic American Antique Furniture.''
   Although a good deal of the antique American furniture on the
market is not as described, in her opinion, a questioning attitude
and careful examination can help one to spot fakes.
   Kaye says that next to a questioning attitude, a strong light is
the most useful aid in identifying furniture that may be posing as
something it is not. She carries a 500-watt portable lamp and uses
it whenever the light is not adequate for complete scrutiny of a
piece. A good flashlight can achieve the same results.
   Other tools Kaye takes along on antique furniture-hunting jaunts
include a yardstick and calipers to measure shrinkage.
   Since old wood furniture invariably shows signs of shrinkage,
taking measurements in several places helps you spot shrinkage and,
hence, confirm that a piece is old. Calipers can be used to take
the dimensions of the round turned parts of wood furniture.
   She also carries tweezers and a needle. The needle is to probe
what look like wormholes. A drill, rather than worms, made any hole
that is deeper than one-eighth of an inch. The tweezers are useful
in extracting splinters which are a common hazard when running your
bare hands over a piece of wood furniture to see if it has the same
degree of roughness all over.
   The types of fakes she says are most common include ``married''
pieces, consisting of parts of different pieces that have been put
together; assembled sets in which one or more elements are new, and
furniture that has been embellished _ for example, with an extra
fan carving _ so that it looks better or more expensive than the
original piece.
   The outright fraud made specifically to deceive is the rarest,
she says, because it takes too much time and money to produce it
and rarely would the anticipated price justify this kind of effort.
   The best indication of authenticity is consistency, adds Kaye.
To ascertain if a piece is consistent, look at each detail of
construction separately. She starts by sizing the piece up to get
an overall impression. Then she opens and removes drawers, looking
at the back and base of cabinets and chairs. She says that
well-finished, unseen areas of furniture excite her suspicion
because American cabinetmakers of the past rarely, if ever,
finished parts that didn't show.
   Since there are no statistics, there is no way to quantify the
number of fakes, according to Pennington. But awareness of the
potential for faking old things is certainly increasing.
   ``Museum-trained experts have educated the public to look at old
things with more awareness. They have taught us that pieces without
major restoration and in pristine condition are more valuable,'' he
said.
   Although any piece of furniture that is 200 years old would
almost have to have some repairs, when virtually rebuilt, its claim
to age might be at least debatable, he said.
   Pennington says the growing public appetite for the country
antique look has led to many reproductions of decorative wares. The
advantage is that you can buy a reproduction much less expensively
than the real thing.
   But if the new piece isn't indelibly marked, eventually it will
probably make its way into the antiques trade. It's difficult to
tell age, especially after an item has acquired some of the patina
of age.
   He advises not to buy art from a stranger who calls you up on
the telephone. Buy from someone with a good reputation. Educate
yourself and beware of things that are too good to be true or
priced too low in comparison to the market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890731-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 0604EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Home:Reproductions     07-31 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Home: Reproductions,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Furnishings: Reproductions</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY709</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA MAYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Once, those who could afford them invariably chose antiques over
reproductions. Nowadays, when the best original design is often
unavailable, too expensive, the wrong dimensions, or too fragile,
the reproduction can be the better choice.
   This change in thinking is due to a variety of factors. For one
thing, many reproductions now have more accurate finishes so they
don't stick out like a sore thumb when mixed with antiques. That
means mixing a little old with a lot of new is a good method of
getting the right look, less expensively.
   Second, an eclectic room is considered more desirable than the
completely accurate period room that was once was fashionable;
comfort has become more important than historical accuracy for many
people.
   Few decorators would hesitate to use plushly upholstered but
anachronistic seating in a historic room, especially since there
really was no comfortable American upholstery in the 18th century,
according to decorator Stanley Hura.
   In the dining room, an extension table of modern origin is often
a necessity. And in the traditional bedroom or family room that
lacks closets, installing a modern wall system may be the only
solution. Hura, for example, recently placed a floor-to-ceiling
wall system in an American traditional bedroom for needed storage
space. He gave the unit a built-in look by installing molding
around it, he said.
   When combining old and new furniture of more than one style, a
few precautions can prevent the pieces from clashing with one
another.
   Certain styles, even though from different periods, look good
together, says Hura. For example, Japanese, Shaker and Scandinavian
modern combine well. English Regency and Chinese furniture work
together. The rounded forms of the 18th-century French pieces and
art nouveau and Victorian also marry well.
   If you're furnishing a formal Victorian room and need storage,
remember that armoires are in character with that style. If you
have contemporary lacquered cabinetry, add Oriental or art deco
accessories and reproductions. At the windows you might choose
pleated shades or Shoji screens. Simple Regency chairs would not be
out of place in this room.
   ``The forms of the pieces dictate how they combine. You could
mix a 17th-century Italian table and chairs and contemporary
furniture and lamps because the lines work well together,'' Hura
says.
   Do-it-yourself decorators can learn their own taste preferences
by studying decorating books and magazines.
   ``The most appealing homes are the ones where people put
together what they love. The accurate period room is for museums,
not for living,'' says Hura.
   One of the marks of an interesting room is the unexpected
touches it contains, especially in the form of accessories.
According to Fran Laufer, who imports unusual accessories, colorful
and exotic items are in demand. For example, relatively affordable
Indian paintings on fabric known as pichwais and Burmese
embroideries are being selected by those seeking distinction
without breaking the bank.
   The decorators she deals with rarely take the item as shipped
and use it in a room. They further embellish it to make it more
important. For example, one decorator created an unusual wall
hanging from a large piece of Burmese embroidered fabric. She had
it stuffed to give it dimension and bring out its interesting
pattern, then mounted it on silk linen and framed it in gold leaf
before hanging it on a wall.
   Another decorator chose three colorful 22-inch Chinese porcelain
jardinieres. She had rosewood bases made for each one, set them in
place in a dining room and then had a one-inch thick glass top made
to cover them, creating a unique dining table.
   Designers often use antiquities such as etched bronze drums from
Thailand, old Korean vessels or wedding baskets from Indonesia as
cocktail table bases. Korean coin chests of a dark wood with iron
hardware become side tables with storage capacity and Coromandel
screens are turned into cabinet fronts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890731-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 0605EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Home:Basics     07-31 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Home: Basics,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Furnishings: Basics</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY708</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The first-home owner doesn't have to settle for make-do
furniture because of a budget, says a furnishings and design editor.
   ``Instead, start with flexible basics that will look terrific
right now, and also will make great building blocks for future
decorating schemes,'' says Denise L. Caringer, of Better Homes and
Gardens magazine.
   Don't settle for lower quality and don't feel locked into a look
or color scheme that will be difficult or costly to change later
on. Instead, she has these suggestions:
   _ Skip the busy wall coverings and fancy window wear. Instead,
slick up and unify the background with white paint, white window
blinds, shades or curtains, and, if possible, neutral floor
coverings.
   This will produce an airy, expansive look, and will also make a
neutral ``canvas'' on which style can be easily created.
   _ Avoid matching ``suites'' of furniture. Instead, choose a mix
of well-designed basics that can be shifted to other rooms or other
homes. A bedroom dresser, for example, has limited use, but an
armoire fits in virtually anywhere, she says.
   Consider modular storage pieces _ bookcases and stacking cubes _
with optional doors, drawers and shelves.
   _ Furnish a sitting spot with four wicker lounge chairs instead
of buying an expensive sofa for the living room. Float the chairs
in a cloverleaf-shaped grouping in the middle of the room and
anchor them with an area rug. Wicker is versatile, she says, so you
won't lock yourself into a changeless look. Fabric cushions can set
the mood.
   Later on, you can move them to a porch or split them up, using a
pair with a new sofa and moving the others to bedrooms.
   _ If the living room does not have a natural focal point, like a
great window or a fireplace, lean a second-hand fireplace surround
against the wall and fill the opening with plants, put two or three
low-cost white bookcases together, or place an antique bench or a
couple of low chests side by side and hang an oversized poster
above them.
   _ Stacked books next to a chair make a great resting place for a
cup or glass. Turn a cube, basket or a concrete block into a coffee
table by topping it with a piece of glass.
   _ Simple, well-designed lamps, such as flex arm architects
lamps, ceramic-base table lamps, or sleek metal floor lamps, can be
supplemented with clamp-on spotlights to highlight artwork and
canister-style uplights to wake up dull corners.
   _ For dining, a white outdoor table and casual chairs _ wicker,
molded plastic, metal, or wood-and-canvas _ serve as
``summer-house'' companions to the airy living room scheme. For a
more formal or traditional look, buy quality dining chairs and team
them with a round, skirted-to-the-floor dining table.
   _ Let your personality color the surroundings. Family photos?
Seashells? Books? Baskets? Group small treasures for a bigger
impact.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890731-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 0606EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Home:Stores     07-31 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Home: Stores,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Furnishings: Stores</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY710</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA MAYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``I've never used a decorator because I like to be in control,
but I'm very aware of esthetics,'' says Boston stockbroker Ginny
Houston. So when she found a store that carried the unusual country
style furniture and accessories she prefers, she was delighted.
   She still prefers to make all the final decisions, but likes
having access to fabrics sold only through decorators and to
services such as drapery workrooms. ``It's a real time saver,''
says Houston, who is typical of a new breed of home furnishings
customers.
   They're sophisticated, well-traveled, affluent and aware of the
latest decorating styles. And they see no reason why they should be
denied access to some furniture and accessories because they prefer
not to hire a designer.
   To cater to this new breed, high-style furniture stores have
been opening in ever greater numbers across the country. These
stores are selling the public furnishings that formerly were
available mainly through designers and architects. Many also show
and sell the work of craftsmen, which otherwise would be
inaccessible.
   What started as a mere trickle has grown to a good-sized stream
not only in the largest population centers, but in smaller cities
all across the country _ stores like Urban Architecture in Detroit;
Oggi in Kansas City, Mo.; Current in Seattle; Verlaine in
Providence, R.I., and Luminaire in the Miami area.
   These retailers are breaking down former barriers, which may
lead to a revolution in furniture retailing, according to some
observers, by selling to both consumers and the trade, often
cutting prices below those of design showrooms, and by developing
alternative sources of supply among craftsmen and foreign
manufacturers.
   One example of the new style retailer is Keith Johnson who with
several partners founded Urban Architecture in Detroit. The store
carries high-style contemporary Italian design from Memphis Milano
and 15 other Italian manufacturers.
   ``When I got started in this business I hated the idea that the
public couldn't come in and that there was a double price system
for the furniture,'' says Johnson, who cut prices and sold to both
designers and the general public.
   His success proves there is a much larger market for advanced
furniture design than most people imagine, says the retailer.
   Lowering prices and putting the furniture on a retail sales
floor where anybody can come in and see it, he says, will make the
furniture as popular in the United States as it is in Europe, where
it usually sells for much less.
   ``I wanted to create a store for a new kind of customer, one for
whom the home is the status symbol of the 1990s,'' says Judy
George, who opened Domain in Chestnut Hill, Mass., in 1986. Since
then, Domain has grown to be a 10-store chain in New England and
more additions are planned.
   George says it's knowledge that defines her customers, not
necessarily affluence. ``Not all are rich, but they are all very
hip. They travel, like movies, read shelter magazines and usually
don't hire a decorator because they want to do it themselves,'' she
says.
   ``It's a small constituency, but a very savvy one,'' says Susan
Symonds, who started Verlaine in Providence about six years ago.
Access to the fabrics and wallcoverings normally available only
through decorators is so important to some customers that they call
Symonds from other areas of the country.
   ``These clients find it frustrating to see things in magazines
and then not to be able to buy them,'' says Symonds.
   If knowledge is one aspect of the new customer, lack of shopping
time is another, says George. So a store's edited version of
interesting new merchandise is a time saver.
   ``We are doing Russian, Gothic, French country, English chintz,
we've got rattan from Poland, we've got South American,'' says
George. ``This group appreciates ethnic furnishings and likes to
include something of their past in their home. But if I get too
serious, I don't sell it.''
   In fact, George and other retailers of this ilk rely on
different resources than the usual. She shops craft fairs to find
talented people and then gives them a large enough order to enable
them to set up production faculties. Currently, 10 artists in
Vermont and three in Maine make furnishings for Domain.
   Although the new-style stores have much in common withach is usually
a reflection of the passions of the
individual who started it, rather than of a management game plan.
Consequently, most change merchandise frequently as the owner finds
some new enthusiasm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
