<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Furnishings: Moderne</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY707</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA MAYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Early 20th-century moderne is a look that is gaining in
popularity.
   Grounded primarily on neoclassical styles _ especially the
streamlined forms of art deco _ this versatile design theme results
in a room that is quieter and more pared down than the ubiquitous
country style.
   Yet, moderne is as adaptable as country and works well in both
the city and the country. By judicious selection of some of its
many elements, moderne style decorating can range from a
contemporary to a traditional room. It will add archite and
can be painted. There are a variety of reproduction patterns in the
Anaglypta and Lincrusta wallcovering lines which are manufactured
in England by Crown Relief Decorations.
   (For information on where to buy Anaglypta and Lincrusta
wallcoverings east of the Mississippi, phone toll free
1-800-824-4777; for outlets west of the Mississippi, phone
1-800-992-8700.)
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FLOATING WINE?=
   The bottles seem to hang in the air with this six-sided wine
rack module _ the Vintage Keeper _ that suspends the bottles in
transparent high impact thermoplastic that won't chip or crack from
normal use.
   A lattice-like configuration allows ambient air to circulate
freely about the bottles, contributing to their coolness. The open
design also inhibits condensate from forming on the cork, which can
cause seepage or mildew.
   The labels can be read through this new wine rack, introduced by
Spectrum International, Inc., P.O. Box 353, Shrewsbury, N.J. 07702.
</TEXT>
