<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 0831EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Spain-BigBang     07-31 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spain-Big Bang,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Markets Rise On First Day Under New Trading System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spain's stock markets rose Monday, the
first day of trading under a new system that introduced the most
sweeping changes in the exchange's 158-year-old history.
   The reform, known here as ``El Big Bang,'' is designed to
broaden the Spanish markets' trading base, tighten disclosure
controls to eliminate insider trading and bring the stock exchanges
in line with others in Europe.
   Provisional figures indicated the Madrid general index reached
303.93, up 1.70 over Friday. Valencia rose 1.76 points to 245.06
while Barcelona's index registered 106.47, up .73 points. The
Bilbao market was closed due to a regional holiday.
   Dealers said trading on the three exchanges remained light,
largely due to investors concern about the changeover process and
recent government moves to restrict credit and slow down the
country's overheated economy.
   ``Today was absolutely calm. There were no problems and the
market was up,'' said Jaime Sanz, spokesman for the Madrid Stock
Exchange, where about 70 percent of all Spanish trading takes place.
   In a ceremony Friday marking the last day of trading under the
old system, National Securities Commission President Luis Carlos
Croissier said the new market ``will be characterized by
transparency, greater technical capacity and competition.''
   The securities commission, set up nine months ago to implement
the June 1988 market reform law, is the markets' chief supervisory
and watchdog authority.
   The law, which took effect Saturday, converted the four
exchanges into private entities owned and managed by newly created
brokerages and broker-dealer companies.
   It eliminated civil servant stockbrokers' monopoly on trading
rights and eventually will integrate the stock exchanges in Madrid,
Barcelona, Bilbao and Valencia into a single, computer automated
trading system.
   Fifty-one brokerages and broker-dealers have been registered on
the Madrid exchange, but analysts say half of them may disappear
within two years because of increased competition in the wake of
the reform.
   So far, 23 companies whose shares account for 22 percent of
trading volume have been listed on the computerized system, set up
in April and modeled after the one pioneered by the Toronto Stock
Exchange.
   Croissier has predicted that more than 50 percent of the total
trading volume in Spain would take place in the new system by the
end of the year.
   The old system, where prices are fixed in two daily open-outcry
sessions on the exchange floors, is to exist side by side with
continuous computerized trading until all shares switch over, Sanz
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
