<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-Inflation     07-31 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Inflation,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Consumer Prices Rose Moderately In June From May</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices in the European Economic
Community rose 0.3 percentage point in June over the previous
month, the EEC reported Monday.
   The EEC's statistical agency Eurostat said prices were up 5.4
percent in June from a year earlier. In June 1988, the 12-month
increase was 3.4 percent.
   In comparison, inflation over the last year for the United
States and Japan was 5.2 percent and 3 percent respectively.
   The EEC warned that that despite the moderate price increase in
June, inflation rates were ``clearly higher than in 1988'' for the
12 member states excluding Denmark, Greece and the Netherlands.
   The Eurostat price index, which uses 1985 as a base of 100,
stood at a provisional 116.4 in June.
   EC inflation was highest in Greece, at 1.6 percent in June.
Prices rose 0.7 percentage point in Portugal; 0.5 percentage point
in Spain; 0.5 percentage point in Italy; 0.3 percentage point in
Britain; 0.3 percentage point in Luxembourg; 0.2 percentage point
in Belgium; 0.2 percentage point in West Germany and 0.1 percentage
point in France.
   Consumer prices fell by 0.3 percentage point in Denmark and 0.1
percentage point in the Netherlands during the month.
</TEXT>
