<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 0943EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-TaxEvasion     07-31 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Tax Evasion,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Amount of Taxes Evaded in Fiscal 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese government reported Monday that a
record $5.17 billion in income was not reported by independent
business owners in fiscal 1987.
   The National Tax Administration Agency said it investigated
168,926 people nationwide, including doctors, lawyers and other
independent business owners, and discovered that 95.8 percent of
them reported their incomes incorrectly, either by mistake or for
tax evasion.
   The undeclared earnings discovered by the agency were 13.7
percent larger than in fiscal 1986, the agency said. Fiscal 1987
ended on March 31, 1988.
   The agency said it levied a record $1.36 billion in penalty
fines, up 18.4 percent from 1986.
   Owners of pinball parlors topped the 1987 list of tax evaders
with an average $270,000 in unreported income, followed by hospital
owners, with an average $115,000 and real estate businesses with
$93,000, the agency said.
</TEXT>
