<SECOND>BC-Earns-Appliances,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whirlpool Reports Second-Quarter Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENTON HARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whirlpool Corp.'s second-quarter
earnings jumped nearly 22 percent because of sales gains
internationally and higher prices domestically, the leading U.S.
appliance maker reported Monday.
   Whirlpool reported earnings of $50.4 million, or 72 cents a
share, for the three months ended June 30, up from $41.4 million,
or 60 cents a share, in the second quarter of 1988.
   Revenue for the period totaled $1.64 billion vs. $1.15 billion.
   For the first six months of 1989, Whirlpool reported earnings of
$91.1 million, or $1.31 a share, on revenues of $3.21 billion, up
from $74.6 million, or $1.08 a share, on revenues of $2.22 billion.
   Whirlpool became the world's largest appliance company in
January when it purchased a 53 percent interest in the appliance
division of N.V. Philips of the Netherlands, forming Whirlpool
International.
   Chairman David R. Whitwam said the second quarter also brought a
strong performance by Whirlpool's Brazilian affiliates, which had
suffered losses in the first quarter attributed to unsettled
economic conditions.
</TEXT>
