<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Xerox     07-31 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Xerox,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Xerox 2nd Quarter Earnings Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Xerox Corp., the world's leading maker of
copy machines, reported a 7 percent gain in second-quarter earnings
Monday, attributing the improvement to a restructuring plan.
   Earnings totaled $179 million or $1.67 per share for the
April-June quarter, vs. $167 million or $1.59 a share a year
earlier. Revenues totaled $4.4 billion vs. $4.1 billion, an 8
percent gain.
   ``These results indicate we are on track toward achieving our
goals fo 1989,'' Chairman David T. Kearns said. ``Improved
financial returns from business products and systems in this year's
second half and in the years beyond will result from the
restructuring program we announced in January, plus our continuing
emphasis on customer satisfaction and tight cost controls.''
   For the first six months, the company earned $337 million, or
$3.15 a share, compared with $319 million, or $2.96 a share, in the
same period a year ago.
   Revenues were up 8 percent in the first half to $8.5 billion
compared witho $7.9 billion in the first six months of 1988.
   Under the restructuring plan, Xerox will eliminate 2,000 jobs by
the end of the year.
</TEXT>
