<DOCNO> AP890731-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1130EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BancTexas     07-31 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-BancTexas,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>BancTexas Seeks Another Federal Bailout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two years after becoming the first major Texas
bank to be recapitalized with federal assistance, BancTexas Group
Inc. is seeking another government bailout.
   The request made Friday comes one week after the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. seized Texas American Bancshares Inc. and National
Bancorp. of Texas Inc., awarding them to new owners. The FDIC said
at the time the move took care of major bank restructuring in Texas.
   BancTexas Group last week reported an $8.8 million loss in the
second quarter, compared to an $11.12 million loss in the same
period last year. So far this year, the bank has lost $14.78
million, compared to $17.02 million last year.
   The losses dropped the holding company's primary capital ratio
on June 30 to 5.3 percent, with BancTexas-Dallas at 2.3 percent,
well below the required 5.5 percent. The Dallas bank accounts for
about half of the company's $776.29 million in assets.
   Other subsidiary banks are BancTexas-Houston, with a capital
ratio of 5.9 percent, and BancTexas-McKinney, at 4.9 percent.
   ``This application contemplates that, in conjunction with FDIC
financial assistance, BancTexas Group and outside investors would
make a substantial capital infusion into BancTexas-Dallas,'' the
company said.
   ``If assistance is granted by the FDIC to BancTexas-Dallas,
BancTexas Group should be able to assist the other two banks in
meeting the new ... capital requirements.''
   Chairman Nathan C. Collins said, ``while it is not possible at
this time to predict the exact effect on the stockholders of
BancTexas Group, it is probable that, if the assistance is granted,
their interest will be substantially diluted as a result of the new
capital injection.''
   BancTexas was recapitalized in 1987 with $150 million in federal
assistance, plus $50 million from the Hallwood Group Inc., a
Cleveland-based investment firm.
   At the time, that seemed as if it would be enough, but
continuing deterioration of the state's real estate market
undermined the bank's recovery, bank spokesman Jim Miller said.
   The bank said it had $64.12 million in non-performing assets on
June 30, with $24.75 million allowance for loan losses. The company
charged $10 million worth of bad loans during the quarter.
   About a third of the bank's portfolio is in real estate, Miller
said.
   BancTexas has been sounding warning signals for about nine
months, Miller said. Earlier, the bank has acknowledged talking to
outside groups in search of additional capital.
   The bank, however, has declined to comment on reports other
banks were reviewing its books. The Dallas Morning News has
reported Hibernia Corp., a Louisiana holding company, was invited
to study the bank's books.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
