<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-31 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weekend Rain Sends Crop Futures Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The soybean and corn markets led grain futures
prices lower in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
reflecting unexpectedly heavy rainfall in the Midwest over the
weekend.
   Soybean futures fell as much as 14\ cents a bushel and corn lost
up to 6} cents a bushel before scattered buying lifted the markets
off their opening lows.
   Many areas of the Corn Belt received one-half inch to two inches
of rain during the weekend, with particularly heavy amounts
reported in southern Minnesota, northern Iowa, northern Illinois
and parts of Missouri.
   Drier weather is expected in the corn-and-soybean region this
week, but some forecasters are calling for more rain before the
weekend.
   On Friday, the National Weather Service issued 30- and 90-day
forecasts that suggested above-average rainfall for the Mississippi
Delta region _ where rain is not needed _ and for the Corn Belt
during the fall harvest period.
   But analysts were skeptical.
   ``The 90-day forecast indicated possible harvest delays, but you
can't really hang your hat on that,'' said Steve Freed, a
grain-market analyst in Chicago with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   In early trading, wheat futures were 1\ cents to 2{ cents lower
with the contract for delivery in September at $3.86{ a bushel;
corn was 3 cents to 5{ cents lower with September at $2.24{ a
bushel; oats were 4{ cents to 5 cents lower with September at
$1.31{ a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents to 13 cents lower with
August at $6.36 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mixed
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .35 cent higher with August
at 72.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .23 cent to .50 cent
higher with August at 83.45 cents a pound; hogs were .13 cent lower
to .15 cent higher with August at 45.92 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .37 cent lower to .35 cent higher with August at 25.62
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Friday.
</TEXT>
