<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1405EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-DockStrike     07-31 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Dock Strike,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Laborers Return to Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-week national dockworkers strike foundered
Monday as more laborers returned to their jobs after employers
threatened to fire those who didn't resume work.
   But 480 dockers at Bristol went against the national trend when
they voted at a private meeting to continue to stay out over
government plans to abolish guaranteed lifelong employment.
   Port employers said the returns on Monday meant that 3,668, or
57 percent, of dockers affected by the job guarantee program were
working and 2,741 remained on strike. Forty of the 60 ports
affected by the strike were working normally, they said.
   ``Clearly more than 50 percent of dockers are back at work. They
have voted with their feet and I hope the Transport and General
Workers' Union will heed their wishes and call off this strike,''
said Nick Finney, director of the National Association of Port
Employers.
   But opposition Labor Party lawmaker Michael Meacher said Sunday
on British Broadcasting Corp. radio: ``The reason is not lack of
support for the cause, but the intimidation and blackmail involved
in threats of sackings.''
   The swing away from the strike came after dockers' leaders voted
decisively on Friday to intensify the dispute and try to get
working dockers to rejoin the strike.
   John Connolly, the union's national docks secretary, said Sunday
the votes to return to work were ``disappointing but not totally
unexpected.''
   They would not affect the union's decision to step up the
dispute, he said, adding: ``We will continue to try to persuade
those members who have returned to change their minds.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
