<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1445EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Autos Bjt   07-31 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Autos, Bjt,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Second-Quarter Earnings Up 6.6 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. said Monday that sales of minivans
and Jeeps pushed second-quarter profits 6.6 percent higher than a
year earlier, when incentive costs hurt earnings.
   Chairman Lee A. Iacocca said deep cost cuts, including
eliminating 2,300 white-collar jobs by the end of the year, should
help Chrysler meet stiffening competition in the automotive market
later this year.
   Chrysler said it earned $341 million, or $1.46 a share, for the
three months ended June 30, compared with $320 million, or $1.45 a
share, in the same 1988 period.
   Revenue for the quarter totaled $10.1 billion, up from $9.34
billion a year ago, the country's third-largest automaker said.
   The increases contrasted with last week's reports of a 3.4
percent quarterly decline in earnings at GM and a 15.4 percent drop
at Ford. But Chrysler was comparing with a weak second quarter in
1988.
   ``They had very poor profit last year. They were pushing heavily
on incentives, and their mix of models was weak,'' said automotive
analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   For the first six months of the year, Chrysler reported earnings
of $692 million, or $2.96 a share, on revenue of $20.1 billion.
That was up from $504 million, or $2.27 a share, on revenue of
$17.9 billion in the first half of 1988.
   Chrysler said incentive costs are still rising, by 20 percent
over the year-earlier period.
   This year, Chrysler said Jeep sales were up 19 percent from last
year's second quarter and the company continued its dominance in
the sale of minivans, commanding 54 percent of sales.
   Iacocca said sales were helped by the Dodge Spirit and Plymouth
Acclaim models that replaced Chrysler's K-series compact cars, and
by more expensive models such as the Chrysler New Yorker Landau.
   The company increased rebates to help lagging sales of
lower-priced models such as the Plymouth Sundance, Dodge Shadow,
Plymouth Horizon and Dodge Omni.
   Iacocca predicted gains from last week's move to cut $1 billion
in costs by year end by deeply cutting Chrysler's white-collar work
force.
   ``We've got aggressive internal cost-control measures in place,
and we plan to continue strong emphasis on cost reductions as a
means of enhancing our competitive position,'' he said. ``These
moves will help us face head on the most competitive automotive
market the world has ever seen.''
   Healy said the cost cuts may not help soon, however. ``I don't
think they'll have much effect on 1989 profits. I think they can
bring the savings on stream during the course of 1990,'' he said.
   GM reported second-quarter earnings of $1.45 billion and Ford
said it earned $1.4 billion.
   Chrysler's earnings brought Big Three profits to $3.20 billion
for the quarter, down from last year's second-quarter total of
$3.49 billion and record first-quarter 1989 profits of $3.54
billion for the three.
   Each of the Big Three has spent hundreds of dollars per vehicle
on incentives during the second quarter to try to boost sales and
shrink inventories in a sluggish car and truck market.
   Chrysler said last week it was spending about $700 per car. Ford
said it spent $600 to $700 per car on incentives during the second
quarter. GM declined to say what it spent but said it exceeded
1988's spending of about $700 per car.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
