<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Drop Sharply on Weekend Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices closed strongly
lower Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade following a weekend of
unexpectedly heavy rain in some of the driest parts of the Midwest.
   ``Rain makes grain,'' said Jerry Gidel, research director for
the futures brokerage LIT American Inc.
   Soybeans for near-month delivery fell to a new 16-month low
around $6.25 a bushel under steady selling pressure.
   Heavy precipitation was reported during the weekend in Missouri,
northern Iowa, southern Minnesota and northern Illinois, with
amounts ranging from { inch to 2 inches.
   Drier, warmer weather was expected for most of this week but
private forecasters predicted more showers in the Corn Belt by this
weekend.
   Long-range forecasts hold a threat of a rain-hampered harvest
this fall, ``but you can't really hang your hat on that,'' said
Steve Freed, a grain-market analyst in Chicago.
   At the close, wheat was 3{ cents to 4{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.84\ a bushel; corn was 2\
cents to 5} cents lower with September at $2.23\ a bushel; oats
were 4 cents to 6 cents lower with September at $1.31 a bushel;
soybeans were 4 cents to 23{ cents lower with August at $6.25{ a
bushel.
