<DOCNO> AP890731-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1529EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-S&amp;Ls-Capital     07-31 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Capital,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Most Thrifts Meet Tougher Capital Requirements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 75 percent of the nation's thrifts already
meet tougher capital standards proposed in the government's
multibillion-dollar bailout bill, according to a study released
Monday.
   The study by Alex Sheshunoff &amp; Co., an Austin-based consulting
firm, said the findings show that ``clearly, this requirement isn't
an unbearable burden for the healthy segment of the savings and
loan industry.''
   Congress is scheduled this week to consider a $157 billion
bailout bill for the industry, which is losing an estimated $20
million a day. Among other components, the bill requires thrifts to
have a 3 percent capital-to-assets ratio.
   The bill allows half of the capital initially to be in so-called
goodwill, or intangible, assets. By Jan. 1, 1995, the entire 3
percent must be in tangible assets.
   The bill has been approved by a House-Senate conference
committee, but Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, has threatened to block
passage in a dispute over financing.
   Sheshunoff said his review of the financial status of the
nation's 2,946 thrifts found 73 percent, or 2,163, already meet the
3 percent core capital requirement contained in the Bush
administration's bailout bill.
   In addition, Sheshunoff said 1,984 of the thrifts, or 67
percent, can meet the 1995 requirement with tangible assets only.
   Whie 25 of the nation's 40 largest thrifts _ including 12 of the
top 13 _ already meet the 1995 standard, the number drops to 12 _
including eight of the top 13 _ if only tangible assets are counted.
   Sheshunoff said that of the 1,984 well-capitalized S&amp;Ls, the
average tangible capital-to-assets ratio is 6 percent, which ``puts
them in a strong position to acquire undercapitalized thrifts.''
   ``The difference between the higher interest rates paid by S&amp;Ls
for deposits and those paid by banks should narrow,'' Sheshunoff
said of the bailout bill. ``As a result, borrowers, particularly
homebuyers, may see a decline in interest costs on mortgages.''
   Of the 2,163 thrifts with more than 3 percent capital,
Sheshunoff said 1,886, or 87.2 percent, were profitable. Of the 783
that don't meet the 3 percent standard, 277, or 35.4 percent, were
profitable.
   Sheshunoff based his study on data in the March 31, 1989, Thrift
Financial Reports of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890731-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 2012EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-McDonnellDouglas     07-31 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McDonnell Douglas,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>To Sell Two Information Systems Businesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. said Monday it will
sell two of its information systems businesses and convert its
Systems International unit into a public company headquartered in
the United Kingdom.
   The company said it has reached a preliminary agreement to sell
Network Systems, which includes the Tymnet public data network, to
British Telecom for $355 million. The sale is conditional on
regulatory clearances.
   McDonnell Douglas also said it intended to sell its North
American field service business later this year.
   McDonnell Douglas announced in June it had reached an agreement
to sell its Telecheck business. The annual revenues of the three
units are about $400 million, the company said. The proceeds are to
be used to reduce debt and raise money for the aerospace businesses.
   The company said Jeremy Causley, the current president of
McDonnell Douglas Intormation Systems Co., will become chief
executive of the British venture and will make arrangements to
partly divest it.
   The present McDonnell Douglas computer systems business in the
United States will become part of the international company, a
spokesman said.
   The company said it considered the announced changes to be the
last step in narrowing its information systems business. For the
first six months of 1989, McDonnell Douglas Information Systems
posted revenues of $559 million and reported earnings of $9 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
