<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 2018EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Coors-Stroh     07-31 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coors-Stroh,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coors Discussing Purchase of Part of Stroh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adolph Coors Co., the nation's No. 4
brewing company, is holding discussions with the Stroh Brewing Co.,
the No. 3 beer-maker, that could lead to Coors becoming a minority
partner, company officials said Monday.
   Details of the discussions were unavailable. Coors vice
president of development Robert Klugman said the talks were
preliminary.
   ``Because we have no agreements, we are not able to comment
further,'' said Anita Russell, a spokeswoman for the Golden-based
brewery.
   Jack Barthwell, vice president of corporate communications and
government affairs for the Detroit-based Stroh, said in a statement
that the discussions are part of an effort launched by Stroh in
February to explore partnership opportunities.
   Stroh in February hired Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. ``to find someone
to buy a minority position in the company,'' Barthwell said in a
telephone interview.
   He said the talks with Coors are part of that process, which has
involved discussions with other international brewers as well.
   ``Although we will confirm that discussions have occurred with
representatives from Coors, it should be clearly understood that
nothing discussed with Coors would cause Stroh to alter its
schedule of meetings with other brewers,'' Barthwell said in his
statement.
   ``As previously stated, Stroh will continue exploring numerous
alternatives to profitably restructure and strengthen its business,
regardless of rumors and speculation,'' his statement said.
   Stroh is privately owned and does not release production or
earnings figures. Besides making Stroh beer products, the brewery
also produces Old Milwaukee, Schlitz and Schaefer beer.
   Coors in April announced a first-quarter loss of $4.8 million,
compared with a $3.7 million profit, or 10 cents per share, during
the same period of 1988. It was Coors' first loss in its 15 years
as a public company. The company blamed a drop in beer shipments
and higher manufacturing costs for the loss.
   During this year's first quarter, Coors' net sales were up 12.9
percent, to $324 million. Beer shipments during the period totaled
3 million barrels, down 5.5 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
