<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1720EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-31 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise on Storm Worries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices rose Monday amid concern
that a storm in the Gulf of Mexico could disrupt oil production off
the Louisana and Texas coasts.
   Speculation that crude oil shipments from the Mideast might be
interrupted depending on how the United States retaliates for the
reported hanging of Lt. Col. William R. Higgins also drove up oil
prices.
   The contract for September delivery of West Texas Intermediate,
the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, rose 38 cents to $18.31 per
42-gallon barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Contracts for
delivery in months further in the future posted similar gains.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the
August contract of unleaded gasoline increased 0.53 cent to 53.48
cents a gallon. It was the last trading day for the August unleaded
gas contract. The September contract, which becomes the near-month
contract on Tuesday, spurted 1.15 cents to 52.70 cents a gallon.
   The August delivery No.2 heating oil contract settled 0.44 cent
higher at 48.67 cents a gallon. It also was the last trading day
for the August heating oil contract. September heating oil
increased 0.49 cent to 49.31 cents a gallon.
   Linda Simard, an energy broker at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
said reports that some oil companies were suspending operations and
evacuating employees from certain installations in the Gulf of
Mexico due to a storm motivated buying in the energy futures pits.
   ``The main thing today was the tropical storm on the Gulf
Coast,'' said Simard. ``People are taking precautions.''
   Tropical storm Chantal, expected to be upgraded to a hurricane,
was reported to be threatening the Louisiana and Texas coasts.
   Although it was unknown how the Bush administration would
respond to the reported hanging of Higgins, energy brokers bought
on the possibility that oil shipments from the Middle East might be
disrupted, Simard said.
   Pro-Iranian captors of Higgins said they hanged him in
retaliation for Israel's abduction of a Moslem cleric. President
Bush cut short a two-day trip and returned to Washington to deal
with the matter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890731-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1752EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru   07-31 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Lower; Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 16th graf, On the ..., to include Republic National Bank
gold quote.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lower U.S. interest rates sapped strength Monday
from the dollar, which fell to springtime levels against major
foreign currencies.
   The drop in interest rates has wiped out the dollar rally that
reached its peak in June, taking the dollar back to levels of May
against the British pound and Japanese yen, April against the West
German mark and March against the Swiss franc.
   The dollar's sharpest drop came against the yen, which has
surged ahead following the brief decline that occurred in the July
political upheaval. Traders said there was optimism that Japan's
governing partner would select a new prime minister shortly.
   Most of the dollar's decline came in Europe. Trading in the
United States was thin and choppy, with most interbank trading
ending by noon because of end-of-the-month squaring of the books.
   The Federal Reserve has been lowering interest rates to
encourage borrowing and stimulate the sluggish U.S. economy. As a
side effect, the lower rates make dollar-denominated securities
less attractive to global investors.
   The dollar did not seem to gain from the crisis atmosphere
surrounding claims by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems in Lebanon that
they executed an American military officer. Often the dollar is
seen as a safe haven in times of international trouble.
   ``People are still concerned with interest rates coming off,''
said Michael Miskulin, a trader at Industrial Bank of Japan Trust
Co. in New York. As for the Lebanon situation, ``I think people are
used to that sort of situation now,'' he said.
   The yen's climb began in Asia Monday, triggered by a large order
to sell marks for yen in Singapore.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before European markets
open, the dollar fell 1.05 yen to close at 138.40 Japanese yen.
Later, in London, the dollar fell to 136.95 yen. In New York the
dollar closed at 137 yen, down from 139.20 on Friday.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6665 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.6455 late Friday.
In New York the pound rose to $1.6655 from $1.6527 on Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8650 West German marks, down from 1.8815; 1.6080
Swiss francs, down from 1.6175; 1.1811 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1826; 6.3135 French francs, down from 6.3715; and 1,341 Italian
lire, down from 1,356.9.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8655 West German marks, down from 1.8845; 1.6065
Swiss francs, down from 1.6180; 6.3155 French francs, down from
6.3825; 2.1030 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1240; 1,340.03 Italian
lire, down from 1,354.00; and 1.1809 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1838.
   Gold price movements were mixed.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose 86 cents a troy ounce to close at
$369.64.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $368.25 a troy ounce,
compared with $369.20 bid late Friday. In Zurich, gold fell to
close at a bid $368.25 compared with $369.75 bid late Friday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $370.50 an ounce from $367 Friday. Later Republic
National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $370.40 as of 4 p.m.
EDT, up from $467 on Friday.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market, where silver
was trading at a late bid price of $5.13 a troy ounce, compared
with Friday's $5.14. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery rose to $5.269 an ounce from $5.137.
</TEXT>
