<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1814EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-31 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Fall Below 80 Cents A Pound, New 13-Year Low</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices tumbled below 80 cents a pound to a
13{-year low on Monday as the market continued its month-long
search for support following the collapse of a price-stabilization
agreement.
   On other markets, precious metals and crude oil futures rallied;
grain and soybean futures fell sharply; and livestock and meat
futures were mixed.
   Green, unroasted coffee settled 1.75 cents to 3.03 cents lower
on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange with the contract for
delivery in September at 78.99 cents a pound, the lowest settlement
for a near-month contract since early 1976.
   The price plunge followed a weekend meeting of Latin American
foreign ministers in Colombia, where the coffee market was
discussed.
   No action was taken but Brazil and Colombia, respectively the
world's first- and second-largest coffee producers, issued a
statement after the meeting saying they supported higher prices.
   ``The market essentially shrugged its shoulders and said `So
what,''' said Arthur Stevenson, a New York-based coffee market
analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   ``Obviously in the deregulated market, no producer wants to see
lower prices,'' he said.
   Coffee futures were trading near $1.14 a pound at the beginning
of July and have fallen steadily following the International Coffee
Organization's suspension of export quotas on July 3. The quotas
were designed to stabilize prices by limiting the amount of green
coffee that producer countries could sell to consumer countries
within the 74-nation organization.
   The quota suspension triggered a battle among coffee producers,
who have been aggressively cutting their prices in hopes of raising
their sales and their market share.
   But coffee roasters in consumer countries have been ``very
lackadaisical'' in their buying, ``because they anticipate the
abundance of coffee supplies to drive prices even lower,'' said
analyst Sandra Kaul of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Roaster demand is typically slack in the summer because coffee
consumption goes down in the warm months.
   Silver futures prices rebounded strongly on New York's Commodity
Exchange, regaining all the ground lost in Friday's sell-off.
   Peter Cardillo of Josephthal &amp; Co. in New York said a weaker
dollar, lower interest rates and concerns about Middle Eastern
stability helped support the market, which initially rose on
technical factors.
   Silver settled 12 cents to 13.2 cents higher with September at
$5.313 a troy ounce; gold was $3.30 to $3.50 higher with August at
$370.50 a troy ounce.
   Crude oil futures advanced on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
ending a six-day slide, amid jitters about the threat to Gulf Coast
drilling platforms from a tropical storm.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents to 38 cents
higher with September at $18.31 a barrel; heating oil was .28 cent
to .49 cent higher with August at 48.67 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .53 cent to 1.15 cents higher with August at 53.48
cents a gallon.
   On the Chicago Board of Trade, soybeans for near-month delivery
plunged to a 16{-month low and corn dropped to its lowest price in
14 months following a weekend of unexpectedly heavy rain in some of
the driest parts of the Midwest.
   Drier, warmer weather was expected for most of this week but
private forecasters predicted more showers in the Corn Belt by the
weekend.
   Soybeans settled 1{ cents to 24{ cents lower with August at
$6.24{ a bushel, the lowest near-month settlement since March 18,
1988; corn settled 2{ cents to 6{ cents lower with September at
$2.22{ a bushel, the lowest near-month corn settlement since June
1, 1988; wheat was 2 cents to 4} cents lower with September at
$3.84{ a bushel; oats were 5{ cents to 6{ cents lower with
September at $1.30{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures finished moderately higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, with feeder cattle leading the way on
speculation that lower corn prices will allow feedlot operators to
budget more for cattle purchases. Pork futures ended mostly lower
on weak pork demand and sluggish cash markets.
   Live cattle settled .03 cent to .33 cent higher with August at
72.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent to .62 cent higher
with August at 83.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent lower
to .10 cent higher with August at 45.97 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were unchanged to .63 cent lower with August at 25.07 cents
a pound.
</TEXT>
