<FIRST>u f AM-LIN-McCaw     07-31 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LIN-McCaw,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>LIN Deadline on McCaw Deal Passes without Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock price of LIN Broadcasting Corp.
slipped Monday after the company's deadline for a negotiated buyout
agreement with McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. passed without an
agreement.
   LIN, a New York-based cellular telephone, television
broadcasting and publishing concern, said its board would pursue
other options.
   McCaw, the nation's largest cellular telephone operator, has an
outstanding hostile tender offer of $110 a share for the 90.2
percent of LIN's stock that it doesn't already own. LIN says the
offer is inadequate.
   In national over-the-counter trading Monday, LIN fell 62{ cents
a share to $109 while McCaw lost $1 a share to close at $37.
   The two companies disclosed in mid-July that they were talking
about a possible buyout at $127.50 a share. But McCaw, which is
based in Kirkland, Wash., said July 21 it had suspended those talks
pending further review.
   Subsequently, LIN set a 9 a.m. EDT Monday deadline for reaching
a definitive agreement under which McCaw would acquire LIN stock
for $127.50 a share, an offer that would value LIN's 53.9 million
shares at nearly $6.9 billion.
   ``LIN has given McCaw every reasonable opportunity to enter into
a merger agreement at the agreed price of $127.50,'' said LIN
Chairman Donald Pels.
   But McCaw called the deadline arbitrary and is continuing to
review the situation, McCaw spokesman Steve Bruce said Monday. In
the meantime, McCaw still feels its $110 a share offer, which
expires Aug. 11, is fair, he said.
   Pels said the $110 per share offer is inadequate and ``clearly
not in the best interests of LIN stockholders.''
   ``LIN's board of directors intends to pursue other options in
order to protect and enhance stockholder values,'' he said.
   Previously, LIN has proposed spinning off its seven television
stations as a company separate from its cellular telephone and
specialty publishing operations, which creates hardcover magazines
for placement in hotel rooms.
   The company has also previously indicated that it was in talks
with a third party that it declined to identify.
</TEXT>
