<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 2115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BuildingContracts     07-31 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Building Contracts,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction Contracts Down 2 Percent in June</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracting for new construction nationwide
slipped 2 percent in June, its second monthly decline, led by a
drop in public works and utilities projects, according to a survey
released Monday.
   The survey, by the F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill Information
Services Co., found that overall construction in June declined 2
percent to an annual rate of $249.7 million. That followed a 5
percent decline in May.
   Public works and utilities construction fell 5 percent in June
to an annual rate of $43.6 billion. June contracts for new
non-residential buildings, mainly commercial, industrial and
institutional structures, declined 3 percent to $89.9 billion.
   ``The overdeveloped commercial building market is the Achilles'
heel of the construction industry,'' said George A. Christie, the
group's vice president and chief economist.
   Despite recent weakening, total new construction in the second
quarter was slightly above that in the first quarter due to April's
high rate of contracting, F.W. Dodge said.
   ``We've been seeing more than the usual volatility in
contracting during the first half of 1989, but on balance, there's
been surprisingly little slowdown from the strong 1987-88 pace of
building,'' Christie said. ``The construction sector's prospects
for this year's second half are good.''

</TEXT>
