<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Unocal     07-31 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Unocal,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unocal Earnings Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unocal Corp.'s second-quarter profit rose 88
percent, due largely to real estate sales, higher crude oil prices
and improved oil shale operations, the oil company said Monday.
   Net earnings were $120 million, or $1.02 per share, on revenue
of $3.08 billion. In the second quarter of 1988, Unocal earned $64
million, or 55 cents per share, on revenue of $2.57 billion.
   The higher real estate earnings were due to $27 million in
after-tax gains from the sale of properties in Torrance, Calif.,
and San Diego County, said Richard J. Stegemeier, Unocal's chairman
and president.
   He said that a gain from the settlement of some pension
obligations also increased earnings.
   Partially offsetting the gains were higher foreign taxes and
increased domestic production expenses, Stegemeier said.
   For the first six months, Unocal earned $207 million, or $1.77
per share, compared with six-month 1988 earnings of $242 million,
or $2.08 per share. Last year's results included a $134 million net
gain from the combined effects of a change in accounting principle
for income taxes, which resulted in a $456 million gain, offset by
$322 million in writedowns of some assets.
   Revenue for the first six months of this year totaled $5.7
billion, up from a restated $4.9 billion in the same period of 1988.
</TEXT>
