<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 2205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HSN-GTETrial     07-31 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HSN-GTE Trial,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>GTE Failed to Say Phone System Inadequate, Home Shopping Claims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GTE Corp. failed to tell Home Shopping
Network its telephone system couldn't handle an ever-growing number
of calls, costing the video retailer millions of dollars, an HSN
attorney told a jury Monday.
   Attorney Chester Kamin contended in his final arguments that GTE
knew in 1986 that the situation had become so bad that 2,500 calls
every five minutes were not making it into HSN's headquarters here.
   In a $1.5 billion fraud suit filed in Pinellas Circuit Court,
HSN claims it lost millions of calls and about $500 million in
potential sales because the the GTE equipment couldn't handle the
call volume in 1986 and early 1987.
   GTE Florida and its parent company, GTE Corp. of Stamford,
Conn., in turn, filed a slander suit against HSN, claiming the
losses were actually due to the electronic retailer's unbridled
growth and customer dissatisfaction.
   The trial, which has lasted six weeks, was to resume Tuesday
morning with final arguments from the attorney for GTE.
   Since presiding Judge Howard Rives has already instructed the
jury on laws pertaining to the case, it could go into deliberation
as soon as Tuesday afternoon.
   In a summation that lasted more than three hours, Kamin said GTE
is trying to muddle the case with its counterclaim. He described
GTE as a ``giant octupus'' that ``squirts ink so you can't see it.
   ``What you see in this courtroom is ink, ink, ink, to keep you
from seeing what's going on,'' Kamin said.
   Kamin accused GTE of greed in declining to give HSN early notice
of problems so steps could be taken to correct the situation. He
said GTE only ``wanted to keep the money made by the (telephone)
network.''
   Kamin said the crux of the problem was that GTE, which knew
early on of HSN's plans to expand, didn't put in enough lines to
handle HSN's calls. ``We lost calls and that's all there is to it.''
   In one year, HSN's cable audience soared from 9 million to 46.5
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
