<DOCNO> AP890731-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 2339EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-PrudhoeProduction     07-31 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Prudhoe Production,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prudhoe Oil Production Decline To Be Felt This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Declining production at Prudhoe Bay
will mean a decrease of almost 10 percent in the next two years in
oil flow through the trans-Alaska pipeline, state and industry
officials say.
   Alyeska Pipeline Service Co., a consortium of the North Slope
oil producers, said Monday that some of the production slippage of
100,000 barrels a day this year is attributable to the spill by the
Exxon Valdez.
   ``The oil spill accounted for about 12 million barrels of lost
opportunity, reducing the average by 32,000 barrels a day,'' said
Alyeska spokesman Tom Brennan. ``But 60,000 barrels was due to
field production decline and producer maintenance.''
   The average daily flow through the pipeline is expected to drop
another 75,000 barrels next year.
   Prudhoe Bay accounts for three-quarters of the production on the
North Slope, which provides about one-fourth of the nation's
domestic oil supply.
   Brennan said the average daily flow in the pipeline is expected
to drop from 2 million barrels to 1.9 million this year and to 1.83
million in 1990.
   The Prudhoe Bay field, the largest in the United States, began
producing in 1977.
   Chuck Logsdon, the state's chief petroleum economist, said that
more than half of the estimated 10 billion barrels in the reservoir
have been drained. He said production is expected to drop 12
percent to 15 percent a year.
   Logsdon said none of the other producing fields on the North
Slope is large enough to compensate for the Prudhoe Bay falloff.
   The production decline will cost the state of Alaska $175
million in lost taxes and royalties over the next two years,
Logsdon says. The state gets about 85 percent of its revenue from
oil.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
