<FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 2349EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EngineOrder     07-31 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Engine Order,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Jet Engine Order Worth $900 Million To GE Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVENDALE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two European airlines have ordered $900
million worth of jet engines from CFM International, a joint
venture of General Electric Co. and SNECMA of France.
   Alitalia of Italy and Iberia International of Spain ordered
Airbus Industrie A321 aircraft powered by the CFM56-5B jet engine
produced by CFM International, the engine manufacturer announced
Monday.
   Alitalia placed 20 firm orders for the jets and has taken an
option for 20 more. Each A321 has two CFM56-5B engines, said Dwight
Weber, a spokesman for GE's jet engine plant in this Cincinnati
suburb.
   If Alitalia exercises all its options, its purchase could total
$600 million.
   Iberia placed eight firm orders for A321s worth $300 million for
CFM International. Iberia also announced that it has firmed seven
options taken previously on seven Airbus A320 aircraft, which are
powered by CFM International CFM56-5-A1 engines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
